ch. Rose\u2019s Rangers, as they were called, had to make its way through the strongly Patriot Hudson Valley to rendezvous with British regulars in New York City, however, and was captured in the vicinity of [[Schunemunk Mountain]] in [[Orange County, New York|Orange County]] after a skirmish with local [[militia]]. Prisoners were taken to [[Fort Montgomery (Hudson River)|Fort Montgomery]] and tried for treason against the recently established state of New York. Most were pardoned in exchange for committing to serve in the [[Continental Army]]; Rose and a few other holdouts were hanged.\n\nThe failure of Rose's mission and the burning of [[Kingston (city), New York|Kingston]] by British forces that year severely blunted Tory sentiment in the Catskills, and for the remainder of the war the region posed no threat to the Patriot cause.\n\n===Jewish resort destination===\n::''See [[Borscht Belt]]''\n\nThe Catskills became a major resort destination for Jewish New Yorkers in the mid-20th century. [[Borscht Belt]] is an informal term for the summer resorts of the Catskill Mountains in Sullivan and Ulster counties in upstate New York which were frequented by [[Ashkenazic Jews]]. Changes in vacationing patterns have led most of those travelers elsewhere, although there are still bungalow communities in the towns of [[Liberty (town), New York|Liberty]], [[Bethel, New York|Bethel]], [[Thompson, New York|Thompson]] and [[Fallsburg, New York|Fallsburg]] catering to [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] populations. The term, which derives from the name of a beet soup popular with people of Eastern European origin, can also refer to the Catskill region itself.\n\n===Woodstock rock festival===\n::''See [[Woodstock Festival]]''\n\nIn August, 1969, the Catskills were the site of a music and art festival in the town of [[Bethel, New York|Bethel]], which had originally been planned for [[Woodstock, New York]]. Thirty-three of the best-known musicians of the era appeared during a sometimes rainy weekend in front of nearly half a million concertgoers. The event, featuring liberal drug use and nudity, exemplified the [[counterculture]] of the 1960s and 1970s.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.catskillarchive.com The Catskill Archive \u2013 history of the Catskill Mtns.]\n*[http://www.brown.edu/Research/Catskills_Institute/ The Catskills Institute \u2013 the Catskills in American Jewish Life]\n*[http://www.hopefarm.com/sullivny.htm Early Sullivan County History]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080828221155/http://catskill-3500-club.org/about-us.htm Catskill 3500 Club History]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Catskill Mountains}}\n[[Category:Catskills]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Catskill_Mountains"}
{"title_page": "2006 Men's World Floorball Championships C-Division", "text_new": "{{about|the C-Division of the 2006 Men's World Floorball Championships|the A-Division|2006 Men's World Floorball Championships}}\n{{unreferenced|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox international floorball competition\n| tourney_name = 2006 Men's<br>World Floorball Championships\n| other_titles = C-Division\n| country = {{ESP}}\n| dates = May 3\u20137, 2006\n| num_teams = 6\n| venues =\n| cities = [[San Lorenzo de El Escorial]], Spain\n| winners = {{flb|POL}}\n| matches = 15\n| goals = 158\n| updated = 04:55, April 13, 2009 (UTC)\n}}\n\nThe '''2006 Men's World Floorball Championships C-Division''' took place over May 3\u20137, 2006 in [[San Lorenzo de El Escorial]], Spain.\n\nThe 2006 Men's World Floorball Championships were the second men's floorball championships that required a C-Division.\n\n==Championship results==\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=Q\n|show_positions=n\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=POL|name_POL={{flb|POL}}\n|team2=ESP|name_ESP={{flb|ESP}}\n|team3=SVK|name_SVK={{flb|SVK}}\n|team4=CAN|name_CAN={{flb|CAN}}\n|team5=FRA|name_FRA={{flb|FRA}}\n|team6=KOR|name_KOR={{flagicon|KOR}} [[Korea men's national floorball team|Korea]]\n|win_POL=4|draw_POL=0|loss_POL=1|gf_POL=48|ga_POL=14\n|win_ESP=4|draw_ESP=0|loss_ESP=1|gf_ESP=27|ga_ESP=16\n|win_SVK=4|draw_SVK=0|loss_SVK=1|gf_SVK=32|ga_SVK=11\n|win_CAN=2|draw_CAN=0|loss_CAN=3|gf_CAN=30|ga_CAN=24\n|win_FRA=1|draw_FRA=0|loss_FRA=4|gf_FRA=19|ga_FRA=23\n|win_KOR=0|draw_KOR=0|loss_KOR=5|gf_KOR=2|ga_KOR=70\n\n|col_A=#ccffcc|text_A=\n|result1=A\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:70%;\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n!width=35%| !!width=15%|\n!\n|-\n| May 3, 2006\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|[[Korea men's national floorball team|Korea]] {{flagicon|KOR}}||align=center|2\u201311||{{flb|ESP}}\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fl-rt|CAN}}||align=center|3\u20137||{{flb|POL}