ball.org/default.asp?sivu=5&alasivu=180&kieli=826 Standings & Statistics]\n\n{{s-start}}\n|-style=\"text-align: center; background: #ffa07a;\"\n|align=\"center\" colspan=\"3\"|'''[[Floorball World Championships|Men's World Floorball Championships C-Division]]'''\n{{succession box |\n  before = [[Legan\u00e9s]], Spain<br>[[2004 Men's World Floorball Championships C-Division|2004]] |\n  after = [[Bratislava]], Slovakia<br>[[2008 Men's World Floorball Championships C-Division|2008]] |\n  title = Host City<br>[[San Lorenzo de El Escorial|San Lorenzo]], Spain | years = [[:Category:2006 in floorball|2006]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{World Floorball Championships}}\n\n[[Category:Floorball World Championships|2006, C-Division]]\n[[Category:2006 in floorball|Mens World Floorball Championships C-division, 2006]]\n[[Category:2006 in Spanish sport]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions hosted by Spain]]\n", "name_user": "Frietjes", "label": "safe", "comment": "expand templates perFb team TfD outcomeandFb competition TfD outcomeandFb cl TfD outcomeandFb rbr TfD outcome", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2006_Men%27s_World_Floorball_Championships_C-Division"}
{"title_page": "Mary S. Lovell", "text_new": "'''Mary Sybilla Lovell''' is a British writer, daughter of William G. and Mary Catherine (n\u00e9e Wooley) Shelton. She married Clifford C. Lovell on 22 October 1960. They divorced in 1974. She married Geoffrey A. H. Watts on 11 July 1992. She has one child: Graeme R. Lovell.\n\nShe was an accountant and company director until she began writing in 1980 following a serious riding accident which left her temporarily disabled.\n\nShe has written biographies of [[Beryl Markham]], [[Amelia Earhart]], [[Jane Digby]], [[Richard Francis Burton]], [[Amy Elizabeth Thorpe]], the [[Mitford sisters|Mitford Girls]], [[Bess of Hardwick]] and [[The Churchills]]. Her book on Markham, ''Straight on Till Morning'', researched and written in under a year, after weeks of interviews with the subject in [[Nairobi]], became an immediate international bestseller when it was published in 1987 and was twelve weeks on the [[New York Times Best Seller list]].\n\nShe also wrote ''[[The Mitford Girls]]'' (titled ''The Sisters'' in the USA), a biography of the celebrated [[Mitford sisters]], first published in September 2001 (paperback August 2002), and her ''[[Bess of Hardwick]]'', was published in the UK in 2005. Four of her books have been optioned for films.\n\nUntil 2011 she often led reader groups interested in Jane Digby around Syria to follow in the footsteps of this favourite subject of hers.  She loves to travel to the [[Middle East]].\n\n''[[Amelia (film)|Amelia]]'', a major movie starring [[Richard Gere]] and [[Hilary Swank]], was based on her bestselling book ''[[The Sound of Wings - a biography of Amelia Earhart]]''. It was released in October 2009.\n\nHer last biography was ''The Churchills'',  a biography of the [[Churchill family]] from the [[1st Duke Marlborough]] to the present generation, was published in April 2011 in the UK and May 2011 in the U.S.A. The paperback was due for release in April/May 2012.\n\nShe lives in the [[New Forest]], Hampshire.\n\n==List of biographies by subject==\n\n*[[Beryl Markham]] - ''Straight on till Morning'' (1987)\n*Beryl Markham\u2019s African stories - ''The Splendid Outcast'' (1988)\n*[[Amelia Earhart]] - ''The Sound of Wings'' (1989 & 2009)\n*[[Amy Elizabeth Thorpe]] - ''Cast No Shadow; Women in WW II Espionage'' (1992)\n*[[Jane Digby]] - ''A Scandalous Life'' (1995)\n*[[Sir Richard Burton]] - ''A Rage to Live'' (1998)\n*[[Mitford sisters]] - ''The Mitford Girls \u2013 the extraordinary lives of the six Mitford sisters'' (2001)\n*[[Bess of Hardwick]] \u2013 ''Empire Builder and First Lady of Chatsworth'' (2005)\n*[[Winston Churchill]] - ''The Churchills: In Love and War'' (2011)\n*[[Maxine Elliott]] - ''The Riviera Set'' (2016)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lovellbiographies.com/ Mary S. Lovell's internet website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150924170903/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3415500100.html Lovell, Mary S(ybilla) 1941 in Contemporary Authors, New Revision Series] ([[Highbeam Research]])\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lovell, Mary Sybilla}}\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British biographers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{UK-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Mary Sybilla Lovell''' is a British writer, daughter of William G. and Mary Catherine (n\u00e9e Wooley) Shelton. She married Clifford C. Lovell on 22 October 1960. They divorced in 1974. She married Geoffrey A. H. Watts on 11 July 1992. She has one child: Graeme R. Lovell.\n\nShe was an accountant and company director until she began writing in 1980 following a serious riding accident which left her temporarily disabled.\n\nShe has written biographies of [[Beryl Markham]], [[Amelia Earhart]], [[Jane Digby]], [[Richard Francis Burton]], [[Amy Elizabeth Thorpe]], the [[Mitford sisters|Mitford Girls]], [[Bess of Hardwick]] and [[The Churchills]]. Her book on Markham, ''Straight on Till Morning'', researched and written in under a year, after weeks of interviews with the subject in [[Nairobi]], became an immediate international bestseller when it was published in 1987 and was twelve weeks on the [[New York Times Best Seller list]].\n\nShe also wrote ''[[The Mitford Girls]]'' (titled ''The Sisters'' in the USA), a biography of the celebrated [[Mitford sisters]], first published in September 2001 (paperback August 2002), and her ''[[Bess of Hardwick]]'', was published in the UK in 2005. Four of her books have been optioned for films.\n\nUntil 2011 she often led reader groups interested in Jane Digby around Syria to follow in the footsteps of this favourite subject of hers.  She loves to travel to the [[Middle East]].\n\n''[[Amelia (film)|Amelia]]'', a major movie starring [[Richard Gere]] and [[Hilary Swank]], was based on her bestselling book ''[[The Sound of Wings - a biography of Amelia Earhart]]''. It was released in October 2009.\n\nHer last biography was ''The Churchills'',  a biography of the [[Churchill family]] from the [[1st Duke Marlborough]] to the present generation, was published in April 2011 in the UK and May 2011 in the U.S.A. The paperback was due for release in April/May 2012.\n\nShe lives in the [[New Forest]], Hampshire.\n\n==List of biographies by subject==\n\n*[[Beryl Markham]] - ''Straight on till Morning'' (1987)\n*Beryl Markham\u2019s African stories - ''The Splendid Outcast'' (1988)\n*[[Amelia Earhart]] - ''The Sound of Wings'' (1989 & 2009)\n*[[Amy Elizabeth Thorpe]] - ''Cast No Shadow; Women in WW II Espionage'' (1992)\n*[[Jane Digby]] - ''A Scandalous Life'' (1995)\n*[[Sir Richard Burton]] - ''A Rage to Live'' (1998)\n*[[Mitford sisters]] - ''The Mitford Girls \u2013 the extraordinary lives of the six Mitford sisters'' (2001)\n*[[Bess of Hardwick]] \u2013 ''Empire Builder and First Lady of Chatsworth'' (2005)\n*[[Winston Churchill]] - ''The Churchills: In Love and War'' (2011)\n*[[Maxine Elliott]] - ''The Riviera Set'' (2016)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lovellbiographies.com/ Mary S. Lovell's internet website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150924170903/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3415500100.html Lovell, Mary S(ybilla) 1941 in Contemporary Authors, New Revision Series] ([[Highbeam Research]])\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lovell, Mary Sybilla}}\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British biographers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{UK-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_S._Lovell"}
{"title_page": "History of the Cleveland Browns", "text_new": "{{short description|Sports team history}}\n{{good article}}\n[[File:Cleveland Browns game program, September 1946.png|250px|thumb|right|Game program depicting the [[Brownie (folklore)|Brownie elf]], the team's primary mascot in its successful early years. From the Browns' first game on September 6, 1946 against the [[Miami Seahawks]].]]\n\nThe '''history of the Cleveland Browns''' [[American football]] team began in 1944  when taxi-cab magnate [[Arthur B. McBride|Arthur B. \"Mickey\" McBride]] secured a [[Cleveland, Ohio]] franchise in the newly formed [[All-America Football Conference]] (AAFC). [[Paul Brown]], who coach [[Bill Walsh (American football coach)|Bill Walsh]] once called the \"father of modern football\",{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=v}} was the team's namesake and first coach. From the beginning of play in 1946 at [[Cleveland Municipal Stadium]], the Browns were a great success. Cleveland won each of the AAFC's four championship games before the league dissolved in 1949. The team then moved to the more established [[National Football League]] (NFL), where it continued to dominate. Between 1950 and 1955, Cleveland reached the [[History of National Football League Championship|NFL championship game]] every year, winning three times.\n\nMcBride and his partners sold the team to a group of Cleveland businessmen in 1953 for a then-unheard-of $600,000. Eight years later, the team was sold again, this time to a group led by New York advertising executive [[Art Modell]]. Modell fired Brown before the 1963 season, but the team continued to win behind running back [[Jim Brown]]. The Browns won the [[1964 NFL Championship Game|championship]] in 1964 and reached the [[1965 NFL Championship Game|title game]] the following season, losing to the [[Green Bay Packers]]. The team subsequently reached the playoffs three times in the late 1980s, but fell short of playing in the [[Super Bowl]], the inter-league championship game between the NFL and the rival [[American Football League]] (AFL) that started in 1966.\n\nWhen the AFL and NFL [[AFL\u2013NFL merger|merged]] before the 1970 season, Cleveland became part of the new [[American Football Conference]] (AFC). While the Browns made it back to the playoffs in 1971 and 1972, they fell into mediocrity through the mid-1970s. A revival of sorts took place in 1979 and 1980, when quarterback [[Brian Sipe]] engineered a series of last-minute wins and the Browns came to be called the \"[[Kardiac Kids]]\". Under Sipe, however, the Browns did not make it past the first round of the playoffs. Quarterback [[Bernie Kosar]], who the Browns drafted in 1985, led the team to three [[AFC Championship game]]s in the late 1980s but lost each time. In 1995, Modell announced he was relocating the Browns to [[Baltimore]], sowing a mix of outrage and bitterness among Cleveland's dedicated fan base. Negotiations and legal battles led to an agreement where Modell was allowed to move the team, but Cleveland kept the Browns' name, colors and history. After three years of suspension while the old municipal stadium was demolished and [[Cleveland Browns Stadium]] took its place, the Browns started play again in 1999 under new owner [[Al Lerner]]. Since resuming operations, the Browns have made the playoffs only once, as a [[Wild card (sports)#National Football League|wild-card team]] in 2002.\n\nThe Browns are only one of 12 NFL franchises to predate the 1960 launch of the [[American Football League]], and are only one of three such teams in the AFC.\n\n==Founding and dominance in the AAFC (1946\u20131949)==\n\n[[File:Paul Brown, American football head coach.png|thumb|right|alt=Cleveland Browns coach Paul Brown stands on the sideline.|Paul Brown, the Browns' namesake and first coach, liked his players \"lean and hungry.\"{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=45}}]]\n\nIn 1944 [[Arch Ward]], the influential sports editor of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', proposed a new professional football league called the All-America Football Conference.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=7}} The AAFC was to challenge the dominant National Football League once it began operations at the end of World War II, which had forced many professional teams to curtail activity, merge or go on hiatus as their players served in the [[United States Armed Forces|U.S. military]].{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=8}} It was a bold proposition, given the failure of three previous NFL competitors and the dominance of college football, which was more popular than the professional game at the time.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=6\u20138}} Ward, who had gained fame and respect for starting all-star games for baseball and college football, lined up deep-pocketed owners for the new league's eight teams in hopes of giving it a better chance against the NFL.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=5\u20139}} One of them was Arthur B. \"Mickey\" McBride, a Cleveland businessman who grew up in Chicago and knew Ward from his involvement in the newspaper business.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=11\u201312}} McBride spent his early career as a circulation manager for the ''[[Cleveland News]]'', and went into business for himself in the 1930s, buying  a pair of Cleveland taxi companies and running a wire service that supplied [[Bookmaker|bookies]] with information about the results of horse races.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=11\u201312}} He had connections to [[organized crime in Chicago]] and Cleveland arising from the wire service.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=11\u201312}}{{sfn|Schwarz|2010|p=85}}\n\nMcBride developed a passion for football attending games at [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]], where his son went to college.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=11}} In the early 1940s he tried to buy the NFL's [[Cleveland Rams]], owned by millionaire supermarket heir [[Dan Reeves (NFL owner)|Dan Reeves]], but was rebuffed.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=11}} Having been awarded the Cleveland franchise in the AAFC, McBride asked ''[[Cleveland Plain Dealer]]'' sportswriter John Dietrich for head coaching suggestions.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=12}} Dietrich recommended Paul Brown, the 36-year-old [[Ohio State Buckeyes]] coach.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=12}} After consulting with Ward, McBride followed Dietrich's advice in early 1945, naming Brown head coach and giving him an ownership stake in the team and full control over player personnel.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=11\u201312}} Brown, who had built an impressive record as coach of a [[Massillon Washington High School|Massillon, Ohio high school]] team and brought the Buckeyes their first national championship, at the time was serving in the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] and coached the football team at [[Naval Station Great Lakes|Great Lakes Naval Station]] near [[Chicago]].{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=13\u201317}}\n\nThe name of the team was at first left up to Brown, who rejected calls for it to be christened the Browns.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=10}} McBride then held a contest to name the team in May 1945; \"Cleveland Panthers\" was the most popular choice, but Brown rejected it because it was the name of an [[Cleveland Panthers|earlier failed football team]]. \"That old Panthers team failed\", Brown said. \"I want no part of that name.\"{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=77}} In August, McBride gave in to popular demand and named the team the Browns, despite Paul Brown's objections.{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=76}}\n\nFor several years, Brown he would occasionally cite an alternate history of the team name. He claimed that the second name-the-team contest yielded the name \"Brown Bombers,\" after then-world heavyweight boxing champion [[Joe Louis]], whose nickname was \"The Brown Bomber.\" According to this version, Brown wanted his team to have a nickname befitting a champion, and felt the nickname \"Brown Bombers\" was apropos. The name was reportedly shortened to simply \"Browns.\" This alternate history of the name was even supported by the team as being factual as recently as the mid-1990s,<ref>{{cite book |title=The Name Game: Football, Baseball, Hockey & Basketball How Your Favorite Sports Teams Were Named |last=Donovan |first=Michael Leo |authorlink= |year=1997 |publisher=Warwick Publishing |location=[[Toronto]] |isbn=1-895629-74-8 |pages= }}</ref> and it continues as an [[urban legend]] to this day. However, Paul Brown never held fast to the Joe Louis story, and later in his life admitted that it was invented in part because of his wariness of having the team being named after him. The Browns and the NFL now both support the position that the team was indeed named after Paul Brown.<ref name=\"latimesblogs.latimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/sports_blog/2011/12/were-the-cleveland-browns-named-after-boxer-joe-louis.html|title=Sports news from Los Angeles and beyond|publisher=latimesblogs.latimes.com|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Franchise nicknames|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/news/franchise-nicknames/|publisher=[[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]|accessdate=April 8, 2016|quote=The Cleveland All-America Football Conference franchise conducted a fan contest in 1945 to name the team. The most popular submission was \"Browns\" in recognition of the team's first coach and general manager Paul Brown, who was already a popular figure in Ohio sports. Brown at first vetoed the choice and the team selected from the contest entries the name \"Panthers.\" However, after an area businessman informed the team that he owned the rights to the name Cleveland Panthers, from an earlier failed football team, Brown rescinded his objection and agreed to the use of his name.}}</ref>\n\nAs the war began to wind down with [[German Instrument of Surrender|Germany's surrender]] in May 1945, the team parlayed Brown's ties to college football and the military to build its roster.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=16\u201318}} The first signing was [[Otto Graham]], a former star quarterback at [[Northwestern University]] who was then serving in the Navy.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=19}} The Browns later signed kicker and offensive tackle [[Lou Groza]] and wide receivers [[Dante Lavelli]] and [[Mac Speedie]].{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=21\u201323}} Fullback [[Marion Motley]] and nose tackle [[Bill Willis]], two of the earliest [[African-American]]s to play professional football, also joined the team in 1946.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=29\u201330}} Cleveland's first training camp took place at [[Bowling Green State University|Bowling Green University]] in northwestern Ohio.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=28}} Brown's reputation for winning notwithstanding, joining the team was a risk; the Browns and the AAFC were nascent entities and faced tough competition from the NFL. \"I just went up there to see what would happen\", center [[Frank Gatski]] said many years later.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=28}}\n\nCleveland's first regular-season game took place September 6, 1946 at Cleveland Municipal Stadium against the [[Miami Seahawks]] before a then-record crowd of 60,135.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=45\u201346}} That contest, which the Browns won 44\u20130, kicked off an era of dominance. With Brown at the helm, the team won all four of the AAFC's championships from 1946 until its dissolution in 1949, amassing a record of 52 wins, four losses and three ties.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=123\u2013150}} This included the 1948 season, in which the Browns became the first unbeaten and untied team in professional football history.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=105\u2013186}} The Browns had few worthy rivals among the AAFC's eight teams, but the [[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]] and [[San Francisco 49ers]] were their closest competition.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2007|p=102}}\n\nWhile the Browns excelled on defense, Cleveland's winning ways were driven by an offense that employed Brown's version of the [[T formation]], which emphasized speed, timing and execution over set plays.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2007|p=102}} Brown liked his players \"lean and hungry\", and championed quickness over bulk.{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=45}} Graham became a star under Brown's system, leading all passers in each of the AAFC's seasons and racking up 10,085 passing yards.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2007|p=103}} Motley, who Brown in 1948 called \"the greatest fullback that ever lived\",<ref name=\"Brown says 1948 team best yet\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Harry|title=Brown Calls His First Unbeaten and Untied Team Since '40 His Best Yet|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 20, 1948|page=23|quote=[Brown said:] 'How that boy can run I think he's the greatest fullback that ever lived&nbsp;... Did you ever see a fullback who runs like a halfback in an open field?'}}</ref> was the AAFC's all-time leading rusher.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=149\u2013150}} Brown and six players from the Browns' AAFC years were later elected to the Pro Football Hall of Fame: Graham, Motley, Groza, Lavelli, Willis and Gatski.<ref name=\"Cleveland hall of fame members\">{{cite web|title=Franchises |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/teams.aspx |publisher=Pro Football Hall of Fame |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UNa2PFX?url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/teams.aspx |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 11, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Cleveland area showered support on the Browns from the outset.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=13\u201316}} Meanwhile, the Browns unexpectedly had Cleveland to themselves; the NFL's Cleveland Rams, who had continually lost money despite winning the [[1945 NFL Championship Game|1945 NFL championship]], moved to Los Angeles after that season.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=14}} The Browns' on-field feats only amplified their popularity, and the team saw average attendance of 57,000 per game in its first season.{{sfn|Neft|1994|p=194}} The Browns, however, became victims of their own success. Cleveland's dominance exposed a lack of balance among AAFC teams, which the league tried to correct by sending Browns players including quarterback [[Y. A. Tittle]] to the [[Baltimore Colts (1947\u20131950)|Baltimore Colts]] in 1948.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=108\u2013109}} Attendance at Browns games fell in later years as fans lost interest in lopsided victories, while attendance for less successful teams fell even more precipitously.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=137\u2013138}} The Browns led all of football during the undefeated season in 1948 with an average crowd of 45,517, but that was more than 10,000 less than the average per game the previous year.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=119}} These factors \u2013 combined with a war for players between the two leagues that raised salaries and ate into owners' profits \u2013 ultimately led to the dissolution of the AAFC and the merger of three of its teams, including the Browns, into the NFL in 1949.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=123\u2013150}} The NFL does not acknowledge AAFC statistics and records because these achievements \u2013 including the Browns' perfect season \u2013 did not take place in the NFL or against NFL teams, and not in a league fully absorbed by the NFL.<ref name=\"AAFC records unrecognized\">{{cite web|last=Grossi |first=Tony |title=1948 Cleveland Browns still lacking NFL respect |url=http://blog.cleveland.com/sports/2008/02/1948_cleveland_browns_still_la.html |publisher=cleveland.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UNk95vf?url=http://blog.cleveland.com/sports/2008/02/1948_cleveland_browns_still_la.html |archivedate=17 June 2012 |accessdate=May 11, 2012 |date=15 February 2008 |quote=NFL Vice President Joe Browne stated that going undefeated and untied was 'a sterling achievement,' but 'it was not achieved in the NFL nor against NFL teams, nor in a league which became in its entirety part of the NFL.' 'As such,' Browne wrote, 'our historians believe it is appropriate that it not be part of the official NFL records.' |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Success and challenges in the NFL (1950\u20131956)==\n\n[[File:Lou Groza and Arthur B. McBride after a game in 1950.jpg|thumb|right|Lou Groza and owner Mickey McBride after a December 1950 playoff game against the New York Giants. Groza's kicking played a major role in the team's first NFL championship.]]\n\nThe AAFC proposed match-ups with NFL teams numerous times during its four-year existence, but no inter-league game ever materialized.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=10\u201311}} That made Cleveland's entry into the NFL in the 1950 season the first test of whether its early supremacy could continue into a more established league.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=160\u2013165}} The proof came quickly: Cleveland's NFL regular-season opener was against the two-time defending champion [[Philadelphia Eagles]] on September 16 in Philadelphia.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=163}} The Browns lit up the Eagles' vaunted defense for 487 total yards\u2014including 246 passing yards from Graham and his receivers\u2014in a 35\u201310 win before a crowd of 71,237.  This decisive win quashed any doubts about the Browns' prowess.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=163\u2013166}} Behind an offense that featured Graham, Groza, Motley, Lavelli and running back [[Dub Jones (American football)|Dub Jones]], Cleveland finished the 1950 season with a 10\u20132 record, tied for first place in the Eastern Conference.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=151\u2013176}} After winning a playoff game against the [[New York Giants]], the Browns advanced to the [[1950 NFL Championship Game|NFL championship match]] against the [[History of the Los Angeles Rams|Los Angeles Rams]] in Cleveland. The Browns won 30\u201328 on a last-minute Groza field goal.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=176\u2013184}} Fans stormed the field after the victory, carting off the goalposts, ripping off one player's jersey and setting a bonfire in the bleachers.<ref name=\"Browns win 1950 championship\">{{cite news|last=Jones |first=Harry |title=Groza's Field Goal Is Signal for Celebration |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19501224BROWNS.html |accessdate=May 12, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UO6ayQb?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19501224BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 24, 1950 |quote=The moment Lou Groza's 16-yard field goal cleared the crossbar in the last 20 seconds of what may well be the greatest gridiron spectacle in Cleveland history, 29,751 citizens went berserk at the stadium. |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"It was the greatest game I ever saw\", Brown later said.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=182}}\n\n{{quote box\n |quote= Show me another guy who toes a<br>Football as neatly as Lou Groza\n |source=\u2013 [[Doggerel]] signed \"Hoosier Pick\", 1946.<br>Groza's nickname was \"The Toe.\"<ref name=\"Groza quote\">{{cite news|last=Doyle|first=James E.|title=The Sport Trail|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 2, 1946|page=25}}</ref>\n |align=left\n |border=2\n}}\n\nAfter five straight championship wins in the AAFC and NFL, the Browns appeared poised to bring another trophy home in 1951. The team finished the regular season with 11 wins and a single loss in the first game of the season.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=223\u2013230}} Cleveland faced the Rams on December 23 in a [[1951 NFL Championship Game|rematch]] of the previous year's title game.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=231}} The score was deadlocked 17\u201317 in the final period, but a 73-yard touchdown pass by Rams quarterback [[Norm van Brocklin]] to wide receiver [[Tom Fears]] broke the tie and gave Los Angeles the lead for good. The 24\u201317 loss was the Browns' first in a championship game.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=231\u2013235}}\n\nThe 1952 and 1953 seasons followed a similar pattern: Cleveland reached the championship game but lost both times to the [[Detroit Lions]].{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=237\u2013286}} In 1952's [[1952 NFL Championship Game|championship game]], Detroit won 17\u20137 after a [[muffed punt]] by the Browns, several Lions defensive stands and a 67-yard touchdown run by [[Doak Walker]] scuttled Cleveland's chances.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=237\u2013254}} The team finished 11\u20131 in 1953, but lost the [[1953 NFL Championship Game|championship]] to the Lions 17\u201316 on a 33-yard [[Bobby Layne]] touchdown pass to [[Jim Doran]] with just over two minutes left.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=263\u2013286}} While the championship losses disappointed Cleveland fans who had grown accustomed to winning, the team continued to make progress. [[Len Ford]], who the Browns picked up from the defunct AAFC's [[Los Angeles Dons]] team, emerged as a force on the defensive line, making the [[Pro Bowl]] each year between 1951 and 1953.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=153\u2013154}} Second-year wideout [[Ray Renfro]] became a star in 1953, also reaching the Pro Bowl.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=237\u2013272}}\n\n[[File:Dave Jones hands Arthur McBride a check, 1953.jpg|thumb|left|Dave Jones hands a check for $250,000 to Arthur B. \"Mickey\" McBride as a down payment on the purchase of the Browns for $600,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cleveland Memory|url=http://images.ulib.csuohio.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/press&CISOPTR=6931&CISOBOX=1&REC=1|publisher=Cleveland Memory Project|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UOPYWPY?url=http://images.ulib.csuohio.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=%2Fpress&CISOPTR=6931&CISOBOX=1&REC=1|archivedate=June 17, 2012|accessdate=June 11, 2012|quote=COOL QUARTER OF A MILLION dollars changed hands today when Dave Jones, new president of the Cleveland Browns, presented a $250,000 check to Arthur B. McBride to complete purchase of the team. Looking on are Homer Marshman (left), secretary and general counsel; Saul Silberman, chairman of the executive committee, and former vice president Edward McBride. Mickey also received a lifetime pass to all Brown home games 'in appreciation of his contribution to Cleveland professional football.' \u2013 photo verso|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\n\nDuring the summer before the 1953 season, the Browns' original owners sold the team for a then-unheard-of $600,000.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=264}} The buyers were a group of prominent Cleveland men: Dave R. Jones, a businessman and former [[Cleveland Indians]] director, [[Ellis Ryan]], a former Indians president, [[Homer Marshman]], an attorney, and Saul Silberman, owner of the Randall Park race track.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=264\u2013265}} McBride had been called in 1950 to testify before the [[United States Senate Special Committee to Investigate Crime in Interstate Commerce|Kefauver Committee]], a congressional body investigating organized crime, which partly exposed his ties to mafia figures but did not result in any charges.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=264}} While McBride never said so, the Kefauver hearings and the growing public association between him and the mafia may have played a role in his decision to get out of football.{{sfn|Schwarz|2010|p=85}}\n\nWhile the Browns came into 1954 as one of the top teams in the NFL, the future was far from certain. Graham, whose leadership and throwing skills were instrumental in the Browns' championship runs, said he planned to retire after the season.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=310}} Motley, the team's best rusher and blocker, retired at the beginning of the season with a bad knee.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=306}} Star [[defensive lineman]] Bill Willis also retired before the season.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=306}} Still, Cleveland finished the regular season 9\u20133{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=305\u2013326}} and met Detroit the day after Christmas in the [[1954 NFL Championship Game|championship game]] for a third consecutive time.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=317\u2013326}} This time Cleveland dominated on both sides of the ball, intercepting Bobby Layne six times while Graham threw three touchdowns and ran for three more.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=317\u2013326}} The Browns, who lost the last game of the regular season to the Lions only a week before, won their second NFL championship 56\u201310.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=317\u2013326}} \"I saw it, but still hardly can believe it\", Lions coach [[Buddy Parker]] said after the game. \"It has me dazed.\"<ref name=\"Browns win 1954 championship\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns Regain Title, 56 to 10 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19541226BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UOfTvFW?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19541226BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 12, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 26, 1954 |quote=Down and being counted out only seven days back, the Cleveland Browns unloaded years of pent-up frustration on the Detroit Lions yesterday at the stadium to take over as the new champions of the National Football League. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCleveland's success continued in 1955 after Brown convinced Graham to come back, arguing that the team lacked a solid alternative.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=332}} Cleveland finished the regular season 9\u20132\u20131 and went on to win its third [[1955 NFL Championship Game|NFL championship]], beating the Los Angeles Rams 38\u201314.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=338\u2013344}} It was Graham's last game; the win capped a 10-year run in which he led his team to the league championship every year, winning four in the AAFC and three in the NFL.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=342\u2013344}} Rams fans gave Graham a standing ovation when Brown pulled him from the game in the final minutes.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=342}}\n\nWithout Graham, the Browns floundered in 1956.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=366}} Injuries to two Browns quarterbacks left the relatively unknown [[Tommy O'Connell]] as the starter, and Cleveland finished with a 5\u20137 record, its first losing season.{{sfn|Peterson|1997|p=118}} Dante Lavelli and Frank Gatski retired at the end of the season, leaving Groza as the only original Browns player still on the team.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=366}} While the Browns' on-field play in 1956 was uninspiring, off-the-field drama developed after a Cleveland-based inventor let Brown test a helmet with a radio transmitter inside.{{sfn|Peterson|1997|p=118}} After trying it out in training camp, Brown used the helmet to call plays during the pre-season with long-time backup [[George Ratterman]] behind center. The device allowed the coach to direct his quarterback on the fly, giving him an advantage over franchises who had to use messenger players to relay instructions.{{sfn|Hollander|1983|p=60\u201363}} The Browns used the device off and on into the regular season, and other teams began to experiment with their own radio helmets.{{sfn|Felton|2007|pp=133\u2013134}} [[Bert Bell]], the [[NFL commissioner]], banned the device in October 1956.<ref name=\"Radio helmet banned\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|title=Silencer Put On Radio Helmets|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=October 19, 1956|page=33|quote=Ban of radio or any form of electronic equipment in the helmets of professional girders was announced in Philadelphia by Commissioner Bert Bell after a poll of the 12 teams in the league. 'All electronic devices, including walkie talkies, must be eliminated for the remainder of the season,' the directive from Bell stated.}}</ref> Today, however, all NFL teams use in-helmet radios to communicate with players.<ref name=\"Radio helmet use, current\">{{cite web|title=NFL installs new coach-to-defense communications system|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d809f61c6&template=with-video&confirm=true|publisher=National Football League|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UOkmc8n?url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d809f61c6&template=with-video&confirm=true|archivedate=June 17, 2012|accessdate=May 12, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Jim Brown era and new ownership (1957\u20131965)==\n\n[[File:Jim Brown running in the 1957 NFL championship.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Cleveland Browns rookie Jim Brown shakes off three tacklers and runs 29&nbsp;yards for a touchdown in the 1957 NFL championship game. Brown led the league in rushing in all but one season in his career.]]\n\nWith Otto Graham and most of the other original Browns in retirement, by 1957 the team was struggling to replenish its ranks.{{sfn|Heaton|2007|p=154}} In the first round of [[1957 NFL Draft|that year's draft]], Cleveland took fullback [[Jim Brown]] out of [[Syracuse University]].{{sfn|Freeman|2007|p=33\u201334}} In his first season, Brown led the NFL with 942&nbsp;yards of rushing and was voted rookie of the year in a United Press poll.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brown Named Top Rookie of the Year|newspaper=The Wilmington News|date=December 24, 1957|agency=United Press|quote=Jim Brown&nbsp;... today was named the National Football League's outstanding 1957 rookie in the annual United Press poll. Brown's 942 rushing yards gave him the league ball-carrying championship&nbsp;... [He] received 28 of the 32 votes cast by sports writers&nbsp;...}}</ref> Cleveland finished 9\u20132\u20131 and again advanced to the [[1957 NFL Championship Game|championship game]] against Detroit. The Lions dominated the game, forcing six turnovers and allowing only 112&nbsp;yards passing in a 59\u201314 rout.<ref name=\"1957 championship\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Lions Crush Browns, 59\u201314  Win Title With Five TD Aerials |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19571229BROWNS.html |accessdate=May 15, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 28, 1957 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UQej1fm?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19571229BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBefore the 1958 season, O'Connell, who lacked the stature and durability Paul Brown wanted in a starter, retired to take a coaching job in Illinois, and [[Milt Plum]] was named as his replacement.{{sfn|Miller|2007|p=76}}<ref name=\"O'Connell retires\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|title=Plum Moves Up As O'Connell Quits|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=January 22, 1958|page=25|quote=Retirement of Tommy O'Connell from the Cleveland Browns yesterday to take the position of backfield coach at Illinois puts the quarterbacking squarely on the broad shoulders of Milt Plum&nbsp;... The decision of the 27-year-old O'Connell probably was swayed by the fact that he ran into several injuries in his second season with the Browns. Although he finished as the league's leading passer&nbsp;... the chunky little fellow was out of the last two regular season games with a sprained ankle and what turned out to be a broken bone in his leg&nbsp;... Brown indicated that O'Connell's physical limitations prevented him from figuring too prominently in long range plans. O'Connell is 5&nbsp;feet, 10&nbsp;inches tall, weighs 190.}}</ref> Cleveland, however, was relying increasingly on the running game, in contrast to its pass-happy early years under Graham. As the team built up a 9\u20133 regular-season record, Brown in 1958 ran for 1,527&nbsp;yards \u2013 almost twice as much as any other back and a league record at the time.<ref name=\"1958 stats\">{{cite web|title=1958 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1958.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UWphVS1?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1958.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nEntering the final game of the 1958 season, Cleveland needed to either win or tie against the New York Giants to clinch the Eastern Conference title and the right to host the [[1958 NFL Championship Game|championship game]].<ref name=\"Browns prepare for Giants, 1958\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|title=Browns Set To Pass Against Giants|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 13, 1958|page=21|quote=If they lose to the Giants, there will be a playoff for the eastern division crown Dec. 21 at Yankee Stadium. If the Browns win there will be a weekend of rest before the championship game against the Baltimore Colts Dec. 28 at Cleveland Stadium.}}</ref> Cleveland lost that game under snowy conditions on a 49-yard field goal by [[Pat Summerall]] as time expired, and then lost a playoff game against the Giants the following week to end the season.<ref name=\"Giants beat Browns, 1958\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns lose to Giants, 13\u201310 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19581214BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UWzQl1D?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19581214BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 14, 1958 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Browns lose playoff 1958\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns Lose Playoff, 10\u20130 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19581221BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UX2pmtm?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19581221BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 21, 1958 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Giants went on to play the [[Baltimore Colts]] in the [[1958 NFL Championship Game|championship]], a game often cited as the seed of professional football's popularity surge in the U.S.{{sfn|Bowden|2008}}\n\nCleveland's campaigns in [[1959 Cleveland Browns season|1959]] and [[1960 Cleveland Browns season|1960]] were unremarkable, aside from Brown's league-leading rushing totals in both seasons.<ref name=\"Browns end 1959 season\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|title=Browns' 14 In 4th Nip Eagles, 28\u201321|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 14, 1959|page=35|quote=Jim Brown&nbsp;... for the third straight year the National League rushing champion with 1,329&nbsp;yards&nbsp;...}}</ref> Plum, meanwhile, became the established starting quarterback, bringing a measure of stability to the squad not seen since Graham's retirement. He led the team to a 7\u20135 record in 1959 and an 8\u20133\u20131 record in 1960, but neither was good enough to win the Eastern Conference and advance to the championship.<ref name=\"1959 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=1959 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1959.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UX6C046?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1959.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"1960 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=1960 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1960.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UX9lmYQ?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1960.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Behind the scenes, however, all was not well. A conflict took shape between Paul Brown and Jim Brown; emboldened by his success, the fullback began to question his coach's disciplinarian methods. He called the coach \"Little Caesar\" behind his back. At halftime during a game in 1959, Paul Brown questioned the severity of an injury Jim Brown was sidelined for, which further inflamed tensions between the two.{{sfn|Dyer|2007|p=114}}\n\n===Art Modell takes ownership===\n\n[[Fred \"Curly\" Morrison]], a former Browns running back who worked as an advertising executive for [[CBS]] television, learned in 1960 that Dave Jones was looking to sell the Browns and told the story to [[Art Modell]], a 35-year-old advertising and television executive from [[Brooklyn]].{{sfn|Coughlin|2011|p=212\u2013213}} Modell was intrigued, partly because of the potentially lucrative television rights that one of the NFL's most successful franchises could bring as football began to challenge baseball as America's biggest sport.{{sfn|Coughlin|2011|pp=213\u2013214}} Having borrowed as much money as he could, Modell completed the purchase in March 1961 for $3.925 million. Bob Gries, who had a share in the Browns from the beginning, agreed to buy in again at the new valuation and take a stake of almost 40%, defraying Modell's costs substantially.{{sfn|Coughlin|2011|p=214}} As the previous owners did when they took over, Modell quickly assured Cleveland fans that Brown would \"have a free hand\" in running the organization and awarded him a new eight-year contract.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=37}} \"As far as I'm concerned Paul Brown can send [plays] in by carrier pigeon\", Modell said. \"In my opinion he has no peer as a football coach. His record speaks for itself. I view our relationship as a working partnership.\"{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=43}}\n\nThe 1961 season was typical on the field: Jim Brown led the league in rushing for the fifth straight season and the team ended with an 8\u20135\u20131 record. That left Cleveland two games out of a berth in the championship.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=50}} During that year, however, players began to question Paul Brown's strict and often overbearing demeanor, while many challenged his control over the team's strategy. Milt Plum spoke out against Brown calling all the team's offensive plays, and Jim Brown said on a weekly radio broadcast that the coach's play-calling and handling of Plum were undermining the quarterback's confidence.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=48}}{{sfn|Lebovitz|2006|p=15}} They found a willing listener in Modell, a bachelor who was closer to their age than the coach's.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=43, 47}}\n\nFurther cracks appeared in the \"working partnership\" between Paul Brown and Modell before the 1962 season. Brown made a trade without informing Modell, giving up star halfback [[Bobby Mitchell]] to acquire the rights to Syracuse running back [[Ernie Davis]], the first African-American to win the [[Heisman Trophy]].{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=50}} Davis was chosen by the [[Washington Redskins]] with the first overall pick in the 1962 draft, but while Davis was the first black player ever selected by Washington, team owner [[George Preston Marshall]] made the move only after being given an ultimatum to add an African-American player or risk losing his stadium lease. Davis demanded a trade, leaving the door open to the Browns, who signed him to a three-year contract worth $80,000.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=51}} As Davis was preparing for the [[College All-Star Game]], however, he came down with a mystery illness and was later diagnosed with [[leukemia]]. Brown ruled Davis out for the season, but the running back returned to Cleveland and began a conditioning program after one of his doctors said playing football would not exacerbate his condition.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=52}} Modell thought Davis could be prepared to play, and Davis, who by then knew he was dying, wanted to be part of the team. Brown, however, continued to insist that he sit out, driving a deeper wedge between him and Modell. Davis died the following May.{{sfn|Lebovitz|2006|pp=15\u201316}}\n\nThe rift between Brown and Modell only widened as the 1962 season progressed. [[Frank Ryan (American football)|Frank Ryan]] took Milt Plum's place as the team's starting quarterback by the end of the season, and the Browns finished with a 7\u20136\u20131 record. Jim Brown was not the NFL's leading rusher for the only time in his career.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=57}}\n\n===Paul Brown is fired===\n\nOn January 9, 1963, Art Modell sent a statement to the newswires: \"Paul E. Brown, head coach and general manager, will no longer serve the team in those capacities\", it said.<ref name=\"Paul Brown fired\">{{cite news|last=Friedman|first=Larry|title=Paul Brown Fired After 17 Years With Browns|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1908&dat=19630111&id=jmEfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ldQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3133,483230|accessdate=May 18, 2012|newspaper=Nevada Daily Mail|date=January 10, 1963|agency=Associated Press|page=8}}</ref> Immediate reaction to the decision was muted due to a newspaper strike that kept the [[Cleveland Plain Dealer]] and [[Cleveland Press]] off the newsstands until April. A printing company executive, however, got together a group of sportswriters and published a 32-page magazine fielding players' views on the firing. Opinions were mixed; Modell came in for his share of criticism, but tackle and team captain [[Mike McCormack (American football)|Mike McCormack]] said he did not think the team could win under Brown.{{sfn|Lebovitz|2006|p=13\u201314}} Nonetheless, it was a shocking end to the 17-year Cleveland career of a coach who was already a seminal figure in the city's sports history.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=62\u201363}} Among many innovations, Brown was the first coach to call plays for his quarterback, give players IQ and personality tests and use game film to evaluate opponents.{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=3}} Even Jim Brown lauded his pioneering role in integrating the game:\n\n<blockquote>Paul Brown integrated pro football without uttering a single word about integration. He just went out, signed a bunch of great black athletes, and started kicking butt. That's how you do it. You don't talk about it.&nbsp;... [I]n his own way, the man integrated football the right way \u2013 and no one was going to stop him.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=49}}</blockquote>\n\nModell named Brown's chief assistant, [[Blanton Collier]], as the team's new head coach.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=64}} Collier was a friendly, studious man who became a player favorite as an assistant on both offense and defense under Brown.{{sfn|Groza|2003|p=52}} He installed an open offense and allowed Ryan to call his own plays.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=67}} In Collier's first season, the Browns finished with a 10\u20134 record but fell short of a division title.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=75, 77}} Jim Brown won the [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|MVP award]] in 1963 with a record 1,863&nbsp;yards rushing. Dominant blocking from the Browns' offensive line, which included guard [[Gene Hickerson]] and left tackle [[Dick Schafrath]], helped boost his totals.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=74, 78}}\n\n===1964 championship===\n\n[[File:Cleveland Browns quarterback Frank Ryan, 1964.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Cleveland quarterback Frank Ryan is mobbed after the 1964 championship.]]\n\nCleveland climbed back to the top of the eastern division in 1964 with a 10\u20133\u20131 record behind Jim Brown's league-leading 1,446&nbsp;yards of rushing.<ref name=\"1964 statistics\">{{cite web|title=1964 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1964.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UXIe1c9?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1964.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Rookie wide receiver [[Paul Warfield]] led the team with 52 catches,{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=112, 198}} and Frank Ryan cemented his place as the team's starting quarterback, recording the best game of his career in the season closer against the New York Giants, a game the Browns needed to win to advance to the championship.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=118\u2013119}} Yet despite Cleveland's prowess, the Browns went into the [[1964 NFL Championship Game|championship game]] as heavy underdogs against the Baltimore Colts. Most sportswriters predicted an easy win for the Colts, who led the league in scoring behind quarterback [[Johnny Unitas]] and halfback [[Lenny Moore]]. The Browns' defense, moreover, was suspect. The team gave up 20 more first downs than any other in the league.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=122\u2013124}} The teams, however, had not faced each other for three years. Before the game, Collier and Colts coach [[Don Shula]] agreed to give each other full access to video of regular-season games. Ever the student, Collier took full advantage of the opportunity. The Browns had run what was dubbed a \"rubber band\" pass defense, allowing short throws while trying to prevent big plays. The Colts' top receivers, however, [[Raymond Berry]] and [[Jimmy Orr]], were not fast. They tended to pick apart defenses with short, tactical completions, which led Collier to institute a man-to-man pass defense for the game. This, he figured, would buy more time for the defensive line and force Unitas to scramble \u2014 not his forte.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=131\u2013132}}\n\nThe strategy paid off, and in the wind-whipped Cleveland Municipal Stadium two days after [[Christmas]], the Browns beat the Colts 27\u20130. Neither team scored in the first half, prompting ''[[New York Times]]'' columnist [[Red Smith (sportswriter)|Red Smith]] to quip, \"Never have so many paid so dearly \u2013 $10, $8, and $6 \u2013 and suffered so sorely to see so little.\"{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=148}} In the second half, the Browns' defense held on and the offense kicked into gear. Baltimore's cornerbacks were double-teaming Warfield, which Ryan exploited by throwing three touchdowns to his second wideout, [[Gary Collins (American football)|Gary Collins]]. The Browns scored 10 points in the third quarter and a further 17 in the fourth, clinching the first title since Otto Graham's departure after the 1955 season.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=150\u2013151}} Collins was named the game's MVP.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=158}}  This would be the last time that any professional sports team from Cleveland would win a league title until 2016, when the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]'s [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] won the [[2016 NBA Finals]].\nTo date, this remains the last time that the Browns have won the NFL title.\n\nThe following year was a strong one as Jim Brown gritted out another league-leading rushing season.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=178}} The Browns ended with an 11\u20133 record and comfortably won the eastern division.<ref name=\"1965 statistics\">{{cite web|title=1965 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1965.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UXOrD2U?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1965.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> That set up a second straight appearance in the [[1965 NFL Championship Game|NFL Championship game]] against the Packers on a slippery, mucky [[Lambeau Field]] on January 2, 1966. While the score was close early on, [[Vince Lombardi]]'s team held the Browns scoreless in the second half, winning 23\u201312 in an upset on a [[Paul Hornung]] touchdown.{{sfn|Page|2010|pp=206\u2013209}} After the season, the NFL and the competing [[American Football League]] agreed to [[AFL\u2013NFL merger|merge]] starting in 1970, but would play an inter-league championship from the 1966 season onward. The 1965 championship thus became the NFL's last before the Super Bowl era, which ushered in a new age of popularity and prosperity for professional football.\n\n{{quote|text=In time, this game would be nearly forgotten, lost in the middle of Lombardi's great triumphs.&nbsp;... This was both unfair and fitting in a sense, because the game was best considered on its own, a faded dream played in the mist and slop, a transitory moment between football past and future.|sign=[[David Maraniss]]|source=''When Pride Still Mattered: A Life of Vince Lombardi''{{sfn|Maraniss|2000}}}}\n\n==Playoff disappointments (1966\u20131973)==\n\nIn early 1966 Jim Brown, who had begun an acting career two years before, was shooting for his second film in London.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=176\u2013178}} ''[[The Dirty Dozen]]'' cast Brown as Robert Jefferson, a convict sent to France during World War II to assassinate German officers meeting at a castle near [[Rennes]] in [[Brittany]]. Production delays due to bad weather meant he would miss at least the first part of training camp on the campus of [[Hiram College]], which annoyed Modell, who threatened to fine Brown $1,500 for every week of camp he missed.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=178\u2013179}} Brown, who had previously said that 1966 would be his last season, announced his retirement instead.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=179}} At the end of his nine-year career, Brown held records for most rushing yards in a game, a season and a career. He also owned the record for all-purpose yards in a career and best average per carry for a running back at 5.22&nbsp;yards, a mark that still stands.<ref name=\"Jim Brown career HOF stats\">{{cite web|title=Jim Brown|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.aspx?PlayerId=33&tab=Highlights|publisher=Pro Football Hall Of Fame|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UZ5wryd?url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.aspx?PlayerId=33&tab=Highlights|archivedate=June 17, 2012|accessdate=June 15, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith Brown gone, halfback [[Leroy Kelly]] became the team's primary rusher in 1966. Kelly, an eighth-round draft choice who saw limited playing time in two years as a backup, ably filled his predecessor's shoes.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=272\u2013276}} Cleveland missed the playoffs in 1966, but made it to the postseason the following year after a realignment of the NFL's divisions that placed the Browns in the new [[Century Division]].{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=50}} The Browns, however, lost the 1967 eastern conference championship to the [[Dallas Cowboys]].{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=50}} After a year in which he made just 11 of 23 field goal attempts, placekicker Lou Groza, the last remaining player from the inaugural 1946 Browns team, retired before the start of the 1968 season.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=190}} Groza, who had been on the roster for 21 seasons and was 44 years old when he hung up his spikes, said in his memoir that retiring was \"the saddest day of my football life.\"{{sfn|Groza|2003|p=100}}\n\nFurther playoff defeats followed. In 1968, as a 32-year-old Ryan was benched in favor of [[Bill Nelsen]],<ref name=\"Ryan benched for Nelsen\">{{cite news|last=Place|first=Tom|title=Nelsen Expects Big Rush By Steelers|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=October 2, 1968|page=33|quote=Coach Blanton Collier has tagged him as the man to rally to the Browns from two straight inept offensive performances in a move that sends Frank Ryan to the bench. After losing to Dallas, 28\u20137, two weeks ago and Los Angeles, 24\u20136, last Sunday, Collier decided a change had to be made.}}</ref> the Browns finished with a 10\u20134 record but lost to the Colts in the playoffs.<ref name=\"Colts beat Browns, 1968\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns' Title Bid Ends, 34\u20130 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19681229BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UZElYZJ?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19681229BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 29, 1968 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Another playoff loss ended the Browns' season in 1969, this time to the [[Minnesota Vikings]].<ref name=\"Vikings beat Browns, 1970\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Vikings Repulse Browns, 27\u20137 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19700104BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UZMEIjN?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19700104BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=January 4, 1970 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After the American Football League's merger with the NFL was finalized in early 1970, the Browns, [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] and Baltimore Colts moved to the new American Football Conference along with the 10 teams of the former AFL. The Browns were slotted in the [[AFC Central]] in the 26-team league, alongside the Steelers, the [[Houston Oilers]] and the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], a team Paul Brown founded in 1968 in the AFL.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|pp=51\u201352}} Cleveland's first big move under the new league structure was to trade star receiver Paul Warfield in January 1970 to the [[Miami Dolphins]] for the rights to draft [[Purdue University]] quarterback [[Mike Phipps]] as a replacement for Bill Nelsen, who had a pair of bad knees.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=61}}<ref name=\"Warfield trade announced\">{{cite news|title=Browns Trade Warfield, Three Others for Jones, Draft Pick|newspaper=The Bryan Times|date=January 27, 1970|agency=United Press International|page=8|quote='Paul has played so well for us and is such a high type person that I hated like the devil to consider any trade involving him,' Modell said. 'However, it was the overwhelming consensus of all our combined thinking that we had a pressing need for backup protection behind quarterback Bill Nelsen.' Warfield called his trade to the Dolphins a 'great surprise'.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1986 Jeno's Pizza - 31 - Rick Volk and Leroy Kelly.jpg|thumb|right|The Browns playing against the Baltimore Colts in a 1971 divisional playoff Game.]]\nThe Browns opened the first post-merger season of 1970 by beating [[Joe Namath]] and the New York Jets in the first-ever broadcast of [[Monday Night Football]] on September 21.{{sfn|Boyer|2006|pp=66\u201368}} The following month, Cleveland faced Paul Brown's Bengals for the first time in a regular-season game, winning 30\u201327. That game was a highlight in an otherwise unsuccessful season. The Browns lost their second match against the Bengals 14\u201310 in November, when Phipps made his first start \u2014 Brown called it \"my greatest victory\" \u2014 and finished 7\u20137.<ref name=\"Browns beat Bengals, 1970\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns nip Cincy, so do Birds |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19701011BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UZOzlMZ?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19701011BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=October 11, 1970 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nPlagued by hearing problems, the 64-year-old Collier announced his retirement before the end of the 1970 season.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=52}} In eight years as coach, Collier led Cleveland to a championship and a 74\u201333\u20132 record.<ref name=\"Collier retires\">{{cite news|title=Browns' Blanton Says He's Retiring This Year|newspaper=Rochester Sentinel|date=December 2, 1970}}</ref> [[Nick Skorich]] was named as his replacement the following year.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=61}} Skorich came to the Browns as offensive coordinator in 1964, when the team won the championship.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=61}} In Cleveland's first year under Skorich, the team improved to 9\u20135 but lost to the Colts in a divisional playoff.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=62}} Mike Phipps was promoted to starting quarterback over Nelsen before the 1972 season.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=62}} After a sluggish start, the Browns went on tear and finished with a 10\u20134 record. That put Cleveland in a playoff against the undefeated Miami Dolphins. The Browns took a lead in the fourth quarter on a touchdown catch by wide receiver [[Fair Hooker]], but the Dolphins responded with a long drive of their own, aided by a pair of Paul Warfield receptions. Running back [[Jim Kiick]] ran for a touchdown, sealing a 20\u201314 win and preserving the Dolphins' perfect season.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=63}} The following year, Phipps threw 20 interceptions and completed less than half of his passes.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=63}} After winning four of the first six games, the Browns slumped and placed third in the division with a 7\u20135\u20132 record.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=63}}\n\n==Brian Sipe era and the Kardiac Kids (1974\u20131984)==\n\nTransition and poor play marked the mid- to late-1970s. Though Collier agreed to come back to the Browns as a quarterbacks coach on an informal basis, his retirement severed the last direct link to Brown and the team's early years.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=297}} Meanwhile, a new generation of players began to replace the old hands who kept Cleveland in playoff contention through most of the 1960s. Gene Hickerson, an anchor on the offensive line in the 1960s, retired at the end of the 1973 season.<ref name=\"Hickerson hall of fame\">{{cite web|title=Gene Hickerson |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.aspx?PLAYER_ID=263 |publisher=Pro Football Hall of Fame |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UauC4Rm?url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.aspx?PLAYER_ID=263 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> An aging Leroy Kelly left the same year to play in the short-lived [[World Football League]].{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=276}} Offensive lineman Dick Schafrath, a six-time Pro Bowl selection, retired in 1971.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=205}}\n\nAgainst that backdrop, the Browns finished the 1974 season with a 4\u201310 record, only the second losing season in the team's history.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=63}} Phipps' woes persisted, and he shared playing time with rookie quarterback [[Brian Sipe]], who Cleveland selected in the 13th round of the 1972 draft out of [[San Diego State]].{{sfn|Pluto|2010|p=62}} Modell fired Skorich after the season. \"You've got to be a winner in this game, and I just didn't produce\", Skorich said at the time.<ref name=\"Skorich fired\">{{cite news|title=Browns Coach Skorich Fired|newspaper=Bangor Daily News|date=December 17, 1974|agency=Associated Press|page=21}}</ref> After pursuing Dolphins offensive line coach [[Monte Clark]], Modell hired [[Forrest Gregg]] as Skorch's replacement.{{sfn|Gregg|2009|pp=196\u2013197}} Gregg, an assistant coach and former Green Bay Packers offensive lineman, preached a hard-nosed, physical brand of football, learned as an offensive lineman on Green Bay's dynastic 1960s teams under Lombardi.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|pp=63\u201364}} His success as a player, however, did not immediately translate into success as a coach. The regular season began with the worst losing streak in Cleveland's history. Gregg's first win did not come until November 23 against Paul Brown's Cincinnati Bengals, and Cleveland finished with a 3\u201311 record.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=64}}\n\nThe team improved the following year, ending with a 9\u20135 record but missing the playoffs.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=16}} The highlight of that season was an 18\u201316 victory over the Pittsburgh Steelers on October 10.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=64}} Kicker [[Don Cockroft]] booted four field goals, while defensive end [[Joe (Turkey) Jones|Joe \"Turkey\" Jones]]' pile-driving sack of quarterback [[Terry Bradshaw]] added fuel to the heated rivalry between the teams.<ref name=\"Browns beat Steelers, 1976\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Steelers jolted |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19761010BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UayWnuK?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19761010BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=October 10, 1976 |url-status=dead }}</ref> While Gregg won the NFL's [[National Football League Coach of the Year Award|Coach of the Year award]] for turning the Browns around as Sipe became the starting quarterback, by the beginning of the 1977 season the same kind of friction that dogged Paul Brown's relationship with Modell was surfacing between the owner and the hotheaded Gregg.{{sfn|Gregg|2009|pp=227\u2013236}} Cleveland got off to a strong start that year, but Sipe hurt his shoulder and elbow in a November 13 game against the Steelers, and backup [[Dave Mays]] took the reins.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=16}} With Mays as the quarterback \u2013 Modell traded Phipps to the [[Chicago Bears]] for a couple of draft picks \u2013 Cleveland slipped to 6\u20137 going into the final game of the season and Modell asked Gregg to resign.<ref name=\"Gregg fired\">{{cite news|title=Gregg Out Of Work After Big 1976 Season|newspaper=The Leader-Post|date=December 20, 1977|agency=Associated Press|page=16|quote=Most persons close to the scene agree that the catalyst in Gregg's downfall was his temper, which turned off many of the veteran players on the team and widened an apparent personality conflict between him and owner Art Modell.}}</ref>\n\nModell said he would look outside the Browns organization for a new coach, a break from past hirings that drew from the team's own ranks.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=11}} Peter Hadhazy, who Modell had hired as the Browns' first general manager, recommended a 45-year-old [[New Orleans Saints]] receivers coach named [[Sam Rutigliano]]. After an interview before Christmas in which Modell and Rutigliano spent hours talking and watching game film in Modell's basement, the owner named him head coach on December 27, 1977.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=11}} An affable, charismatic man with an even temper, Rutigliano was a stark contrast to Gregg.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=11\u201312}} Sipe immediately flourished under Rutigliano, racking up 21 touchdowns and 2,906 passing yards during the 1978 season, when the NFL moved to a 16-game schedule.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=16}} His prime targets were [[Reggie Rucker]], a veteran receiver the Browns signed in 1975, and [[Ozzie Newsome]], a rookie tight end out of [[University of Alabama|Alabama]] who the Browns drafted with a pick acquired in the Phipps trade.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=19\u201321}} Cleveland won its first three games, but poor defense dashed the team's playoff chances and the Browns finished with an 8\u20138 record.<ref name=\"1978 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=1978 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1978.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ub2Wcep?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1978.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Kardiac Kids===\n\n[[File:Sipe1979bySherk.jpeg|thumb|right|Cleveland Browns quarterback Brian Sipe led the \"Kardiac Kids\" to a series of last-minute victories.]]\n\nRutigliano was a gambler: he tinkered with offenses, took chances on trick plays and was not afraid to break with the play-calling conventions of his time.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=12\u201313}} The coach, who earned the nickname \"Riverboat Sam\" for his risk-taking approach, once said that security was \"for cowards\". \"I believe in gambling\", he said. \"No successful man ever got anywhere without gambling.\"{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=13}} This seat-of-your-pants philosophy began to manifest itself on the field in 1979. The campaign started with a nail-biter against the New York Jets that the Browns won in overtime on a Cockroft field goal as time expired. \"If we continue to play 'em that way all year, I'll be gone before the 10th game because my heart just won't take it\", Rutigliano said after the game.<ref name=\"Browns beat Jets in OT, 1979\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns stun Jets in OT |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19790902BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ub4u7Cx?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19790902BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 25, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=September 2, 1979 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the second week, Cleveland beat the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] 27\u201324 on a Sipe touchdown to Rucker with 52 seconds left.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=74}} The third game was an equally improbable 13\u201310 win against the Baltimore Colts.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=74}} ''Cleveland Plain Dealer'' sports editor [[Hal Lebovitz]] wrote after the game that these \"[[Kardiac Kids]]\" were lucky to have pulled off the win after Colts kicker [[Toni Linhart]] missed three field goals.<ref name=\"Lebovitz on Kardiac Kids\">{{cite news|last=Lebovitz|first=Hal|title=Gift from Colts|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 17, 1979|page=1\u2013C}}</ref>\n\nAfter a string of four wins and three losses, the late-game heroics returned in an overtime victory on November 18 against the Miami Dolphins.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=13}} \"You should never pipe Browns games into an intensive care unit, expose them to anyone weak of pulse\", wrote [[Toledo Blade]] columnist Jim Taylor. \"They're one of those teams that stands 8\u20134, and could easily be 1\u201311.\"<ref name=\"Blade on Kardiac Kids\">{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Jim|title=Browns' Routine Not Routine|newspaper=The Toledo Blade|date=November 19, 1979|page=20}}</ref> While the Browns' 9\u20137 record did not get the team into the playoffs \u2013 the defense struggled all year, forcing Sipe and the offense to compensate with late-game comebacks \u2013 a sense of optimism and excitement took hold.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=13\u201314}}\n\nThe Kardiac Kids magic returned in the third game of the next season against the Chiefs, when the Browns scored a touchdown in the fourth quarter to win 20\u201313.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=75}} More down-to-the-wire games followed, including one against Green Bay on October 19 in which the team won on a touchdown to receiver [[Dave Logan (American football)|Dave Logan]] on the last play of the game.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=82\u201383}} After a close win over the Steelers and a victory over the Bears in which Sipe broke Otto Graham's club record for career passing yards, the Browns met the Colts and eked out a 28\u201327 win.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=98\u201399, 108, 111, 118}} The team ended with an 11\u20135 record.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=223}}\n\n===Red Right 88===\n\n{{Main|Red Right 88}}\n\nThat was good for first place in the AFC Central and a trip to the postseason for the first time since 1972.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=76}} The Browns began their playoff run against the [[Oakland Raiders]] on January 4, 1981 in a bitterly cold Cleveland Municipal Stadium.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=234\u2013236}} The game started slowly: each team scored only a touchdown in the first half, although Cockroft missed Cleveland's extra point because of a bad snap.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=238\u2013242}} In the third quarter, Cleveland went ahead 12\u20137 on a pair of Cockroft field goals, but the Raiders came back in the final period, driving 80&nbsp;yards down the field for a touchdown. That put Oakland ahead 14\u201312.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=243\u2013245}} The ball changed hands five times with no scoring from either side, and with 2:22 on the clock, Cleveland had a final shot to win the game.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=246\u2013247}} Sipe and the offense took over at the Browns' 15-yard line. In eight plays, Cleveland drove down to Oakland's 14, leaving 56 seconds on the clock.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=250}}\n\n[[File:Sam-Rutigliano-1979.jpg|thumb|left|Sam Rutigliano, the Browns' head coach during the Kardiac Kids years]]\n\nAfter a one-yard [[Mike Pruitt]] run, Rutigliano called a timeout.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=250}} A short field goal would have been the safe bet \u2014 that was all Cleveland needed to win. Rutigliano, ever the risk-taker, decided to go for a touchdown. The coach was reluctant to stake the game's outcome on the usually sure-footed Cockroft, who had missed two field goals and an extra point earlier in the game.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=250}} The play he called was [[Red Right 88]], a passing formation in which a slanting Logan would be Sipe's primary target, while Newsome was insurance. If everyone was covered, Rutigliano told Sipe on the sidelines, \"if you feel you have to force the ball, throw it into Lake Erie, throw it into some blonde's lap in the bleachers.\"{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=251}} Sipe took the snap, dropped back and threw to Newsome as he crossed to the left. But Oakland safety [[Mike Davis (defensive back)|Mike Davis]] leaped in front and intercepted the ball, cementing the Oakland win. The Raiders went on to win [[Super Bowl XV]], while Red Right 88 became an enduring symbol of Cleveland's postseason stumbles.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=252\u2013254, 261, 265}}\n\nDespite 1980's playoff defeat, the Browns were widely expected to be even better the following year. But 1981 came with none of the comebacks or late-game magic the Kardiac Kids were known for. Several games were close, but most were losses. Sipe threw only 17 touchdowns and was intercepted 25 times.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=269\u2013270}} The team finished 5\u201311.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=272}} The [[1982 NFL strike]], which began in September and lasted until mid-November, shortened the regular season the following year to nine games.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=276}} Coming off a poor year, Sipe split starts with his backup, [[Paul McDonald (American football)|Paul McDonald]], and neither was able to bring back the old Kardiac Kids spark.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=276}} The team ended with a 4\u20135 record, which qualified for an expanded Super Bowl playoff tournament created to accommodate the shorter season. The Browns faced the Raiders in a rematch of 1980's playoff thriller. This time, though, McDonald was the starter and the ending was far from tense. The Raiders won 27\u201310.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=276}}\n\nThe following two years brought the Sipe era and the short-lived success of the Kardiac Kids to an end.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=277}} Sipe returned to form in 1983, and the team narrowly missed a spot in the playoffs after a loss to the Houston Oilers in the second-to-last game of the regular season.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=78}} Sipe signed before the end of the season to play for the [[New Jersey Generals]], a team owned by real estate mogul [[Donald Trump]] in the upstart [[United States Football League]].{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=277}}\n\nIn training camp before the 1984 season, cornerback [[Hanford Dixon]] tried to motivate the team's defensive linemen by barking at them between plays in practice and calling them \"the Dogs\". \"You need guys who play like dogs up front, like dogs chasing a cat\", Dixon said.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=26}} The media picked up on the name, which gained traction in part because of the improvement of the Browns' defense during the regular season. Fans put on face paint and dog masks, and the phenomenon coalesced in rowdy fans in Cleveland Stadium's cheap bleachers section close to the field.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=26}} The [[Dawg Pound]], as the section was eventually nicknamed, is a continuing symbol of Cleveland's dedicated fan base.{{sfn|Boyer|2006|pp=101\u2013105}}\n\nDespite the defensive improvement, Sipe's departure left Cleveland's offense in disarray in 1984. Browns began the season 1\u20137 with McDonald at quarterback, and fans' frustration with the team and Rutigliano boiled over.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=78}} The breaking point came in an October 7 game against the [[New England Patriots]] that bore an eerie resemblance to Cleveland's 1980 playoff loss to the Raiders. The Browns were down 17\u201316 in the fourth quarter, and lost on an interception in New England's end zone as time expired.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=278}} Chants of \"Goodbye Sam\" rung out from the stands after the New England game. Modell called the play-calling \"inexcusable\" and fired Rutigliano two weeks later.<ref name=\"Rutigliano on hot seat\">{{cite news|last=Schneider|first=Russ|title=Rutigliano's control is key to his destiny|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=October 14, 1984|page=2\u2013B}}</ref> Defensive coordinator [[Marty Schottenheimer]] took over, and the Browns ended with a 5\u201311 record.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=279}}\n\n==Bernie Kosar years, The Drive and The Fumble (1985\u20131990)==\n\nThe selection of [[Miami Hurricanes football|University of Miami]] quarterback [[Bernie Kosar]] in 1985's [[supplemental draft]] ushered in a new, largely successful era for Cleveland. With Schottenheimer, Kosar and a cast of talented players on offense and defense, the team reached greater heights than Rutigliano and Sipe ever did. Though they became consistent playoff contenders in this era, the Browns did not reach the Super Bowl, falling one win short three times in the late 1980s.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=299\u2013300}}\n\n[[File:Bruce-and-Clay-Matthews-80s.jpg|thumb|right|Browns linebacker [[Clay Matthews, Jr.|Clay Matthews]] (right) with his brother [[Bruce Matthews (American football)|Bruce Matthews]] of the Houston Oilers. Matthews played a key role on Cleveland's defenses of the late 1980s.]]\n\nKosar, who wanted to play for Cleveland because his family lived in a suburb of nearby [[Youngstown, Ohio|Youngstown]], signed a five-year contract worth nearly $6 million in 1985 and was immediately embraced by the Browns organization and the team's fans.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=16, 21}} \"It's not an everyday occurrence that somebody ''wants'' to play in Cleveland\", Modell said. \"This has lent such an aura to Bernie.\"<ref name=\"SI on Bernie 1985\">{{cite journal|last=Looney|first=Douglas S.|title=There's A Love Feast On Lake Erie|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=August 26, 1985}}</ref> Kosar saw his first action in the fifth week of the 1985 season against the New England Patriots, when he substituted before halftime for [[Gary Danielson]], a 34-year-old veteran who the Browns had acquired in the offseason from the Lions.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=24, 44\u201345}} Kosar fumbled his first-ever NFL snap, but rebounded and led the team to a 24\u201320 win.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=45}} A mix of success and failure followed, but Kosar progressed a bit more each Sunday and led the team to an 8\u20138 record.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=50, 52\u201354}} Two young running backs, [[Earnest Byner]] and [[Kevin Mack]], complemented Kosar's aerial attack with more than 1,000&nbsp;yards rushing each.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=54\u201355}}\n\nWhile not stellar, the Browns' record won first place in a weak AFC Central, and the team looked poised to shock the heavily favored Miami Dolphins in a divisional playoff game on January 4, 1986.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=56}} Cleveland surged to a 21\u20133 halftime lead, and it took a spirited second-half comeback by [[Dan Marino]] and the Dolphins to win it 24\u201321 and end the Browns' season.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=58\u201362}} Despite the loss, many people expected Cleveland to be back the following year. \"The Browns' days, the good days, are here and ahead of us\", radio personality Pete Franklin said.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=62}}\n\nPrior to the 1986 season the Browns lost standout safety and former defensive rookie of the year [[Don Rogers (safety)|Don Rogers]]. Rogers died of a cocaine overdose leaving the team without one of its best defenders in the secondary for the 1986 season. Despite the tumultuous off season, 1986 marked Cleveland's entry into the ranks of the NFL's elite as Kosar's play improved and the defensive unit came together. Kosar threw for 3,854&nbsp;yards to a corps of receivers that included [[Brian Brennan]], Newsome and rookie [[Webster Slaughter]].{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=93, 95, 98}} On defense, cornerbacks [[Frank Minnifield]] and Hanford Dixon emerged as one of the NFL's premiere pass-defending duos.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=28\u201329}} After a slow start, the Browns rose to the top of the divisional standings, twice beating the Pittsburgh Steelers and ending a 16-game losing streak at [[Three Rivers Stadium]].{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=73, 79, 93}} A 12\u20134 record earned Cleveland home-field advantage throughout the playoffs.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=89}}\n\nThe Browns' first opponents in the 1986 playoffs were the New York Jets.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=97\u201398}} The Jets were ahead for most of the game and held a 20\u201310 lead as time wound down in the final quarter. But Cleveland took over and began a march down the field, ending with a Kevin Mack touchdown.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=100\u2013103}} The defense forced the Jets to punt after the ensuing kickoff, leaving the offense with less than a minute to get within field goal range and even the score at 20\u201320. A pass interference penalty and a completion to Slaughter put the ball at the Jets' five-yard line, and kicker [[Mark Moseley]] booted through the tying score with 11 seconds left.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=103\u2013105}} In an initial 15-minute overtime period, Moseley missed a short field goal and neither team scored, sending the game into double overtime.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=106\u2013108}} This time, Moseley made a field goal and won the game for the Browns 23\u201320. It was the team's first playoff victory in 17 years.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=109}}\n\n===The Drive===\n\n{{Main|The Drive}}\n\nThe following week, the Browns matched up against the [[Denver Broncos]] in the AFC Championship game in Cleveland.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=116}} Denver got out to an early lead, but Cleveland tied the game and then went ahead 20\u201313 in the fourth quarter.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=116, 118\u2013119}} After the ensuing kickoff, the Broncos were pinned at their own 2-yard line with 5:32 remaining. Denver quarterback [[John Elway]] then engineered a 98-yard drive for a touchdown with the cold, whipping wind in his face.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=121\u2013127}} \"[[The Drive]]\", as the series came to be known, tied the score and sent the game into overtime. Cleveland received the ball first in the [[sudden death (sport)|sudden-death period]] but was stopped by the Denver defense. On Denver's first possession, Elway again led the Broncos on a long drive ending with a [[Rich Karlis]] field goal that sailed just inside the left upright and won the game.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=128\u2013130}} The drive that tied the game has since come to be seen as one of the best in playoff history, and is remembered by Cleveland fans as an historic meltdown. Denver went on to lose [[Super Bowl XXI]] to the New York Giants.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=131\u2013132}}\n\n{{quote|text=The drive, one of the finest ever engineered in a championship game, had been performed directly in the Browns' faces. There was no sneakiness about it; John Elway had simply shown what a man with all the tools could do. It was what everybody who had watched him enter the league as perhaps the most heralded quarterback since Joe Namath knew he could do. One was left with the distinct feeling that Elway would have marched his team down a 200-yard-or 300-yard-or five-mile-long field to pay dirt.|sign=[[Rick Telander]]|source=''Sports Illustrated''<ref name=\"Telander on The Drive\">{{cite journal|last=Telander|first=Rick|title=Getting There The Hard Way|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=January 19, 1987}}</ref>}}\n\nAlthough downtrodden by 1986's playoff defeat, Cleveland continued to win the following season.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=132}} Minnifield and Dixon excelled defending the pass, while Matthews and defensive tackle [[Bob Golic]] kept runners in check.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=152\u2013153, 162}} The Browns finished with a 10\u20135 record in 1987 and won the AFC Central for the third year in a row.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=92}} In the divisional playoff round, the Browns faced the [[Indianapolis Colts]] and won 38\u201321.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=166\u2013167}}\n\n===The Fumble===\n\n{{Main|The Fumble}}\n\nThe win set up a rematch with the Broncos in the AFC Championship in Denver.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=169}} The Broncos held a 21\u20133 lead at halftime, but a pair of rushing touchdowns and another by receiver [[Reggie Langhorne]] brought Cleveland to within seven points.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=173\u2013177}} Cleveland scored again in the fourth quarter, but the Broncos went ahead again by seven points on a touchdown with four minutes left.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=178\u2013179}} After Denver's kickoff, Kosar and the offense reached the Broncos' eight-yard line with 1:12 remaining.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=180}} Kosar handed the ball to Earnest Byner on a second down. Byner ran left and broke inside with a clear path to the end zone, but was stripped by Denver's [[Jeremiah Castille]] just before crossing the goal line. The Broncos ran down the clock before intentionally taking a [[Safety (American and Canadian football score)|safety]] and winning 38\u201333.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=181\u2013183}} \"[[The Fumble]]\" quickly entered the lexicon of the Browns' modern-era disappointment, just as The Drive had a year before.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=92}}\n\nThe 1988 season was marred by injuries to the Browns' quarterbacks. Kosar was injured in the opener against Kansas City Chiefs and two backups were subsequently injured, leaving [[Don Strock]], who the Browns signed as an emergency fill-in, to start before Kosar's return.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=191\u2013192, 197}} Kosar came back but was hurt again at the end of the regular season.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=209}} Despite the rotating cast of quarterbacks, Cleveland managed to finish with a 10\u20136 record and made the playoffs as a wild-card team.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=211, 215\u2013218}} Cleveland met the Houston Oilers in the wild-card playoff round at home, but lost the game 24\u201323.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=226}} Four days after the Oilers loss, Schottenheimer and Modell announced that the coach would leave the team by mutual consent. Modell felt hiring an offensive coordinator was necessary to keep pace with the Oilers and the Bengals, a pair of divisional opponents then on the rise, but Schottenheimer said it \"became evident that some of the differences we had, we weren't going to be able to resolve.\"{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=228\u2013229}}<ref name=\"Schottenheimer leaves Browns\">{{cite news|last=Melvin|first=Chuck|title=Schottenheimer Leaves Cleveland|newspaper=Gainesville Sun|date=December 28, 1988|agency=Associated Press|page=1\u2013C}}</ref> Modell named [[Bud Carson]] as his replacement.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=232\u2013233}}\n\nCarson, an architect of Pittsburgh's 1970s \"[[Steel Curtain]]\" defenses, made several changes to Cleveland's lineup.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=233}} Byner was traded to the Washington Redskins in April, while the Browns moved up in the draft to acquire [[Eric Metcalf]].{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=236\u2013238}} Kevin Mack, meanwhile, was suspended for the first four games of the 1989 season after pleading guilty to cocaine possession.<ref name=\"Mack cocaine plea\">{{cite news|title=Mack Pleads Guilty To Using Cocaine |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/08/31/sports/sports-people-football-mack-pleads-guilty-to-using-cocaine.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UcGD6Pe?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1989/08/31/sports/sports-people-football-mack-pleads-guilty-to-using-cocaine.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 27, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=August 26, 1989 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Despite these changes, Kosar led Cleveland to a division-winning 9\u20136\u20131 record in 1989, including a season-opening 51\u20130 shutout of the rival Pittsburgh Steelers and the team's first victory over the Denver Broncos in 15 years.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=243\u2013245, 252}} Cleveland narrowly survived a scare from the [[Buffalo Bills]] in the first playoff game, staving off a comeback thanks to an interception in the Browns' end zone by Clay Matthews with 14 seconds on the clock.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=281\u2013282}} The victory set up the third AFC championship matchup in four years between the Browns and Broncos. The Broncos led from start to finish, and a long Elway touchdown pass to Sammy Winder put the game way in the fourth quarter. Denver won 37\u201321.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=283\u2013285}}\n\nThe defeat in [[Mile High Stadium]] proved to be the last of Cleveland's streak of playoff appearances in the mid- to late-1980s. Kosar played through numerous injuries in 1989, including bruising on his right arm and a bad knee.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=265, 278}} Strong defense had carried the Browns to the playoffs even when the offense faltered, but that all crumbled in 1990. Kosar threw more interceptions than touchdowns for the first time in his career, and the defense allowed more points than any other in the league.<ref name=\"1990 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=1990 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1990.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UcIuG2k?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1990.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Browns' 2\u20137 start cost Carson his job.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=288\u2013289}} [[Jim Shofner]] was named interim head coach, and the team finished 3\u201313.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=290}} After the season [[Bill Belichick]], the defensive coordinator of the then-Super Bowl champion New York Giants, was named head coach.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=292}}\n\n==Bill Belichick and Modell's move (1991\u20131995)==\n\n===Belichick era===\n\nBelichick, who came to the Browns after 12 years mostly with the Giants under [[Bill Parcells]], quickly made his mark by restricting media access to the team. He acted gruff or bored at press conferences, shrugging, rolling his eyes and often giving short answers to long questions.{{sfn|Holley|2011|p=1}} This bred the perception that the new coach was not a good communicator and lacked a vision for the team. Behind the scenes, however, he was trying to remake the Browns. He reformed Cleveland's scouting methods and, in conjunction with player personnel director [[Michael Lombardi (sportscaster)|Mike Lombardi]], tried to form a coherent identity: a big and strong cold-weather team.{{sfn|Holley|2011|pp=1\u20132}} Belichick's new way forward, however, did not immediately translate to on-field success. Cleveland's record only improved slightly in 1991 to 6\u201310 as the offense struggled to produce scoring drives and the defense was plagued by injuries.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=101}} Kosar was a rare bright spot, passing for almost 3,500&nbsp;yards and 18 touchdowns.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=101}} Bridging the end of the 1990 season and the beginning of 1991, the quarterback threw a then-record 307 straight passes without an interception.{{sfn|Gordon|2002|p=84}} Kosar broke his ankle twice and sat out for most of the 1992 season, leaving quarterback [[Mike Tomczak]] under center. The team finished with a 7\u20139 record and did not make the playoffs.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=101}}\n\nBy the end of 1992, Kosar's physical decline had long been apparent to Belichick, which left the coach with a difficult choice.{{sfn|Holley|2011|pp=7\u20138}} Kosar was Cleveland's most popular athlete, a hometown boy who had forgone big money and a bigger profile to lead a struggling team back to the top.{{sfn|Holley|2011|pp=7\u20138}} While he recognized it would be an unpopular decision, Belichick wanted to bench Kosar, and in 1992 the team picked up a potential replacement in [[Vinny Testaverde]] from the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].{{sfn|Holley|2011|pp=8\u20139}} Belichick named Kosar the starter before the 1993 season,{{sfn|Holley|2011|p=13}} but in the third game against the Raiders, Belichick pulled Kosar after he threw his third interception of the night. Taking over with Los Angeles ahead 13\u20130, Testaverde led two touchdown drives to win the game. Two weeks later, Belichick named Testaverde the starter. On the verge of tears after a loss to the Dolphins, Kosar said he was disappointed with the decision and felt he had done what he could with what was at his disposal.<ref name=\"Testaverde named starter\">{{cite news|last=Cabot |first=Mary Kay |title=The Job is Testaverde's |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19931010BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UlYco7d?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19931010BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 28, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=October 10, 1993 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nKosar returned after Testaverde suffered a separated right shoulder in a win against the Steelers on October 24, but it was only temporary. The day after a loss against the Broncos the following week, the team cut him.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=101}} Belichick cited his declining skills, while Modell said it was the right move and asked fans to \"bear with us.\"<ref name=\"Kosar cut\">{{cite news|title=First-place Browns Cut Kosar|newspaper=Daily News, Bowling Green|date=November 9, 1993|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Fans brought out grills and set fire to their season tickets. A 20-year-old student at [[Baldwin\u2013Wallace College]] picketed outside the team's training facilities with a sign that read, \"Cut Belichick, Not Bernie.\"{{sfn|Holley|2011|p=13\u201314}} Cleveland won only two of the eight games after Kosar's release, finishing with a 7\u20139 record for the second year in a row.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=101}}\n\nCleveland managed to right the ship in 1994. While the quarterback situation had not stabilized, the defense led the league in fewest points allowed.<ref name=\"1994 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=1994 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1994.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UlcSpHc?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1994.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Browns finished 11\u20135, making the playoffs for the first time in five years. The Browns beat the Patriots in a wild-card game,<ref>{{cite news|last=Cabot |first=Mary Kay |title=One Playoff Down Browns 'Step Up' And Beat Patriots 20\u201313 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19950101BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UlftXA1?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19950101BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=January 1, 1995 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but arch-rival Pittsburgh won a 29\u20139 victory in the divisional playoff, ending the Browns' season.<ref name=\"Steelers beat Browns, 1994\">{{cite news|last=Cabot |first=Mary Kay |title=Simply The Pitts The Browns Get Whipped, Indisputably |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19950107BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ulj9rpH?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19950107BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=January 7, 1995 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Modell's Move to Baltimore===\n\n{{Main|Cleveland Browns relocation controversy}}\n\n[[File:Cleveland Municipal Stadium last game played in the stadium December 17, 1995.jpg|thumb|right|Browns owner Art Modell's 25-year lease of Cleveland Municipal Stadium planted the seed of financial troubles that culminated in his decision to relocate the team in 1995.]]\n\nAs the Browns recaptured a hint of past success in 1994, all was not well behind the scenes. Modell was in financial trouble. The origins of Modell's woes dated to 1973, when he worked out a deal to lease Cleveland Municipal Stadium from the city for a pittance: only enough to service the facility's debt and pay property taxes.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|p=137}} Cleveland Browns Stadium Corporation, or Stadium Corp., a company Modell and a business associate created and owned, held the 25-year lease. Stadium Corp. then subleased the stadium to the Browns and the [[Cleveland Indians]], and rented it out for concerts and other events.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|pp=137\u2013138}} While the deal worked fine for the city and Modell early on, the owner was later dogged by excessive borrowing and lawsuits.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|pp=137\u2013145}}\n\n[[File:1980-modell-browns crop.jpg|thumb|right|Cleveland owner Art Modell in 1983. Lawsuits by Browns minority owner Bob Gries and the Indians in the early 1980s exacerbated his financial problems.]]\n\nWhen the stadium was profitable, Modell had used Stadium Corp. to buy land in [[Strongsville, Ohio|Strongsville]] that he had previously acquired as the potential site for a future new stadium. Modell originally paid $625,000 for the land, but sold it to his own Stadium Corp. for more than $3 million. Then, when the stadium was taking losses in 1981, he sold Stadium Corp. itself to the Browns for $6 million. This led to a fight the following year with Bob Gries, whose family had been part of the Browns' ownership group since its founding and had 43% of the team to Modell's 53%. Gries's complaint was that Modell treated the Browns and Stadium Corp. as his own fiefdom, rarely consulting him about the team's business. The sale of Stadium Corp. to the Browns, he argued, enriched Modell at the team's expense.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|pp=139\u2013140}} Gries's case went to the [[Supreme Court of Ohio|Ohio Supreme Court]], where he won. In 1986, Modell had to reverse the Browns' purchase of Stadium Corp. and pay $1 million in Gries's legal fees. This left Modell in need of financial help, and it came in the form of [[Al Lerner]], a banking and real estate executive who bought half of Stadium Corp. and 5% of the Browns in 1986.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|p=139}}\n\nHis reputation damaged by the lawsuits, Modell was eager to get out of Cleveland. He met with Baltimore officials about selling the Browns to Lerner and buying an expansion team to replace the Colts, who had left for Indianapolis in 1984. He also discussed moving the Browns.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|p=143}} Proposals were made to spend $175 million on a stadium renovation after the Indians and [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] got new facilities in downtown Cleveland, but it was not enough.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|pp=143\u2013145}} As the Browns started the 1995 season with a 4\u20134 record, word leaked that Modell was moving the team.<ref name=\"NYT on Browns move\">{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Timothy W.|title=Baltimore Browns May Be a Done Deal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/04/sports/football-baltimore-browns-may-be-a-done-deal.html?src=pm|accessdate=May 31, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=November 4, 1995}}</ref> Beset by rising player salaries and political indifference to the team's financial plight, he said he was forced to move.<ref name=\"SI on Browns move\">{{cite journal|last=Munson |first=Lester |title=A Busted Play |journal=Sports Illustrated |date=December 4, 1995 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1007507/index.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UlqeldI?url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1007507/index.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 31, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The day after Modell formally announced the move, Cleveland voters overwhelmingly approved the $175 million of stadium renovations. Despite this, Modell ruled out a reversal of his decision, saying his relationship with Cleveland had been irrevocably severed. \"The bridge is down, burned, disappeared\", he said. \"There's not even a canoe there for me.\"<ref name=\"Modell bridges burned\">{{cite news|title=Modell: franchise movement is bad (but I'm still going)|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=November 8, 1995|agency=Associated Press|page=25}}</ref>\n\nThe city immediately sued to prevent the move, on the basis that the lease of the stadium was active until 1998. Fans were in an uproar, staging protests, signing petitions, filing lawsuits and appealing to other NFL owners to block the relocation. Advertisers pulled out of the stadium, fearing fans' ire.<ref name=\"NYT on Modell's move reaction\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=A City Fights To Save The Browns|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/12/sports/pro-football-a-city-fights-to-save-the-browns.html?ref=art_modell&pagewanted=all|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ulvzp8V?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/12/sports/pro-football-a-city-fights-to-save-the-browns.html?ref=art_modell&pagewanted=all|archivedate=June 17, 2012|accessdate=May 31, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 12, 1995|url-status=live}}</ref> Talks between the city, Modell and the NFL continued as the Browns finished the season with a 5\u201311 record. At the team's final home game against the Bengals, unruly fans in the Dawg Pound bleachers section rained debris, beer bottles and entire sections of seats onto the field, forcing officials to move play to the opposite end to ensure players' safety.{{sfn|Boyer|2006|p=131}} Cleveland won the game, its only victory after the announcement of the move.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=103}}\n\nThe following February, the warring parties reached a compromise. Under its terms, Modell would be allowed to take his personnel to Baltimore, but would leave Cleveland the Browns' colors, logos and heritage for a reactivated Browns franchise that would take the field no later than 1999.<ref name=\"Modell cleared to move\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir |first=Richard |title=N.F.L. Gives Modell a Ticket to Baltimore |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/10/sports/pro-football-nfl-gives-modell-a-ticket-to-baltimore.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Um048ay?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/10/sports/pro-football-nfl-gives-modell-a-ticket-to-baltimore.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |date=February 10, 1996 |work=The New York Times |url-status=dead }}</ref> The $175 million earmarked for stadium improvements was to be used instead build a new stadium, with up to $48 million of additional financial assistance from the NFL. Further, Modell was ordered to pay Cleveland $9.3 million to compensate for lost revenues and taxes during the Browns' three years of inactivity, plus up to $2.25 million of the city's legal fees. As a result of the deal Modell's team was technically an expansion franchise, called the [[Baltimore Ravens]].<ref name=\"Modell deal details\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=How Compromise Built Cleveland a New Stadium|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/12/sports/pro-football-how-compromise-built-cleveland-a-new-stadium.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=June 17, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Um3PzfT?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/12/sports/pro-football-how-compromise-built-cleveland-a-new-stadium.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|archivedate=June 17, 2012|date=February 12, 1996|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Inactivity (1996\u20131998)==\n\nPreparations for a reactivated franchise began shortly after Modell, the city and the NFL struck their compromise. The NFL established the Cleveland Browns Trust to direct the Browns' return in early 1996, and in June  appointed Bill Futterer as its president. Futterer, who had helped bring the [[Carolina Panthers]] and [[Charlotte Hornets]] expansion teams to [[North Carolina]], was charged with marketing the team, selling season tickets and representing the NFL's interests in the construction of a new stadium.<ref name=\"Futterer appointed\">{{cite news|title=Exec appointed for new Browns|newspaper=The Vindicator|date=June 28, 1996|agency=Associated Press|page=C3}}</ref> The trust also leased suites, sold [[personal seat license]]s in the new stadium and reorganized Browns Backers fan clubs.<ref name=\"NYT on Browns, 1998\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=The Price of Cleveland's Heart|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/02/sports/pro-football-the-price-of-cleveland-s-heart.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=16 June 2012|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Uor4H0s?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/02/sports/pro-football-the-price-of-cleveland-s-heart.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|archivedate=17 June 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 2, 1998|url-status=live}}</ref> By September 1996, architects were finalizing the design of a new stadium to be built following the destruction of Cleveland Municipal Stadium.<ref name=\"Stadium proposal\">{{cite news|title=Stadium proposed to be architecturally unique|newspaper=The Vindicator|date=September 9, 1996|agency=Associated Press|page=D1}}</ref> Demolition work began on the old stadium in November, and the ground-breaking for the new stadium took place the following May.<ref name=\"Stadium groundbreaking\">{{cite news|title=Ceremony kicks off project building phase|newspaper=The Vindicator|date=May 16, 1997|agency=Associated Press|page=C5}}</ref>\n\nAs the stadium's construction got underway, the NFL began to search for an owner for the team, which the league decided would be an expansion franchise March 23, 1998.<ref name=\"Browns to be expansion team\">{{cite news|title=Cleveland rejoices return of Browns|newspaper=Observer-Reporter|date=March 25, 1998|agency=Associated Press|page=C4}}</ref> A litany of potential owners lined up, including Kosar and a group backed partly by [[HBO]] founder Charles Dolan, comedian [[Bill Cosby]] and former Miami coach [[Don Shula]].<ref name=\"Cosby joins Dolans\">{{cite news|title=Cosby joins Dolans in attempt to acquire Browns|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=June 3, 1998|agency=Associated Press|page=33}}</ref><ref name=\"Shula joins ownership group\">{{cite news|last=Affleck|first=John|title=Shula joins Browns group|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=June 16, 1998|agency=Associated Press|page=C\u20136}}</ref> The ultimate winner was Al Lerner, the Baltimore man who had helped Modell in 1986 by buying a small stake in the Browns.<ref name=\"Owner list cut to four\">{{cite news|title=Owner list for Browns cut to four candidates|newspaper=Lawrence Journal-World|date=September 1, 1998|agency=Associated Press|page=6C}}</ref><ref name=\"Lerner wins Browns\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir |first=Richard |title=Lerner Wins Browns for $530 Million |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/09/sports/pro-football-lerner-wins-browns-for-530-million.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Up1RTEd?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/09/sports/pro-football-lerner-wins-browns-for-530-million.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=September 9, 1998 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A seven-member NFL expansion committee awarded the team to Lerner for $530 million in September 1998.<ref name=\"Lerner wins Browns\" /> Lerner, then 65 years old, had a majority share, while [[Carmen Policy]], who helped build the 49ers dynasty of the 1980s, owned 10% of the team and was to run football operations.<ref name=\"Lerner wins Browns\" />\n\n[[File:Browns Stadium-2.jpg|thumb|right|upright=2.0|[[FirstEnergy Stadium]], then known as Cleveland Browns Stadium, in 2006]]\n\nAs the Browns geared up to reactivate, the Browns Trust set up a countdown clock for the team's return<ref name=\"Browns to be expansion team\" /> and used Hall of Famers such as Lou Groza and Jim Brown extensively to promote the team, alongside celebrity fans including [[Drew Carey]].<ref name=\"Browns return rally\">{{cite news|last=Wray|first=Brandon|title=Cleveland holds Browns return rally|newspaper=The Bryan Times|date=August 21, 1998|agency=Associated Press|page=3}}</ref> Lerner and Policy hired [[Dwight Clark]], a former 49ers wide receiver, as the team's operations director in December 1998.<ref name=\"Clark hired\">{{cite news|title=Clark Takes Browns' Reins |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/01/sports/pro-football-clark-takes-browns-reins.html?src=pm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Up4hpyj?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/01/sports/pro-football-clark-takes-browns-reins.html?src=pm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=December 1, 1998 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The owners then signed [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] offensive coordinator [[Chris Palmer (American football)|Chris Palmer]] in January 1999 as the reactivated team's first head coach.<ref name=\"Palmer hired\">{{cite news|title=Browns to name Palmer as coach|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=January 21, 1999|agency=Associated Press|page=4C}}</ref> The NFL then conducted an [[1999 NFL Expansion Draft|expansion draft]] the following month to stock the new Browns team with players.<ref name=\"Expansion draft NYT\">{{cite news|last=Pennington |first=Bill |title=130 Veteran Faces For the Browns |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/16/sports/nfl-roundup-expansion-draft-130-veteran-faces-for-the-browns.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Up7uWCY?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/16/sports/nfl-roundup-expansion-draft-130-veteran-faces-for-the-browns.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=January 16, 1999 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The team added to its roster through free agency,<ref name=\"Free agency signings 1999\">{{cite news|title=Brown inks with Browns|newspaper=Kingman Daily Miner|date=March 4, 1999|agency=Associated Press|page=6}}</ref> and was also given the first pick in the [[1999 NFL Draft|draft]] in April 1999, which it used to draft quarterback [[Tim Couch]].<ref name=\"Couch chosen in 1999\">{{cite news|last=Freeman |first=Mike |title=Couch Gets Squeezed Before First Game |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/19/sports/on-pro-football-couch-gets-squeezed-before-first-game.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UpDK1Ye?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/19/sports/on-pro-football-couch-gets-squeezed-before-first-game.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=April 19, 1999 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nConstruction on the new stadium finished on time in August 1999, paving the way for Cleveland to host a football game for the first time in more than three years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypaper.com/columns/story.asp?id=8519 |title=Welcome to the Big Time |publisher=Citypaper.com |date=September 23, 1998 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UpGmCh7?url=http://www2.citypaper.com/columns/story.asp?id=8519 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=December 2, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During the years after Modell's move and the Browns' suspension, a dozen new stadiums were built for NFL teams. Citing the precedent set by the Browns' relocation, NFL owners used the threat of a move to convince their cities to build new stadiums with public funds.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Katherine C.|last=Leone|title=No Team, No Peace: Franchise Free Agency in the National Football League|journal=[[Columbia Law Review]]|volume=97|issue=2|pages=473\u2013523|year=1997|doi=10.2307/1123368}}</ref>\n\n==Rejoining the NFL (1999\u20132004)==\n\n[[File:Blimp Hall Fame.JPG|thumb|right|The Browns' first pre-season game following reactivation was played at the Pro Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio.]]\n\nCleveland fans' hopes were high upon the arrival of the new team. However, as an expansion team the Browns were forced to build a new roster from scratch using rookies, free agents, and the players other teams chose not to protect in the expansion draft.  With a new team composed of a mix of fresh faces and castoffs, the Browns floundered. The Steelers shut out the Browns 43\u20130 in the season opener at Cleveland Browns Stadium on September 12, 1999, the first of seven straight losses. A 2\u201314 season in 1999 was followed by a 3\u201313 record in 2000 after Couch suffered a season-ending thumb injury. Early in 2001, Policy and Lerner fired Palmer. The coach and the team, Policy said, were not headed in the right direction.<ref name=\"Palmer fired\">{{cite news|title=Palmer fired after 5\u201327 record at helm of Browns |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/news/2001/01/11/browns_palmer_ap/ |publisher=CNNSI.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Upoai9F?url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/news/2001/01/11/browns_palmer_ap/ |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Mike McCarthy (American football)|Mike McCarthy]], New Orleans' offensive coordinator, [[Herman Edwards]], a Tampa Bay assistant coach, and [[Marvin Lewis]], Baltimore's defensive coordinator, were mentioned as possible replacements for Palmer.<ref name=\"Palmer fired\" /> Policy also met with [[Butch Davis]], the head coach of the University of Miami's football team. After rejecting an initial offer in December, Davis accepted the job the following month. Davis had turned around Miami's football program and put the team back in championship contention; Policy and Lerner hoped he could do the same in Cleveland.<ref name=\"Davis hired\">{{cite news|last=Nobles |first=Charlie |title=Browns Hire Miami's Davis To Be Coach |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/01/30/sports/pro-football-browns-hire-miami-s-davis-to-be-coach.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Upqu4rY?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/01/30/sports/pro-football-browns-hire-miami-s-davis-to-be-coach.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=January 30, 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Butch Davis era: 2001\u20132004===\n\nThe Browns improved under Davis, and contended for a spot in the 2001 playoffs until a loss in the 15th week against Jacksonville that featured one of the most controversial calls in team history.<ref name=\"PD on bottlegate\">{{cite news|last=Grossi |first=Tony |title=They can't hold their beer Fans pelt field with bottles after reversal |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/20011216BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UptChpU?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F20011216BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 16, 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref> As time expired in the fourth quarter with the Jaguars ahead 15\u201310, Couch led a drive into Jacksonville territory. On a fourth-down play that the team needed to convert to stay in the game, Couch threw to receiver [[Quincy Morgan]] over the middle. Morgan appeared to bobble the ball before grasping it firmly as he hit the ground. After the pass was ruled complete and Couch spiked the ball to stop the clock, officials reversed Morgan's catch on a Jacksonville challenge. As Davis pleaded his case that the play could not be reviewed because another play had been run, frustrated fans began throwing plastic beer bottles onto the field. Amid the bedlam, later named \"[[bottlegate]]\", officials ended the game with 48 seconds on the clock and left the field as objects rained down on them from the stands.<ref name=\"PD on bottlegate\" /> After most of the fans had left, NFL commissioner [[Paul Tagliabue]] called and ordered the game to be completed. Jacksonville ran down the clock for the win, and the Browns finished the season at 7\u20139.<ref name=\"PD on final 2001 game\">{{cite news|last=Grossi |first=Tony |title=A hot finish to a cold day Offense, Couch steal show with 4th-quarter comeback |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/20011230BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UpwTmFn?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F20011230BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 30, 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCleveland improved again in 2002, but Lerner did not live to see his team make the playoffs. He died in October 2002 at 69 of brain cancer. Browns players wore a patch with the initials \"AL\" for the remainder of the season.<ref name=\"Lerner dies\">{{cite news|title=Browns owner Lerner dies at age of 69|newspaper=The Free Lance-Star|date=October 24, 2002|agency=Associated Press|page=B5}}</ref> Ownership of the team, meanwhile, passed to his son [[Randy Lerner|Randy]].<ref name=\"Randy Lerner takes over\">{{cite news|title=Lerner wasn't typical owner |url=http://cjonline.com/stories/102502/spo_lerner.shtml |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Upyk6F8?url=http://cjonline.com/stories/102502/spo_lerner.shtml |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Topeka Capital-Journal |date=October 25, 2002 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> Cleveland finished the season with a 9\u20137 record, earning a spot in the playoffs as a wild-card team.<ref name=\"Browns last 2002 game\">{{cite news|last=Grossi |first=Tony |title=Browns Stand Strong |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/20021229BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Uq0ps3c?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F20021229BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 29, 2002 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Couch suffered a broken leg in the final game of the season, however, and backup [[Kelly Holcomb]] started in the Browns' first playoff game versus the Steelers. Cleveland held the lead for most of the game as Holcomb passed for 429&nbsp;yards. But a defensive collapse helped Pittsburgh come charging back in the fourth quarter and win 36\u201333 to end the Browns' season.<ref name=\"Browns lose to Steelers, 2002\">{{cite news|last=Grossi |first=Tony |title=Bitter End For Browns |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/20030106BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Uq2gaI8?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F20030106BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=January 6, 2003 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  To date, this is the only postseason appearance for the Browns since resuming operations in 1999.\n\nThe team's progress under Davis screeched to a halt in 2003. The Browns finished 5\u201311, and Randy Lerner embarked upon a major front-office reshuffling.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=115}} Policy resigned unexpectedly as president and chief executive of the Browns in April 2004, saying things had changed after Al Lerner's death. \"I opened the door and it was like someone sucked the air and the life out of Berea\", he said. \"He was a major presence for the organization. I'm talking about the aura, and the inner power of the man.\"<ref name=\"Policy resigns\">{{cite news|title=Browns' Policy stepping aside|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=April 8, 2004|agency=Associated Press|page=C2}}</ref> [[John Collins (sports executive)|John Collins]] was named as his replacement.<ref name=\"Policy resigns\" /> Several other front-office executives also stepped down, including chief contract negotiator Lal Heneghan and lead spokesman Todd Stewart.<ref name=\"Front office firings 2004\">{{cite news|title=Browns fire lead spokesman|newspaper=The Beaufort Gazette|date=July 21, 2004|agency=Associated Press|page=1B}}</ref>\n\nThe 2004 season was little better, and Davis resigned in November with the team at 3\u20138. Lerner had given him a contract extension through 2007 that January, but Davis said \"intense pressure and scrutiny\" made the move necessary.<ref name=\"Davis resigns\">{{cite news|last=Withers |first=Tom |title=Butch Davis resigns as Browns coach |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2004-11-30-davis-resignation_x.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Uq5Wswz?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2004-11-30-davis-resignation_x.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |date=November 30, 2004 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> Offensive coordinator [[Terry Robiskie]] was named head coach for the remainder of the season, which the Browns finished 4\u201312.<ref name=\"Davis resigns\" />\n\n==Struggles and change (2005\u20132012)==\n\n===Savage/Crennel: 2005\u20132008===\n\n[[File:20080728 Braylon Edwards.jpg|thumb|right|Browns wide receiver Braylon Edwards made the Pro Bowl in the 2007 season, along with five other teammates.]]\n\nOn January 6, 2005, while the Browns were still searching for a new head coach, the team announced [[Phil Savage]]'s appointment as general manager.<ref name=\"Savage hired\">{{cite news|title=Browns get their man: Savage hired as GM |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2005-01-07-savage-gm_x.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UqwO1Sy?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2005-01-07-savage-gm_x.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |date=January 7, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Savage, who was director of player personnel for the Baltimore Ravens for two years, had a hand in drafting [[Ed Reed]], [[Jamal Lewis]], [[Ray Lewis]] and other stars for the Ravens.<ref name=\"Savage hired\" />\n\nA month later, Cleveland brought in [[Romeo Crennel]] as the head coach, signing him to a five-year deal worth $11 million. Crennel was the defensive coordinator for the New England Patriots, who had just won the Super Bowl.<ref name=\"Crennel hired\">{{cite news|authorlink=Nick Cafardo|last=Cafardo|first=Nick|title=In love with Romeo|newspaper=Ocala Star-Banner|date=February 9, 2005|page=5C}}</ref> His style was described as \"quiet, reserved and gentlemanly\", but he said he wanted to stock the team with tough, physical players.<ref name=\"Crennel hired\" /> Before the start of training camp, the Browns acquired veteran quarterback [[Trent Dilfer]] from the [[Seattle Seahawks]].<ref name=\"Dilfer trade\">{{cite news|title=Seattle trades Dilfer to Browns for fourth-round draft pick |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/seahawks/2002198274_webhawk05.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UqzmD5j?url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/seahawks/2002198274_webhawk05.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=Seattle Times |date=March 5, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the draft that year the Browns took wide receiver [[Braylon Edwards]] with the third pick in the first round.<ref name=\"Browns take Edwards\">{{cite news|title=Browns to rebuild with Edwards |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2005/football/nfl/specials/draft/2005/04/23/bc.fbn.draft.edwards.ap/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ur4kyVa?url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2005/football/nfl/specials/draft/2005/04/23/bc.fbn.draft.edwards.ap/ |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Sports Illustrated |date=April 23, 2005 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDilfer was the starting quarterback to begin the 2005 season. The team started 2\u20132, but had two three-game losing streaks later in the season and finished with a 6\u201310 record.<ref name=\"2005 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2005 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2005.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ur7F66N?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2005.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the team's final five games, rookie [[Charlie Frye]] took over as the starting quarterback, winning two of those contests. Before the Browns' final regular-season game, the front office was embroiled in a controversy that threatened to send the team into rebuilding mode. Citing sources, ESPN reported that president John Collins was going to fire general manager Phil Savage over \"philosophical differences\" in managing the salary cap.<ref name=\"Savage to be fired\">{{cite news|title=Sources: Browns ready to fire GM Savage |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2275447 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrFGWss?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2275447 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=December 30, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The resulting uproar from fans and local media was so strong that it was Collins who resigned on January 3, 2006.<ref name=\"Collins quits\">{{cite news|title=Browns' Collins quits job in power struggle|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=January 4, 2006|agency=Associated Press|page=C2}}</ref> A replacement for Collins was not immediately named, and Randy Lerner assumed his responsibilities.<ref name=\"Collins quits\" />\n\nCleveland regressed in the ensuing season, finishing with a 4\u201312 record. Edwards and tight end [[Kellen Winslow II|Kellen Winslow Jr.]], who the Browns had drafted in 2004, put up respectable numbers, but the Browns were close to the bottom of the league in points scored and offensive yards gained.<ref name=\"2006 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2006 Cleveland Browns Players & Statistics |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2006.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrQsd1d?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2006.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Frye injured his wrist toward the end of the season and shared starts with quarterback [[Derek Anderson (American football)|Derek Anderson]], who showed promise in the five games he played in.<ref name=\"Frye wrist injury\">{{cite news|title=Frye's wrist may be broken; Taylor, Maroney, Wilson top infirmed list |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2006-12-03-injury-roundup_x.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrTkg5s?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2006-12-03-injury-roundup_x.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |date=December 4, 2006 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> During the season, the team produced a series of articles on its website called ''60th Moments''. The series commemorated the establishment of the Browns 60 years before in 1946, recapturing the 60 greatest moments in franchise history. Beginning on September 6, 2006, the Browns' site ran articles covering those 60 moments; the final article ran on December 31, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|author=King, Steve|date=September 5, 2006|title=Moment 60 \u2013 A new era|url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/article.php?id=5606|work=ClevelandBrowns.com|publisher=Cleveland Browns|accessdate=September 9, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061021103223/http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/article.php?id=5606|archivedate=October 21, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=King, Steve|date=December 31, 2006|title=Moment 1: Dawson's strike|url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/article.php?id=6364|work=ClevelandBrowns.com|publisher=Cleveland Browns|accessdate=September 9, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012155946/http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/article.php?id=6364|archivedate=October 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\nAfter two losing seasons, the Browns made it back to contention in 2007. After opening with a 34\u20137 loss to the Steelers, the Browns traded Frye to the Seahawks and put Anderson in as the starter.<ref name=\"Frye dealt to Seahawks\">{{cite web|title=Browns deal quarterback Frye to Seahawks for draft pick |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3014233 |publisher=ESPN.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrWA83g?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3014233 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In his first start, Anderson led the Browns to a surprise 51\u201345 win over the Cincinnati Bengals, throwing five touchdown passes and tying the franchise record. More success followed, and the Browns finished the regular season with a 10\u20136 record, the team's best mark since finishing 11\u20135 in 1994.<ref name=\"2007 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2007 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2007.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrYi8v2?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2007.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> While the Browns tied with the Steelers for first place in the AFC North, the team missed the playoffs because of two tie-breaking losses to Pittsburgh earlier in the season. Still, six players were selected for the Pro Bowl, including Anderson, Winslow, Edwards, kick returner [[Josh Cribbs]] and rookie left tackle [[Joe Thomas (American football)|Joe Thomas]].<ref name=\"2007 Pro Bowl roster\">{{cite web|title=2007 NFL Pro Bowlers |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2007/probowl.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrbGSUJ?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2007/probowl.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Crennel agreed to a two-year contract extension until 2011,<ref name=\"Crennel contract extension\">{{cite news|last=Withers |first=Tom |title=Browns, Crennel agree on contract extension through 2011 |url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/sports/2008/01/29/browns29.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrdsqW4?url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/sports/2008/01/29/browns29.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=The Columbus Dispatch |date=January 9, 2008 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the team hired Mike Keenan as team president, filling a position left vacant upon the departure of Collins two years before.<ref name=\"Keenan hired\">{{cite news|title=Keenan appointed as Browns team president |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3408378 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrivLK8?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3408378 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=May 22, 2008 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nExpectations were high for the 2008 season, but Cleveland finished last in the AFC North with a 4\u201312 record.<ref name=\"2008 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2008 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2008.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrkmzGL?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2008.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Anderson shared starts with [[Ken Dorsey]], who the Browns had acquired by trading away Trent Dilfer, and [[Brady Quinn]], a young quarterback the team drafted in 2007.<ref name=\"Dorsey to Browns\">{{cite news|title=49ers trade Dorsey to Browns for Dilfer |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2006-05-05-dilfer-trade_x.htm?POE=SPOISVA |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrpgUux?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2006-05-05-dilfer-trade_x.htm?POE=SPOISVA |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |date=May 5, 2006 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Quinn drafted\">{{cite news|last=Fine |first=Larry |title=Quinn gets wish to play for Browns |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/04/28/us-nfl-draft-quinn-idUSL2802480020070428 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ursg6kU?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/04/28/us-nfl-draft-quinn-idUSL2802480020070428 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Reuters |date=April 28, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Browns never contended during 2008 and failed to score a touchdown in the final six games. Near the end of the season, two scandals shook the team. It was revealed that several Browns players, including Winslow, were suffering from [[Staphylococcal infection|staph infections]], which raised questions about sanitation in the Browns' Berea practice facilities.<ref name=\"Staph infection scandal\">{{cite news|last=Lubinger |first=Bill |title=Are staph infections plaguing the Browns? |url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2008/10/are_staph_infections_plaguing.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Urxw80z?url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2008/10/are_staph_infections_plaguing.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=October 20, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In November, Savage found himself in the center of a media storm after an angry e-mail exchange with a fan was published on [[Deadspin]], a sports blog.<ref name=\"Savage Deadspin scandal\">{{cite web|last=Daulerio |first=A.J. |title=Browns' GM Phil Savage Responds To Email Hecklers Swiftly, But Not Very Politely |url=http://deadspin.com/5093632/browns-gm-phil-savage-responds-to-email-hecklers-swiftly-but-not-very-politely-update |publisher=Deadspin.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Us1Cb0L?url=http://deadspin.com/5093632/browns-gm-phil-savage-responds-to-email-hecklers-swiftly-but-not-very-politely-update |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Shortly after the final game, a 31\u20130 loss to the Steelers, Lerner fired Savage and, a day later, Crennel.<ref name=\"Crennel, Savage fired\">{{cite web|title=Crennel fired after Browns' 4-win season |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3797518 |publisher=ESPN.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Us3mPuj?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3797518 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Holmgren/Heckert: 2009\u20132011===\n\nCleveland pursued former Steelers coach and Browns linebacker [[Bill Cowher]] and former Browns scout Scott Pioli for the head coaching job.<ref name=\"Crennel, Savage fired\" /> The team, however, hired former New York Jets coach [[Eric Mangini]] in January 2009.<ref name=\"Mangini hired\">{{cite news|last=Cimini |first=Rich |title=Cleveland Browns hire ex-Jet Eric Mangini as their new head coach |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-01-07/sports/17914557_1_eric-mangini-belichick-coaching-tree-jets |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Us73lV6?url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-01-07/sports/17914557_1_eric-mangini-belichick-coaching-tree-jets |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=New York Daily News |date=January 7, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Before the start of the season, Mangini and the front office traded Winslow to the Buccaneers after five seasons marked by injuries and a motorcycle crash that threatened to end the tight end's career.<ref name=\"Winslow traded\">{{cite news|title=Winslow traded to Bucs for draft picks |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3939777 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Us9WBnE?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3939777 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=February 27, 2009 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Browns showed little sign of improvement in Mangini's first year, finishing 5\u201311 in 2009. While Cleveland lost 11 of its first 12 games, the team won the final four games of the season, including a 13\u20136 victory over the rival Steelers.<ref name=\"2009 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2009 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2009.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsCFgEh?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2009.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the season, Lerner hired former Packers coach [[Mike Holmgren]] as team president, moving Keenan to chief financial officer.<ref name=\"Holmgren hired\">{{cite news|title=Browns Say Holmgren Will Become Team President |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/22/sports/football/22nfl.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsEea8l?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/22/sports/football/22nfl.html?_r=2 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=December 21, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A month later, the owner hired Eagles front-office executive [[Tom Heckert, Jr.|Tom Heckert]] as general manager.<ref name=\"Heckert hired\">{{cite news|title=AP: Browns hiring Eagles' Tom Heckert as GM |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2010-01-10-tom-heckert-eagles_N.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsHqtzs?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2010-01-10-tom-heckert-eagles_N.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |date=January 12, 2010 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> Heckert replaced former general manager [[George Kokinis]], who was fired the previous November. The new management said Mangini would return for a second season.<ref name=\"Heckert hired\" />\n\nUnder Holmgren and Heckert's watch, the Browns overhauled the quarterbacking corps. Brady Quinn was traded to the Denver Broncos for running back [[Peyton Hillis]] in March,<ref name=\"Quinn trade\">{{cite news|title=Quinn sent to Broncos for Hillis, picks |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4995081 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsLHYEx?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4995081 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=March 15, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> while Derek Anderson was released.<ref name=\"Anderson released\">{{cite news|title=Browns release former Pro Bowl QB Derek Anderson |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/03/09/browns-release-qb-derek-anderson/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsNhJR4?url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/03/09/browns-release-qb-derek-anderson/ |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 17, 2012 |newspaper=Fox News |date=March 9, 2010 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> Meanwhile, [[Jake Delhomme]] was acquired from Carolina and Seneca Wallace from Seattle.<ref name=\"Delhomme signs\">{{cite news|last=Chandler |first=Charles |title=Delhomme signs with Browns |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/03/13/387855/delhomme-signs-with-browns.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsRFjwp?url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/03/13/387855/delhomme-signs-with-browns.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=Charlotte News-Observer |date=March 13, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The team also drafted quarterback [[Colt McCoy]] from the [[University of Texas]].<ref name=\"McCoy drafted\">{{cite news|last=Chadiha|first=Jeffri|title=McCoy, Mays among best draft bargains|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft10/columns/story?columnist=chadiha_jeffri&id=5132963|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsUPfrz?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft10/columns/story?columnist=chadiha_jeffri&id=5132963|archivedate=June 17, 2012|accessdate=June 16, 2012|newspaper=ESPN|date=April 24, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> With Delhomme as the starting quarterback, Cleveland lost its first three games and continued to struggle. Wallace started four games, but was replaced by McCoy in the second half of the season. Hillis had a breakout season, rushing for 1,177&nbsp;yards, and was later chosen to appear on the cover of the [[Madden NFL 12]] video game.<ref name=\"Hillis chosen Madden\">{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Craig |title=Voters pick Browns' Hillis for 'Madden NFL 12' cover |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-04-27/tech/hillis.madden.cover_1_madden-curse-michael-vick-madden-nfl?_s=PM:TECH |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsX5vrU?url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-04-27/tech/hillis.madden.cover_1_madden-curse-michael-vick-madden-nfl?_s=PM:TECH |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=CNN |date=April 27, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Despite the emergence of Hillis, the Browns finished with a 5\u201311 record for the second season in a row, and Mangini was fired in January 2011.<ref name=\"Mangini fired\">{{cite news|title=Mangini Fired by Browns After Second Straight 5\u201311 Season |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2011/01/03/mangini-fired-browns-second-straight-season/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsZZb6u?url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2011/01/03/mangini-fired-browns-second-straight-season/ |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=Fox News |date=January 3, 2011 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFollowing Mangini's firing, the Browns named [[Pat Shurmur]] as his replacement. Formerly the offensive coordinator for the [[St. Louis Rams]], Shurmur helped groom quarterback [[Sam Bradford]]. Holmgren and Heckert hoped he could do the same with McCoy.<ref name=\"Shurmur hired\">{{cite news|title=Browns hire Pat Shurmur as coach |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=6018483 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Usbtez9?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=6018483 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=January 13, 2011 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> Contract negotiations between the NFL Players Association and the league shortened the 2011 off-season, which gave Shurmur little time to coach McCoy or institute his version of the [[West Coast offense]].<ref name=\"Shurmur and McCoy\">{{cite news|last=Lankhof |first=Bill |title=Shurmur hopes to turn Browns around |url=https://lfpress.com/sports/football/2011/01/13/16880561.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsfcCqb?url=http://www.lfpress.com/sports/football/2011/01/13/16880561.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=London Free Press |date=January 13, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The team started at 2\u20131, then 3\u20133, but McCoy's struggles and a lack of offensive production led to a series of defeats, including six straight losses to end the year. The Browns finished the season at 4\u201312.<ref name=\"2011 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2011 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2011.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UshkLK2?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2011.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During that same season, comedian and frustrated Browns fan [[Mike Polk]] made a video to complain about the team's futility, screaming \"You are a factory of sadness!\" while facing [[Cleveland Browns Stadium]]. \"Factory of Sadness\" has since become a colloquial nickname for the stadium.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2011/11/cleveland_browns_fans_growing.html | title=Are Cleveland Browns fans at last growing weary of their NFL 'factory of sadness'? | publisher=Cleveland.com | work=The Plain Dealer | date=November 11, 2011 | accessdate=December 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the offseason, Hillis signed as a free agent with the Kansas City Chiefs after a lackluster season and unsuccessful contract talks with the Browns.<ref name=\"Hillis to KC\">{{cite news|last=Teicher |first=Adam |title=Hillis ready to help Chiefs however he can |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d827a1c9a/article/hillis-ready-for-fresh-start-with-chiefs-after-disappointing-year |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsqF4NF?url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d827a1c9a/article/hillis-ready-for-fresh-start-with-chiefs-after-disappointing-year |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 17, 2012 |newspaper=NFL.com |date=May 3, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the [[2012 NFL Draft|2012 draft]], the Browns chose running back [[Trent Richardson]] with the third selection and took quarterback [[Brandon Weeden]] with the 22nd pick. Weeden was expected to replace McCoy at quarterback after McCoy's limited success in one and a half seasons as the starter.<ref name=\"Weeden expected to start\">{{cite news|title=GM expects Brandon Weeden to start |url=http://espn.go.com/dallas/nfl/story/_/id/7957477/cleveland-browns-gm-expecting-brandon-weeden-guy-season |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UstzJXE?url=http://espn.go.com/dallas/nfl/story/_/id/7957477/cleveland-browns-gm-expecting-brandon-weeden-guy-season |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=May 22, 2012 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn September 6, Art Modell died in Baltimore at the age of 87.<ref name=\"Modell AP obit\">{{cite news|last=Ginsburg|first=David|title=Former Ravens owner Art Modell dies at 87|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/former-ravens-owner-art-modell-112143255--nfl.html|accessdate=October 7, 2012|newspaper=Yahoo.com|date=September 6, 2012|agency=Associated Press|location=Baltimore}}</ref> Although the Browns planned to have a moment of silence on their home opener for their former owner, his family asked the team not to, well aware of the less-than-friendly reaction it was likely to get.<ref name=\"Browns cancel Modell silence\">{{cite news|last=Cabot|first=Mary Kay|title=Cleveland Browns cancel Art Modell recognition Sunday at request of Modell family|url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2012/09/cleveland_browns_cancel_their.html|accessdate=October 7, 2012|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 8, 2012}}</ref> Weeden started the Browns' first game of the season. The 28-year-old rookie threw four interceptions in a 17\u201316 loss to Philadelphia in which the Browns' only touchdown was scored by the defense.<ref name=\"Browns first game\">{{cite news|last=Withers|first=Tom|title=Eagles win season opener against Browns, 17\u201316|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wpvi/story?section=news/sports/pro/football&id=8803974|accessdate=October 7, 2012|newspaper=ABC 6 News|date=September 9, 2012|agency=Associated Press|location=Cleveland}}</ref>\n\n==Jimmy Haslam era (2012\u2013present)==\n[[File:Haslam 2012 Sports Awards (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|175px|Current Browns owner [[Jimmy Haslam]]]]\n[[File:Johnny Manziel training camp Browns 2014.jpg|right|thumb|175px|The Browns selected high-profile and controversial quarterback [[Johnny Manziel]] in the first round of the [[2014 NFL draft]] with much fanfare.<br />After two seasons of inconsistent play and numerous off-field incidents, Manziel was waived by the team on March 11, 2016]]\n\nIn July 2012, owner Randy Lerner announced he planned to sell the Browns to businessman [[Jimmy Haslam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d82ad9ba4/article/cleveland-browns-up-for-sale-mike-holmgren-confirms?module=HP11_breaking_news |title=Cleveland Browns up for sale, Mike Holmgren confirms |publisher=Nfl.com |date= |accessdate=June 2, 2013}}</ref> The sale was finalized on August 2, 2012, in excess of $1&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite web|first=Adam|last=Schefter |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/8225861/randy-lerner-sells-cleveland-browns-more-1b-sources-say |title=Randy Lerner sells Cleveland Browns for more than $1B, sources say |publisher=ESPN |date=August 2, 2012 |accessdate=September 3, 2012}}</ref> Haslam officially was approved as the new owner on October 16, 2012, at the NFL owners' meetings, and the very next day former Eagles president [[Joe Banner]] was named as the Browns' new CEO.\n\nThe Browns began the 2012 season by losing their first five games. Having lost their last six games to end the 2011 season, this marked an 11-game losing streak, tied for the longest in team history with the 1974\u20131975 teams.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130120023351/http://www.cleveland.com/ohio-sports-blog/index.ssf/2012/10/cleveland_browns_loseto_the_n_1.html]</ref> On October 12, the Browns defeated the Bengals 34\u201324 in Cleveland, behind two touchdown passes from rookie quarterback [[Brandon Weeden]] (on his 29th birthday) to end the streak. On December 31, 2012, head coach Pat Shurmur and general manager [[Tom Heckert, Jr.|Tom Heckert]] were fired. Shurmur went 9\u201323 in his two seasons as head coach.\n\n===Banner/Lombardi/Chudzinski: 2013===\nAfter interviewing numerous candidates such as [[Chip Kelly]] and [[Ken Whisenhunt]], the Browns decided to hire former offensive coordinator and tight ends coach, [[Rob Chudzinski]], on January 10, 2013.\n\nOn January 15, 2013, Haslam and Banner announced the naming rights to Cleveland Browns Stadium were sold to [[FirstEnergy]], and the stadium would be renamed FirstEnergy Stadium. The name change officially received [[Cleveland City Council]] approval on February 15, 2013.\n\nOn January 18, 2013, the Browns hired [[Michael Lombardi (sportscaster)|Michael Lombardi]] \u2013 who had a previous stint with the Browns in the player personnel department in the 1980s and 90s \u2013 as Vice President of Player Personnel (two months later he was officially given the title of general manager), making him Tom Heckert's replacement.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schudel|first=Jeff|url=http://morningjournal.com/articles/2013/03/06/sports/doc5136b61a5c34b767388986.txt |title=Cleveland Browns name Mike Lombardi General Manager, hire Ray Farmer as Assistant GM |publisher=morningjournal.com |date=March 6, 2013 |accessdate=June 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Browns would finish with a 4\u201312 record in the first season under the new regime, finishing last in the AFC North Division, and losing seven in a row to finish the 2013 campaign. Following the 2013 season finale on December 29, 2013, the Browns fired Chudzinski after only one year as head coach.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sessler|first=Marc|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000305869/article/rob-chudzinski-fired-by-cleveland-browns|title=Rob Chudzinski fired by Cleveland Browns|publisher=[[National Football League]]|date=December 29, 2013|accessdate=December 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Scheiner/Farmer/Pettine: 2014-2015===\nOn January 24, 2014, the Browns hired Bills defensive coordinator [[Mike Pettine]] as the 15th full-time head coach in team history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/10330448/cleveland-browns-tab-mike-pettine-head-coach |title=Cleveland Browns tab Mike Pettine as next coach - ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=January 24, 2014 |accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref> On February 11, 2014 the Browns announced that Lombardi would be replaced by [[Ray Farmer]] as general manager, and that Joe Banner would resign as CEO.<ref name=\"go\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/10435830/cleveland-browns-overhaul-front-office-name-ray-farmer-new-gm |title=Cleveland Browns overhaul front office, name Ray Farmer as new GM |publisher=espn.go.com|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref> In the first round of the [[2014 NFL draft]], the Browns selected [[cornerback]] [[Justin Gilbert]] from [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma State]] with the eighth pick, and Heisman Trophy-winning quarterback [[Johnny Manziel]]  of Texas A&M with the 22nd overall pick.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-nfl-draft-live-20140508-htmlstory.html|title=Browns 2014 draft picks|publisher=[[LA Times]]|accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in the 2014 season, the Browns use a live [[bullmastiff]] named \"Swagger\" as their new mascot.<ref name = \"Swagger\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000364960/article/browns-to-use-live-bullmastiff-swagger-as-mascot|title=Cleveland Browns to Use Live Bullmastiff as Mascot|publisher=[[NFL.com]]|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> On October 5, 2014, the Browns staged the largest rally in team history, when after trailing the [[Tennessee Titans]] 28\u20133 with 1:09 left in the second quarter, Cleveland scored 26 unanswered points to win the game 29\u201328. This was also the largest rally by a road team in NFL history.<ref name=\"go2\">{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=400554204 |title=Browns vs. Titans - Game Recap - October 5, 2014 - ESPN |publisher=scores.espn.go.com|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"twitter\">{{cite tweet|user=NFLhistory|author=NFL History|number=518871685668147200|date=5 October 2014|title=. @Browns' 25-point comeback today is largest in @NFL history by a road team|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref>  After a 7\u20134 start, the Browns would lose their final five games to finish the 2014 season at 7\u20139, last in the AFC North.\n\nIn February 2015, the team made headlines when two high-profile players were in the news due to substance abuse issues. On Monday February 2, it was announced quarterback [[Johnny Manziel]] had checked himself into a treatment center, reportedly for alcoholism. The following day, wide receiver [[Josh Gordon]] was suspended for the 2015 season due to failing a drug test.<ref name=\"espncleveland\">{{cite web|url=http://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=41941 |title=It's time for Browns GM Ray Farmer to face the music and answer some tough questions |publisher=espncleveland.com |accessdate=September 29, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930155325/https://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=41941 |archivedate=September 30, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> On February 28, it was revealed that former [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] quarterback [[Josh McCown]] had signed a three-year deal with the Browns. On March 30, the NFL announced that Browns general manager [[Ray Farmer]] would be suspended for the first four regular season games, and that the team would be fined $250,000 (U.S.) for Farmer text messaging the coaching staff during games in the 2014 season, which is against NFL rules. The story had been dubbed \"Textgate\" due to its scandalous nature.<ref name=\"espncleveland2\">{{cite web|url=http://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=43681 |title=The penalties on the Browns and GM Ray Farmer run deeper than a fine and suspension |publisher=espncleveland.com |accessdate=September 29, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930125814/https://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=43681 |archivedate=September 30, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn April 14 at a ceremony at the [[Huntington Convention Center of Cleveland]], the team unveiled their new uniforms. They feature brown, white, and orange jerseys along with brown, white, and orange pants that can be worn in any combination. Unique features include the word \"Cleveland\" across the front of the jersey, the word \"Browns\" going down the pant leg, and the words \"Dawg Pound\" on the inside collar - all first of their kind features on NFL uniforms. Browns President [[Alec Scheiner]] compared these new jerseys to those of the [[Oregon Ducks football]] team, as the Ducks are known for their various uniform combinations.<ref name=\"espncleveland3\">{{cite web|url=http://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=44131 |title=Browns two-year uniform makeover returns attention now to the team and quarterback |publisher=espncleveland.com |accessdate=September 29, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930130329/https://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=44131 |archivedate=September 30, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2015 NFL draft]], the Browns had two first round picks, selecting [[nose tackle]] [[Danny Shelton]] from [[Washington Huskies football|Washington]] at #12, and [[offensive lineman]] [[Cameron Erving]] from [[Florida State]] at #19.\n\nOn September 8, 2015, the Browns announced that they indefinitely suspended offensive line coach [[Andy Moeller]] after an alleged domestic assault incident at his home during Labor Day weekend. This meant that at the beginning of the 2015 regular season, the team had a player ([[Josh Gordon]]), a coach ([[Moeller]]), and a front office executive ([[Ray Farmer]]) all suspended for various league and legal infractions.<ref name=\"irontontribune\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irontontribune.com/2015/09/08/browns-suspend-moeller |title=Browns suspend Moeller &#124; The Tribune |publisher=irontontribune.com|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref>  Moeller would subsequently be fired on September 29.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsnet5.com/sports/browns/cleveland-browns-and-offensive-line-coach-andy-moeller-agree-to-part-ways|title=Cleveland Browns and offensive line coach Andy Moeller agree to 'part ways'|first=Tim|last=Rearden|date=September 30, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001044214/http://www.newsnet5.com/sports/browns/cleveland-browns-and-offensive-line-coach-andy-moeller-agree-to-part-ways|archivedate=October 1, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter starting 2\u20133, the Browns lost 10 of their last 11 games to finish the 2015 season at 3-13. This stretch included a 33\u201327 home loss to the Baltimore Ravens in which Ravens safety Will Hill return a blocked field goal 64 yards for a touchdown on the game's final play. The Browns lost at home 37\u20133 to the division-rival Cincinnati Bengals the following week, dropping the team's record to 2-10 and making them the first team in the 2015 season to be mathematically eliminated from playoff contention. On January 3, 2016, soon after the final game of the season (a 28\u201312 loss to the Pittsburgh Steelers), both Ray Farmer and Mike Pettine were fired from their respective positions as general manager and head coach.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rosenthal|first=Gregg|title=Cleveland Browns fire Mike Pettine, GM Ray Farmer|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000614532/article/cleveland-browns-fire-general-manager-ray-farmer|publisher=National Football League|date=January 3, 2016|accessdate=January 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Brown/DePodesta/Jackson/Dorsey: 2016-2018===\n [[File:Hue Jackson Browns Mini Camp.png|right|thumb|175px|Former head coach [[Hue Jackson]] won only three out of 40 games with the Browns and posted an 0\u201316 record in 2017]]\nIn January 2016, the Browns made headlines when after firing Farmer and Pettine, promoted general counsel [[Sashi Brown]] to executive vice president of football operations, and hired longtime baseball executive [[Paul DePodesta]] as [[chief strategy officer]]. These moves were viewed nationally as the Browns trying to take a more analytics intensive approach to building the team, taking a page from the \"[[Moneyball]]\" style of [[Major League Baseball]] teams like the [[Oakland Athletics]] - of which DePodesta helped pioneer during his time as an assistant to Athletics general manager [[Billy Beane]]. With Brown essentially taking over general manager duties, this marks the fourth different head of personnel (either as general manager or similar job title) under the Haslam ownership era, which began in 2012.<ref name=\"BrownsHireDePodesta\">{{cite web|title=Paul DePodesta named Browns Chief Strategy Officer|url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-5/Paul-DePodesta-named-Browns-Chief-Strategy-Officer/fffdcf77-786a-441c-ba4d-a715669be515|publisher=Cleveland Browns|date=January 5, 2016|accessdate=January 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109195438/http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-5/Paul-DePodesta-named-Browns-Chief-Strategy-Officer/fffdcf77-786a-441c-ba4d-a715669be515|archive-date=January 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/cleveland-browns/post/_/id/17513/paul-depodesta-takes-browns-from-draft-day-to-moneyball|title=Paul DePodesta takes Browns from 'Draft Day' to 'Moneyball'|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 2016, the Browns hired Bengals offensive coordinator (and former Oakland head coach) [[Hue Jackson]] as head coach - making him the eighth full-time head coach since the team's return in 1999 and fourth since 2012, when the Haslam ownership era began.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cabot|first1=Mary Kay|title=Hue Jackson hired as Cleveland Browns' 8th head coach since 1999|url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2016/01/hue_jackson_named_cleveland_br.html#incart_big-photo|accessdate=January 13, 2016|agency=Cleveland.com|publisher=The Plain Dealer|date=January 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, the Browns hired Andrew Berry\u2014a longtime scout with the [[Indianapolis Colts]]\u2013as vice president of personnel. Berry, being a [[Harvard]] alumnus like DePodesta and Sashi Brown, has been noted as furthering the Browns new analytic approach, and the trio has been dubbed as the \"Harvard Connection\" (and other similar monikers) by local and national media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waitingfornextyear.com/2016/02/wfny-roundtable-cleveland-browns-staff/|title=WFNY Roundtable: Meet the Browns staff|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/cleveland-browns-sashi-brown-paul-depodesta-andrew-berry-harvard-front-office-012816|title=Harvard triumvirate now running the show in Cleveland - FOX Sports|date=January 28, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> On March 4, team president Alex Scheiner announced he would be stepping down from his post effective March 31, and would remain with the team as a consultant for the rest of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14902886/alex-scheiner-resigns-cleveland-browns-president-effective-march-31|title=Browns president Scheiner resigns from post|publisher=}}</ref>  With this move, Paul DePodesta essentially became the top ranked executive of the team in his role as Chief Strategy Officer.<ref name = \"PDP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2016/01/05/cleveland-browns-new-york-mets-paul-depodesta-hired|title=Browns hire Paul DePodesta as executive VP|first=SI|last=Wire|publisher=}}</ref>  This makes DePodesta the fourth different top executive of the team under the Haslams' ownership. On March 11, following two seasons of inconsistent play on the field and numerous highly publicized incidents off the field, the Browns waived quarterback Johnny Manziel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14933932/johnny-manziel-waived-cleveland-browns-tumultuous-two-years|title=Browns part ways with Manziel after two seasons|publisher=}}</ref> On March 24, the Browns signed quarterback [[Robert Griffin III]] to a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/15058201/cleveland-browns-sign-robert-griffin-iii|title=Browns sign RG III as latest quarterback project|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nGoing into the [[2016 NFL Draft]], the Browns had the #2 overall pick.  They traded that pick to Philadelphia in exchange for the #8 pick in the first round (along with various later round 2016 picks, and Philadelphia's first round pick in 2017).  On draft night they traded the #8 pick to Tennessee in exchange for the #15 pick in the first round (and later round picks). With the #15 pick in the 2016 draft, the Browns selected wide receiver [[Corey Coleman]] from [[Baylor University|Baylor]].\n\nThe 2016 season began with the Browns losing their first 14 games, which combined with losing their last three games in 2015, gave the team a franchise record 17 game losing streak.  On December 24, in a game that has since been dubbed \"The Christmas Miracle\", the Browns defeated the [[San Diego Chargers]] 20\u201317.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsnet5.com/sports/browns/a-christmas-miracle-browns-get-first-win-of-the-season-beat-chargers-20-17|title=A Christmas miracle: Browns get first win of the season, beat Chargers 20-17|first=Tom|last=Withers|date=December 24, 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cleveland.cbslocal.com/2016/12/24/browns-hang-on-to-beat-chargers-20-17/|title=A Christmas Miracle: Browns Hang On To Beat Chargers 20-17|first=Daryl |last=Ruiter|publisher=}}</ref> The Browns then lost their last game of the season to finish 1-15 - then the worst record in team history. With that final game loss, the Browns clinched the #1 pick in the [[2017 NFL Draft]], with which the Browns selected [[Myles Garrett]], a [[defensive end]] from [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]].\n\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = vertical\n   | width     = 175\n   | footer    = Hue Jackson's first two seasons, while historically atrocious, netted the Browns two consecutive first overall picks: [[Myles Garrett]] (top) and [[Baker Mayfield]] (bottom)\n   | image1    = Myles_Garrett_2018.jpg\n   | alt1      = \n   | caption1  = \n   | image2    = Baker_Mayfield_training_camp_2018_(2)_(cropped).jpg\n   | alt2      = \n   | caption2  = \n}}\n\nIn the midst of a disappointing 2017 season, Brown was fired as executive vice president of football operations on December 7, 2017,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2017/12/browns_sashi_brown_has_been_fi.html#incart_2box|title=Browns' Sashi Brown has been fired and Hue Jackson will remain as head coach|last1=Cabot|first1=Mary Kay|date=December 7, 2017|publisher=Cleveland.com}}</ref> and hired [[John Dorsey (American football)|John Dorsey]] as general manager the same day, making him the ninth general manager/head of personnel since the Browns' return in 1999, and the fifth in the Haslam ownership era.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-5/Browns-name-John-Dorsey-General-Manager/afd38a04-201f-4f9f-bfb8-88f6aa9f320c|title=Browns name John Dorsey General Manager|date=December 7, 2017|publisher=ClevelandBrowns.com|access-date=May 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208105235/http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-5/Browns-name-John-Dorsey-General-Manager/afd38a04-201f-4f9f-bfb8-88f6aa9f320c|archive-date=December 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/executives.htm Cleveland Browns executives - Pro Football Reference]</ref> The Browns finished the 2017 season with an 0\u201316 record, becoming only the second team in league history to do so,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/amp/news/cleveland-browns-become-second-winless-team-nfl-history/|title=Cleveland Browns become second team in NFL history to go 0-16|accessdate=1 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> and for the second straight season giving the team the #1 pick in the [[2018 NFL Draft]] (along with the #4 pick, which was previously acquired via trade from Houston). Despite the winless season and a 1\u201331 record as head coach of the Browns, Hue Jackson was retained by Haslam.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theringer.com/nfl/2018/1/1/16837862/browns-retain-hue-jackson|title=The Browns Are Retaining the Least Successful Coach in NFL History|date=January 1, 2018|publisher=The Ringer}}</ref> With the first overall pick, the Browns selected former [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]] quarterback and 2017 Heisman Trophy winner [[Baker Mayfield]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2018/04/browns_draft_baker_mayfield_no.html|title=Browns draft Baker Mayfield No. 1 overall in 2018 NFL draft|date=April 27, 2018|publisher=Cleveland.com}}</ref>\n\nDespite Mayfield's status as the #1 overall pick, the Browns began the [[2018 NFL season]] with veteran [[Tyrod Taylor]] as the starting quarterback.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/tyrod-taylor-starter-browns-baker-mayfields-strong-debut/story?id=57147161|title=Tyrod Taylor still starter for Browns, despite Baker Mayfield's strong debut|date=August 12, 2018|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> On opening day, the Browns tied the [[2018 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] 21\u201321 after neither team scored in overtime, ending the Browns' losing streak at 17 games, but extending their winless streak to 18 games. Two weeks later, on September 20, Mayfield entered the game near the end of the first half after Taylor left with a concussion and led the Browns to a 21\u201317 comeback victory over the [[2018 New York Jets season|New York Jets]]  at FirstEnergy Stadium. The victory was the Browns' first since week 16 of the 2016 season, ending their winless streak at 19 games, which was the 4th-longest in NFL history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/20/sports/cleveland-browns-win.html|title=Baker Mayfield Ends Cleveland Browns\u2019 635-Day Winless Streak|date=September 20, 2018|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> Four days later, Jackson announced Mayfield as the Browns' starter for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24783519/baker-mayfield-named-starter-cleveland-browns|title=Baker Mayfield gets starting QB nod for Week 4|date=September 24, 2018|publisher=ESPN.com}}</ref> On October 7, 2018, the Browns defeated the [[2018 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] 12\u20139 in overtime to end an 18-game winless streak against divisional opponents dating back to 2015. After a Week 8 loss to the Pittsburgh Steelers that dropped the Browns to a 2-5-1 record, Hue Jackson was fired as head coach along with offensive coordinator Todd Haley.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000980394/article/browns-fire-hue-jackson-promote-gregg-williams|title=Browns fire Hue Jackson, promote Gregg Williams|date=October 29, 2018|publisher=NFL.com}}</ref> Jackson's final record of 3-36-1 as the Browns' head coach is the worst of any coach's with a single franchise in NFL history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2018/11/1/18048338/hue-jackson-cleveland-browns-coach-tenure-review|title=Review: Hue Jackson\u2019s astoundingly bad tenure with the Browns will never be topped|date=November 1, 2018|publisher=SB Nation}}</ref> Defensive coordinator Gregg Williams was named interim head coach and running backs coach [[Freddie Kitchens]] was named interim offensive coordinator. Their 35\u201320 win over the [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]] at [[Paul Brown Stadium]] on November 25 was the Browns' first win away from home since 2014 and broke a 25-game road losing streak that ranks second all-time in NFL history. Three weeks later, the Browns defeated the [[2018 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] 17\u201316 at [[Broncos Stadium at Mile High]], their first win over Denver since 1990. Following the coaching changes the Browns won five of their remaining eight games to finish the season 7\u20138\u20131, one win shy of having their first winning season since 2007. Mayfield enjoyed a successful rookie season, throwing for 3,725 yards and 27 touchdowns (an NFL record for a rookie quarterback) despite starting only 13 games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001006054/article/baker-mayfield-breaks-rookie-passing-td-record|title=Baker Mayfield breaks rookie passing TD record|date=December 30, 2018|publisher=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===Dorsey/Kitchens: 2019===\n\nOn January 9, 2019, owner Jimmy Haslam and general manager John Dorsey named interim offensive coordinator Freddie Kitchens the 17th head coach of the Cleveland Browns, due in part to the offense's rapid improvement and Baker Mayfield's growth under Kitchens in the second half of the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2019/01/browns-will-name-freddie-kitchens-head-coach-today-per-report.html|title=Freddie Kitchens hired as Cleveland Browns head coach|date=January 9, 2019|publisher=Cleveland.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2019, the Browns acquired Pro Bowl wide receiver [[Odell Beckham Jr.]] and pass rusher [[Olivier Vernon]] in two separate trades with the New York Giants in exchange for offensive guard [[Kevin Zeitler]], safety [[Jabrill Peppers]], and two draft picks, including the Browns' 2019 first-round pick.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/03/08/olivier-vernon-kevin-zeitler-trade-giants-browns|title=Giants Trade Odell Beckham Jr. and Olivier Vernon to Browns|date=March 13, 2019|publisher=Sports Illustrated}}</ref> The trade is widely considered one of the most significant and bizarre in NFL history: the Giants traded Beckham (26 years old on the day of the trade) despite his status as one of the best wide receivers in the NFL only one year after signing him to the largest contract for a wide receiver in NFL history at the time.<ref>\n{{cite news|url=https://www.cleveland.com/sports/2019/03/cleveland-browns-odell-beckham-trade-strange-comments-from-giants-ownership-terry-pluto.html|title=Cleveland Browns: Odell Beckham trade & strange comments from Giants ownership|date=March 31, 2019|publisher=Cleveland.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fancy-stats/wp/2016/11/06/odell-beckham-jr-could-become-the-nfls-best-wide-receiver-ever/|title=Odell Beckham Jr. could become the NFL\u2019s best wide receiver ever|date=November 6, 2016|publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/28/odell-beckham-jr-signs-record-breaking-95-million-deal-with-new-york-giants.html|title=Odell Beckham Jr. signs record-breaking $95 million deal with New York Giants|date=August 28, 2018|publisher=CNBC}}</ref> The move instantly raised expectations for the Browns, with many declaring them a Super Bowl contender despite their recent history and [[List of NFL franchise post-season droughts|16-year playoff drought]], the longest active streak in the NFL.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2825356-the-browns-finally-are-super-bowl-contenders-after-landing-odell-beckham-jr|title=The Browns Finally Are Super Bowl Contenders After Landing Odell Beckham Jr.|date=March 12, 2019|publisher=Bleacher Report}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|2019]] season would be a disaster for the Browns as they finished with a record of 6\u201310. With that record, combined with many numerous discipline problems from both on and off the field plus poor play, the Cleveland Browns fired Freddie Kitchens hours after the Browns' loss to the Cincinnati Bengals on December 29. Two days later, the Browns also parted ways with general manager John Dorsey after disagreements with discussions about structural reformations of the team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001093675/article/browns-part-ways-with-general-manager-john-dorsey|title=Browns part ways with general manager John Dorsey|date=December 31, 2019|publisher=NFL.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28400906/john-dorsey-browns-general-manager|title=John Dorsey out as Browns general manager|date=December 31, 2019|publisher=espn.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|American football|Sports}}\n* [[List of Cleveland Browns seasons]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bowden|first=Mark|year=2008|title=The Best Game Ever: Giants vs. Colts, 1958, and the Birth of the Modern NFL|publisher=Atlantic Monthly Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-87113-988-7|ref={{sfnRef|Bowden|2008}}|url=https://archive.org/details/bestgameevergian00bowd}}\n* {{cite book|last=Boyer|first=Mary Schmitt|year=2006|title=Browns Essential|publisher=Triumph Books|location=Chicago|isbn=978-1-57243-873-6|ref={{sfnRef|Boyer|2006}}|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/brownsessentiale0000boye}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cantor|first=George|year=2008|title=Paul Brown: The Man Who Invented Modern Football|publisher=Triumph Books|location=Chicago|isbn=978-1-57243-725-8|ref={{sfnRef|Cantor|2008}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Coughlin|first=Dan|year=2011|title=Pass the Nuts: More Stories About the Most Unusual People and Remarkable Events from My Four Decades As a Sports Journalist|isbn=978-1-59851-073-7|ref={{sfnRef|Coughlin|2011}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Dyer|first=Bob|year=2007|title=The Top 20 Moments in Cleveland Sports: Tremendous Tales of Heroes and Heartbreaks|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-59851-030-0|ref={{sfnRef|Dyer|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Felser|first=Larry|year=2008|title=The Birth of the New NFL: How the 1966 NFL/AFL Merger Transformed Pro Football|publisher=Lyons Press|location=Guilford, Connecticut|isbn=1-59921-151-3|ref={{sfnRef|Felser|2008}}|url=https://archive.org/details/birthofnewnflhow00fels}}\n* {{cite book|last=Felton|first=Bruce|year=2007|title=What Were They Thinking?, New and Revised: Really Bad Ideas Throughout History|publisher=The Lyons Press|location=Guilford, Connecticut|isbn=1-59921-132-7|ref={{sfnRef|Cantor|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Freeman|first=Mike|year=2007|title=Jim Brown: The Fierce Life of an American Hero|publisher=It Books|location=New York|isbn=0-06-077683-8|ref={{sfnRef|Freeman|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Gordon|first=Roger|year=2002|title=Cleveland Browns A-Z|publisher=Sports Publishing LLC|location=Champaign, Illinois|isbn=978-1-58261-240-9 |ref={{sfnRef|Gordon|2002}} }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Gregg|first1=Forrest|authorlink1=Forrest Gregg|last2=O'Toole|first2=Andrew|year=2009|title=Winning in the Trenches: A Lifetime of Football|publisher=Clerisy Press|location=Covington, Kentucky|isbn=1-57860-363-3|ref={{sfnRef|Gregg|2009}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Grossi|first=Tony|year=2004|title=Tales From the Browns Sideline|publisher=Sports Publishing LLC|location=Champaign, Illinois|isbn=978-1-58261-713-8 |ref={{sfnRef|Grossi|2004}} }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Groza|first1=Lou|authorlink1=Lou Groza|last2=Hodermarsky|first2=Mark|year=2003|title=The Toe: The Lou Groza Story|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-886228-80-1|ref={{sfnRef|Groza|2003}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|year=2007|title=Browns Scrapbook: A Fond Look Back at Five Decades of Football, from a Legendary Cleveland Sportswriter|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-59851-043-0|ref={{sfnRef|Heaton|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Henkel|first=Frank M.|year=2005|title=Cleveland Browns History|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=Mount Pleasant, South Carolina|isbn=978-0-7385-3428-2 |ref={{sfnRef|Henkel|2005}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Hollander|first=Zander|year=1983|title=Strange But True Football Stories|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=978-0-394-80198-8|ref={{sfnRef|Hollander|1983}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Holley|first=Michael|year=2011|title=War Room: The Legacy of Bill Belichick and the Art of Building the Perfect Team|publisher=It Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0-06-208239-8|ref={{sfnRef|Holley|2011}}|url=https://archive.org/details/warroomlegacyofb00holl_0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Knight|first=Jonathan|year=2003|title=Kardiac Kids: The Story of the 1980 Cleveland Browns|publisher=Kent State University Press|location=Kent, Ohio|isbn=0-87338-761-9|ref={{sfnRef|Knight|2003}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Knight|first=Jonathan|year=2006|title=Sundays in the Pound: The Heroics and Heartbreak of the 1985\u201389 Cleveland Browns|publisher=Kent State University Press|location=Kent, Ohio|isbn=978-0-87338-866-5|ref={{sfnRef|Knight|2006}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Lebovitz|first=Hal|authorlink=Hal Lebovitz|year=2006|title=The Best of Hal Lebovitz: Great Sportswriting from Six Decades in Cleveland|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-59851-023-2|ref={{sfnRef|Lebovitz|2006}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Maraniss|first=David|year=2000|title=When Pride Still Mattered : A Life Of Vince Lombardi|url=https://archive.org/details/whenpridestillma00mara|url-access=registration|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=978-0-684-87018-2|ref={{sfnRef|Maraniss|2000}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Maxymuk|first=John|year=2007|title=Strong Arm Tactics: A Historical and Statistical Analysis of the Professional Quarterback|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|isbn=978-0-7864-3277-6|ref={{sfnRef|Maxymuk|2007}}|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786432776}}\n* {{cite book|last=Miller|first=Jeff|year=2004|title=Going Long : The Wild Ten Year Saga of the Renegade American Football League in the Words of Those Who Lived It|publisher=McGraw-Hill|location=New York|isbn=978-0-07-144154-4|ref={{sfnRef|Miller|2004}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Miller|first=Jeffrey|year=2007|title=Rockin' the Rockpile: The Buffalo Bills of the American Football League|publisher=ECW Press|location=Toronto|isbn=978-1-55022-797-0|ref={{sfnRef|Miller|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Morgan|first=Jon|year=1997|title=Glory for Sale: Fans, Dollars and the New NFL|publisher=Bancroft Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-0-9631246-5-4|ref={{sfnRef|Morgan|1997}} }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Neft|first1=David S.|last2=Cohen|first2=Richard M.|last3=Korch|first3=Rick|year=1994|title=The Football Encyclopedia: The Complete History of Professional Football from 1892 to the Present|publisher=St. Martin's Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-312-11435-0|ref={{sfnRef|Neft|1994}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Page|first=Joseph S.|year=2010|title=Pro Football Championships Before the Super Bowl: A Year-by-Year History, 1926\u20131965 |publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|isbn=978-0-7864-4809-8|ref={{sfnRef|Page|2010}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Peterson|first=Robert W.|year=1997|title=Pigskin: The Early Years of Pro Football|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-511913-8|ref={{sfnRef|Peterson|1997}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Piascik|first=Andy|year=2007|title=The Best Show in Football: The 1946\u20131955 Cleveland Browns|publisher=Taylor Trade Publishing|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=978-1-58979-571-6|ref={{sfnRef|Piascik|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Pluto|first=Terry|authorlink=Terry Pluto|year=1997|title=Browns Town 1964: Cleveland Browns and the 1964 Championship|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-886228-72-6|ref={{sfnRef|Pluto|1997}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Pluto|first=Terry|year=2010|title=Things I've Learned from Watching the Browns|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-59851-065-2|ref={{sfnRef|Pluto|2010}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Schwarz|first=Ted|year=2010|title=Shocking Stories of the Cleveland Mob|publisher=The History Press|location=Charleston, South Carolina|isbn=978-1-59629-918-4|ref={{sfnRef|Schwarz|2010}} }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/ Cleveland Browns official web site]\n\n{{Cleveland Browns}}\n{{NFL team history}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Cleveland Browns}}\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns]]\n[[Category:National Football League history by team|Cleveland Browns]]\n[[Category:History of Cleveland|Browns]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sports team history}}\n{{good article}}\n[[File:Cleveland Browns game program, September 1946.png|250px|thumb|right|Game program depicting the [[Brownie (folklore)|Brownie elf]], the team's primary mascot in its successful early years. From the Browns' first game on September 6, 1946 against the [[Miami Seahawks]].]]\n\nThe '''history of the Cleveland Browns''' [[American football]] team began in 1944  when taxi-cab magnate [[Arthur B. McBride|Arthur B. \"Mickey\" McBride]] secured a [[Cleveland, Ohio]] franchise in the newly formed [[All-America Football Conference]] (AAFC). [[Paul Brown]], who coach [[Bill Walsh (American football coach)|Bill Walsh]] once called the \"father of modern football\",{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=v}} was the team's namesake and first coach. From the beginning of play in 1946 at [[Cleveland Municipal Stadium]], the Browns were a great success. Cleveland won each of the AAFC's four championship games before the league dissolved in 1949. The team then moved to the more established [[National Football League]] (NFL), where it continued to dominate. Between 1950 and 1955, Cleveland reached the [[History of National Football League Championship|NFL championship game]] every year, winning three times.\n\nMcBride and his partners sold the team to a group of Cleveland businessmen in 1953 for a then-unheard-of $600,000. Eight years later, the team was sold again, this time to a group led by New York advertising executive [[Art Modell]]. Modell fired Brown before the 1963 season, but the team continued to win behind running back [[Jim Brown]]. The Browns won the [[1964 NFL Championship Game|championship]] in 1964 and reached the [[1965 NFL Championship Game|title game]] the following season, losing to the [[Green Bay Packers]]. The team subsequently reached the playoffs three times in the late 1980s, but fell short of playing in the [[Super Bowl]], the inter-league championship game between the NFL and the rival [[American Football League]] (AFL) that started in 1966.\n\nWhen the AFL and NFL [[AFL\u2013NFL merger|merged]] before the 1970 season, Cleveland became part of the new [[American Football Conference]] (AFC). While the Browns made it back to the playoffs in 1971 and 1972, they fell into mediocrity through the mid-1970s. A revival of sorts took place in 1979 and 1980, when quarterback [[Brian Sipe]] engineered a series of last-minute wins and the Browns came to be called the \"[[Kardiac Kids]]\". Under Sipe, however, the Browns did not make it past the first round of the playoffs. Quarterback [[Bernie Kosar]], who the Browns drafted in 1985, led the team to three [[AFC Championship game]]s in the late 1980s but lost each time. In 1995, Modell announced he was relocating the Browns to [[Baltimore]], sowing a mix of outrage and bitterness among Cleveland's dedicated fan base. Negotiations and legal battles led to an agreement where Modell was allowed to move the team, but Cleveland kept the Browns' name, colors and history. After three years of suspension while the old municipal stadium was demolished and [[Cleveland Browns Stadium]] took its place, the Browns started play again in 1999 under new owner [[Al Lerner]]. Since resuming operations, the Browns have made the playoffs only once, as a [[Wild card (sports)#National Football League|wild-card team]] in 2002.\n\nThe Browns are only one of 12 NFL franchises to predate the 1960 launch of the [[American Football League]], and are only one of three such teams in the AFC.\n\n==Founding and dominance in the AAFC (1946\u20131949)==\n\n[[File:Paul Brown, American football head coach.png|thumb|right|alt=Cleveland Browns coach Paul Brown stands on the sideline.|Paul Brown, the Browns' namesake and first coach, liked his players \"lean and hungry.\"{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=45}}]]\n\nIn 1944 [[Arch Ward]], the influential sports editor of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', proposed a new professional football league called the All-America Football Conference.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=7}} The AAFC was to challenge the dominant National Football League once it began operations at the end of World War II, which had forced many professional teams to curtail activity, merge or go on hiatus as their players served in the [[United States Armed Forces|U.S. military]].{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=8}} It was a bold proposition, given the failure of three previous NFL competitors and the dominance of college football, which was more popular than the professional game at the time.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=6\u20138}} Ward, who had gained fame and respect for starting all-star games for baseball and college football, lined up deep-pocketed owners for the new league's eight teams in hopes of giving it a better chance against the NFL.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=5\u20139}} One of them was Arthur B. \"Mickey\" McBride, a Cleveland businessman who grew up in Chicago and knew Ward from his involvement in the newspaper business.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=11\u201312}} McBride spent his early career as a circulation manager for the ''[[Cleveland News]]'', and went into business for himself in the 1930s, buying  a pair of Cleveland taxi companies and running a wire service that supplied [[Bookmaker|bookies]] with information about the results of horse races.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=11\u201312}} He had connections to [[organized crime in Chicago]] and Cleveland arising from the wire service.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=11\u201312}}{{sfn|Schwarz|2010|p=85}}\n\nMcBride developed a passion for football attending games at [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]], where his son went to college.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=11}} In the early 1940s he tried to buy the NFL's [[Cleveland Rams]], owned by millionaire supermarket heir [[Dan Reeves (NFL owner)|Dan Reeves]], but was rebuffed.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=11}} Having been awarded the Cleveland franchise in the AAFC, McBride asked ''[[Cleveland Plain Dealer]]'' sportswriter John Dietrich for head coaching suggestions.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=12}} Dietrich recommended Paul Brown, the 36-year-old [[Ohio State Buckeyes]] coach.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=12}} After consulting with Ward, McBride followed Dietrich's advice in early 1945, naming Brown head coach and giving him an ownership stake in the team and full control over player personnel.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=11\u201312}} Brown, who had built an impressive record as coach of a [[Massillon Washington High School|Massillon, Ohio high school]] team and brought the Buckeyes their first national championship, at the time was serving in the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] and coached the football team at [[Naval Station Great Lakes|Great Lakes Naval Station]] near [[Chicago]].{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=13\u201317}}\n\nThe name of the team was at first left up to Brown, who rejected calls for it to be christened the Browns.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=10}} McBride then held a contest to name the team in May 1945; \"Cleveland Panthers\" was the most popular choice, but Brown rejected it because it was the name of an [[Cleveland Panthers|earlier failed football team]]. \"That old Panthers team failed\", Brown said. \"I want no part of that name.\"{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=77}} In August, McBride gave in to popular demand and named the team the Browns, despite Paul Brown's objections.{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=76}}\n\nFor several years, Brown he would occasionally cite an alternate history of the team name. He claimed that the second name-the-team contest yielded the name \"Brown Bombers,\" after then-world heavyweight boxing champion [[Joe Louis]], whose nickname was \"The Brown Bomber.\" According to this version, Brown wanted his team to have a nickname befitting a champion, and felt the nickname \"Brown Bombers\" was apropos. The name was reportedly shortened to simply \"Browns.\" This alternate history of the name was even supported by the team as being factual as recently as the mid-1990s,<ref>{{cite book |title=The Name Game: Football, Baseball, Hockey & Basketball How Your Favorite Sports Teams Were Named |last=Donovan |first=Michael Leo |authorlink= |year=1997 |publisher=Warwick Publishing |location=[[Toronto]] |isbn=1-895629-74-8 |pages= }}</ref> and it continues as an [[urban legend]] to this day. However, Paul Brown never held fast to the Joe Louis story, and later in his life admitted that it was invented in part because of his wariness of having the team being named after him. The Browns and the NFL now both support the position that the team was indeed named after Paul Brown.<ref name=\"latimesblogs.latimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/sports_blog/2011/12/were-the-cleveland-browns-named-after-boxer-joe-louis.html|title=Sports news from Los Angeles and beyond|publisher=latimesblogs.latimes.com|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Franchise nicknames|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/news/franchise-nicknames/|publisher=[[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]|accessdate=April 8, 2016|quote=The Cleveland All-America Football Conference franchise conducted a fan contest in 1945 to name the team. The most popular submission was \"Browns\" in recognition of the team's first coach and general manager Paul Brown, who was already a popular figure in Ohio sports. Brown at first vetoed the choice and the team selected from the contest entries the name \"Panthers.\" However, after an area businessman informed the team that he owned the rights to the name Cleveland Panthers, from an earlier failed football team, Brown rescinded his objection and agreed to the use of his name.}}</ref>\n\nAs the war began to wind down with [[German Instrument of Surrender|Germany's surrender]] in May 1945, the team parlayed Brown's ties to college football and the military to build its roster.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=16\u201318}} The first signing was [[Otto Graham]], a former star quarterback at [[Northwestern University]] who was then serving in the Navy.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=19}} The Browns later signed kicker and offensive tackle [[Lou Groza]] and wide receivers [[Dante Lavelli]] and [[Mac Speedie]].{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=21\u201323}} Fullback [[Marion Motley]] and nose tackle [[Bill Willis]], two of the earliest [[African-American]]s to play professional football, also joined the team in 1946.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=29\u201330}} Cleveland's first training camp took place at [[Bowling Green State University|Bowling Green University]] in northwestern Ohio.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=28}} Brown's reputation for winning notwithstanding, joining the team was a risk; the Browns and the AAFC were nascent entities and faced tough competition from the NFL. \"I just went up there to see what would happen\", center [[Frank Gatski]] said many years later.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=28}}\n\nCleveland's first regular-season game took place September 6, 1946 at Cleveland Municipal Stadium against the [[Miami Seahawks]] before a then-record crowd of 60,135.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=45\u201346}} That contest, which the Browns won 44\u20130, kicked off an era of dominance. With Brown at the helm, the team won all four of the AAFC's championships from 1946 until its dissolution in 1949, amassing a record of 52 wins, four losses and three ties.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=123\u2013150}} This included the 1948 season, in which the Browns became the first unbeaten and untied team in professional football history.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=105\u2013186}} The Browns had few worthy rivals among the AAFC's eight teams, but the [[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]] and [[San Francisco 49ers]] were their closest competition.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2007|p=102}}\n\nWhile the Browns excelled on defense, Cleveland's winning ways were driven by an offense that employed Brown's version of the [[T formation]], which emphasized speed, timing and execution over set plays.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2007|p=102}} Brown liked his players \"lean and hungry\", and championed quickness over bulk.{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=45}} Graham became a star under Brown's system, leading all passers in each of the AAFC's seasons and racking up 10,085 passing yards.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2007|p=103}} Motley, who Brown in 1948 called \"the greatest fullback that ever lived\",<ref name=\"Brown says 1948 team best yet\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Harry|title=Brown Calls His First Unbeaten and Untied Team Since '40 His Best Yet|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 20, 1948|page=23|quote=[Brown said:] 'How that boy can run I think he's the greatest fullback that ever lived&nbsp;... Did you ever see a fullback who runs like a halfback in an open field?'}}</ref> was the AAFC's all-time leading rusher.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=149\u2013150}} Brown and six players from the Browns' AAFC years were later elected to the Pro Football Hall of Fame: Graham, Motley, Groza, Lavelli, Willis and Gatski.<ref name=\"Cleveland hall of fame members\">{{cite web|title=Franchises |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/teams.aspx |publisher=Pro Football Hall of Fame |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UNa2PFX?url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/teams.aspx |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 11, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Cleveland area showered support on the Browns from the outset.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=13\u201316}} Meanwhile, the Browns unexpectedly had Cleveland to themselves; the NFL's Cleveland Rams, who had continually lost money despite winning the [[1945 NFL Championship Game|1945 NFL championship]], moved to Los Angeles after that season.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=14}} The Browns' on-field feats only amplified their popularity, and the team saw average attendance of 57,000 per game in its first season.{{sfn|Neft|1994|p=194}} The Browns, however, became victims of their own success. Cleveland's dominance exposed a lack of balance among AAFC teams, which the league tried to correct by sending Browns players including quarterback [[Y. A. Tittle]] to the [[Baltimore Colts (1947\u20131950)|Baltimore Colts]] in 1948.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=108\u2013109}} Attendance at Browns games fell in later years as fans lost interest in lopsided victories, while attendance for less successful teams fell even more precipitously.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=137\u2013138}} The Browns led all of football during the undefeated season in 1948 with an average crowd of 45,517, but that was more than 10,000 less than the average per game the previous year.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=119}} These factors \u2013 combined with a war for players between the two leagues that raised salaries and ate into owners' profits \u2013 ultimately led to the dissolution of the AAFC and the merger of three of its teams, including the Browns, into the NFL in 1949.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=123\u2013150}} The NFL does not acknowledge AAFC statistics and records because these achievements \u2013 including the Browns' perfect season \u2013 did not take place in the NFL or against NFL teams, and not in a league fully absorbed by the NFL.<ref name=\"AAFC records unrecognized\">{{cite web|last=Grossi |first=Tony |title=1948 Cleveland Browns still lacking NFL respect |url=http://blog.cleveland.com/sports/2008/02/1948_cleveland_browns_still_la.html |publisher=cleveland.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UNk95vf?url=http://blog.cleveland.com/sports/2008/02/1948_cleveland_browns_still_la.html |archivedate=17 June 2012 |accessdate=May 11, 2012 |date=15 February 2008 |quote=NFL Vice President Joe Browne stated that going undefeated and untied was 'a sterling achievement,' but 'it was not achieved in the NFL nor against NFL teams, nor in a league which became in its entirety part of the NFL.' 'As such,' Browne wrote, 'our historians believe it is appropriate that it not be part of the official NFL records.' |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Success and challenges in the NFL (1950\u20131956)==\n\n[[File:Lou Groza and Arthur B. McBride after a game in 1950.jpg|thumb|right|Lou Groza and owner Mickey McBride after a December 1950 playoff game against the New York Giants. Groza's kicking played a major role in the team's first NFL championship.]]\n\nThe AAFC proposed match-ups with NFL teams numerous times during its four-year existence, but no inter-league game ever materialized.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=10\u201311}} That made Cleveland's entry into the NFL in the 1950 season the first test of whether its early supremacy could continue into a more established league.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=160\u2013165}} The proof came quickly: Cleveland's NFL regular-season opener was against the two-time defending champion [[Philadelphia Eagles]] on September 16 in Philadelphia.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=163}} The Browns lit up the Eagles' vaunted defense for 487 total yards\u2014including 246 passing yards from Graham and his receivers\u2014in a 35\u201310 win before a crowd of 71,237.  This decisive win quashed any doubts about the Browns' prowess.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=163\u2013166}} Behind an offense that featured Graham, Groza, Motley, Lavelli and running back [[Dub Jones (American football)|Dub Jones]], Cleveland finished the 1950 season with a 10\u20132 record, tied for first place in the Eastern Conference.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=151\u2013176}} After winning a playoff game against the [[New York Giants]], the Browns advanced to the [[1950 NFL Championship Game|NFL championship match]] against the [[History of the Los Angeles Rams|Los Angeles Rams]] in Cleveland. The Browns won 30\u201328 on a last-minute Groza field goal.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=176\u2013184}} Fans stormed the field after the victory, carting off the goalposts, ripping off one player's jersey and setting a bonfire in the bleachers.<ref name=\"Browns win 1950 championship\">{{cite news|last=Jones |first=Harry |title=Groza's Field Goal Is Signal for Celebration |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19501224BROWNS.html |accessdate=May 12, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UO6ayQb?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19501224BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 24, 1950 |quote=The moment Lou Groza's 16-yard field goal cleared the crossbar in the last 20 seconds of what may well be the greatest gridiron spectacle in Cleveland history, 29,751 citizens went berserk at the stadium. |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"It was the greatest game I ever saw\", Brown later said.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=182}}\n\n{{quote box\n |quote= Show me another guy who toes a<br>Football as neatly as Lou Groza\n |source=\u2013 [[Doggerel]] signed \"Hoosier Pick\", 1946.<br>Groza's nickname was \"The Toe.\"<ref name=\"Groza quote\">{{cite news|last=Doyle|first=James E.|title=The Sport Trail|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 2, 1946|page=25}}</ref>\n |align=left\n |border=2\n}}\n\nAfter five straight championship wins in the AAFC and NFL, the Browns appeared poised to bring another trophy home in 1951. The team finished the regular season with 11 wins and a single loss in the first game of the season.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=223\u2013230}} Cleveland faced the Rams on December 23 in a [[1951 NFL Championship Game|rematch]] of the previous year's title game.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=231}} The score was deadlocked 17\u201317 in the final period, but a 73-yard touchdown pass by Rams quarterback [[Norm van Brocklin]] to wide receiver [[Tom Fears]] broke the tie and gave Los Angeles the lead for good. The 24\u201317 loss was the Browns' first in a championship game.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=231\u2013235}}\n\nThe 1952 and 1953 seasons followed a similar pattern: Cleveland reached the championship game but lost both times to the [[Detroit Lions]].{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=237\u2013286}} In 1952's [[1952 NFL Championship Game|championship game]], Detroit won 17\u20137 after a [[muffed punt]] by the Browns, several Lions defensive stands and a 67-yard touchdown run by [[Doak Walker]] scuttled Cleveland's chances.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=237\u2013254}} The team finished 11\u20131 in 1953, but lost the [[1953 NFL Championship Game|championship]] to the Lions 17\u201316 on a 33-yard [[Bobby Layne]] touchdown pass to [[Jim Doran]] with just over two minutes left.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=263\u2013286}} While the championship losses disappointed Cleveland fans who had grown accustomed to winning, the team continued to make progress. [[Len Ford]], who the Browns picked up from the defunct AAFC's [[Los Angeles Dons]] team, emerged as a force on the defensive line, making the [[Pro Bowl]] each year between 1951 and 1953.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=153\u2013154}} Second-year wideout [[Ray Renfro]] became a star in 1953, also reaching the Pro Bowl.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=237\u2013272}}\n\n[[File:Dave Jones hands Arthur McBride a check, 1953.jpg|thumb|left|Dave Jones hands a check for $250,000 to Arthur B. \"Mickey\" McBride as a down payment on the purchase of the Browns for $600,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cleveland Memory|url=http://images.ulib.csuohio.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/press&CISOPTR=6931&CISOBOX=1&REC=1|publisher=Cleveland Memory Project|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UOPYWPY?url=http://images.ulib.csuohio.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=%2Fpress&CISOPTR=6931&CISOBOX=1&REC=1|archivedate=June 17, 2012|accessdate=June 11, 2012|quote=COOL QUARTER OF A MILLION dollars changed hands today when Dave Jones, new president of the Cleveland Browns, presented a $250,000 check to Arthur B. McBride to complete purchase of the team. Looking on are Homer Marshman (left), secretary and general counsel; Saul Silberman, chairman of the executive committee, and former vice president Edward McBride. Mickey also received a lifetime pass to all Brown home games 'in appreciation of his contribution to Cleveland professional football.' \u2013 photo verso|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\n\nDuring the summer before the 1953 season, the Browns' original owners sold the team for a then-unheard-of $600,000.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=264}} The buyers were a group of prominent Cleveland men: Dave R. Jones, a businessman and former [[Cleveland Indians]] director, [[Ellis Ryan]], a former Indians president, [[Homer Marshman]], an attorney, and Saul Silberman, owner of the Randall Park race track.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=264\u2013265}} McBride had been called in 1950 to testify before the [[United States Senate Special Committee to Investigate Crime in Interstate Commerce|Kefauver Committee]], a congressional body investigating organized crime, which partly exposed his ties to mafia figures but did not result in any charges.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=264}} While McBride never said so, the Kefauver hearings and the growing public association between him and the mafia may have played a role in his decision to get out of football.{{sfn|Schwarz|2010|p=85}}\n\nWhile the Browns came into 1954 as one of the top teams in the NFL, the future was far from certain. Graham, whose leadership and throwing skills were instrumental in the Browns' championship runs, said he planned to retire after the season.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=310}} Motley, the team's best rusher and blocker, retired at the beginning of the season with a bad knee.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=306}} Star [[defensive lineman]] Bill Willis also retired before the season.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=306}} Still, Cleveland finished the regular season 9\u20133{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=305\u2013326}} and met Detroit the day after Christmas in the [[1954 NFL Championship Game|championship game]] for a third consecutive time.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=317\u2013326}} This time Cleveland dominated on both sides of the ball, intercepting Bobby Layne six times while Graham threw three touchdowns and ran for three more.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=317\u2013326}} The Browns, who lost the last game of the regular season to the Lions only a week before, won their second NFL championship 56\u201310.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=317\u2013326}} \"I saw it, but still hardly can believe it\", Lions coach [[Buddy Parker]] said after the game. \"It has me dazed.\"<ref name=\"Browns win 1954 championship\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns Regain Title, 56 to 10 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19541226BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UOfTvFW?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19541226BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 12, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 26, 1954 |quote=Down and being counted out only seven days back, the Cleveland Browns unloaded years of pent-up frustration on the Detroit Lions yesterday at the stadium to take over as the new champions of the National Football League. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCleveland's success continued in 1955 after Brown convinced Graham to come back, arguing that the team lacked a solid alternative.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=332}} Cleveland finished the regular season 9\u20132\u20131 and went on to win its third [[1955 NFL Championship Game|NFL championship]], beating the Los Angeles Rams 38\u201314.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=338\u2013344}} It was Graham's last game; the win capped a 10-year run in which he led his team to the league championship every year, winning four in the AAFC and three in the NFL.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|pp=342\u2013344}} Rams fans gave Graham a standing ovation when Brown pulled him from the game in the final minutes.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=342}}\n\nWithout Graham, the Browns floundered in 1956.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=366}} Injuries to two Browns quarterbacks left the relatively unknown [[Tommy O'Connell]] as the starter, and Cleveland finished with a 5\u20137 record, its first losing season.{{sfn|Peterson|1997|p=118}} Dante Lavelli and Frank Gatski retired at the end of the season, leaving Groza as the only original Browns player still on the team.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=366}} While the Browns' on-field play in 1956 was uninspiring, off-the-field drama developed after a Cleveland-based inventor let Brown test a helmet with a radio transmitter inside.{{sfn|Peterson|1997|p=118}} After trying it out in training camp, Brown used the helmet to call plays during the pre-season with long-time backup [[George Ratterman]] behind center. The device allowed the coach to direct his quarterback on the fly, giving him an advantage over franchises who had to use messenger players to relay instructions.{{sfn|Hollander|1983|p=60\u201363}} The Browns used the device off and on into the regular season, and other teams began to experiment with their own radio helmets.{{sfn|Felton|2007|pp=133\u2013134}} [[Bert Bell]], the [[NFL commissioner]], banned the device in October 1956.<ref name=\"Radio helmet banned\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|title=Silencer Put On Radio Helmets|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=October 19, 1956|page=33|quote=Ban of radio or any form of electronic equipment in the helmets of professional girders was announced in Philadelphia by Commissioner Bert Bell after a poll of the 12 teams in the league. 'All electronic devices, including walkie talkies, must be eliminated for the remainder of the season,' the directive from Bell stated.}}</ref> Today, however, all NFL teams use in-helmet radios to communicate with players.<ref name=\"Radio helmet use, current\">{{cite web|title=NFL installs new coach-to-defense communications system|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d809f61c6&template=with-video&confirm=true|publisher=National Football League|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UOkmc8n?url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d809f61c6&template=with-video&confirm=true|archivedate=June 17, 2012|accessdate=May 12, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Jim Brown era and new ownership (1957\u20131965)==\n\n[[File:Jim Brown running in the 1957 NFL championship.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Cleveland Browns rookie Jim Brown shakes off three tacklers and runs 29&nbsp;yards for a touchdown in the 1957 NFL championship game. Brown led the league in rushing in all but one season in his career.]]\n\nWith Otto Graham and most of the other original Browns in retirement, by 1957 the team was struggling to replenish its ranks.{{sfn|Heaton|2007|p=154}} In the first round of [[1957 NFL Draft|that year's draft]], Cleveland took fullback [[Jim Brown]] out of [[Syracuse University]].{{sfn|Freeman|2007|p=33\u201334}} In his first season, Brown led the NFL with 942&nbsp;yards of rushing and was voted rookie of the year in a United Press poll.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brown Named Top Rookie of the Year|newspaper=The Wilmington News|date=December 24, 1957|agency=United Press|quote=Jim Brown&nbsp;... today was named the National Football League's outstanding 1957 rookie in the annual United Press poll. Brown's 942 rushing yards gave him the league ball-carrying championship&nbsp;... [He] received 28 of the 32 votes cast by sports writers&nbsp;...}}</ref> Cleveland finished 9\u20132\u20131 and again advanced to the [[1957 NFL Championship Game|championship game]] against Detroit. The Lions dominated the game, forcing six turnovers and allowing only 112&nbsp;yards passing in a 59\u201314 rout.<ref name=\"1957 championship\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Lions Crush Browns, 59\u201314  Win Title With Five TD Aerials |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19571229BROWNS.html |accessdate=May 15, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 28, 1957 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UQej1fm?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19571229BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBefore the 1958 season, O'Connell, who lacked the stature and durability Paul Brown wanted in a starter, retired to take a coaching job in Illinois, and [[Milt Plum]] was named as his replacement.{{sfn|Miller|2007|p=76}}<ref name=\"O'Connell retires\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|title=Plum Moves Up As O'Connell Quits|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=January 22, 1958|page=25|quote=Retirement of Tommy O'Connell from the Cleveland Browns yesterday to take the position of backfield coach at Illinois puts the quarterbacking squarely on the broad shoulders of Milt Plum&nbsp;... The decision of the 27-year-old O'Connell probably was swayed by the fact that he ran into several injuries in his second season with the Browns. Although he finished as the league's leading passer&nbsp;... the chunky little fellow was out of the last two regular season games with a sprained ankle and what turned out to be a broken bone in his leg&nbsp;... Brown indicated that O'Connell's physical limitations prevented him from figuring too prominently in long range plans. O'Connell is 5&nbsp;feet, 10&nbsp;inches tall, weighs 190.}}</ref> Cleveland, however, was relying increasingly on the running game, in contrast to its pass-happy early years under Graham. As the team built up a 9\u20133 regular-season record, Brown in 1958 ran for 1,527&nbsp;yards \u2013 almost twice as much as any other back and a league record at the time.<ref name=\"1958 stats\">{{cite web|title=1958 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1958.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UWphVS1?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1958.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nEntering the final game of the 1958 season, Cleveland needed to either win or tie against the New York Giants to clinch the Eastern Conference title and the right to host the [[1958 NFL Championship Game|championship game]].<ref name=\"Browns prepare for Giants, 1958\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|title=Browns Set To Pass Against Giants|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 13, 1958|page=21|quote=If they lose to the Giants, there will be a playoff for the eastern division crown Dec. 21 at Yankee Stadium. If the Browns win there will be a weekend of rest before the championship game against the Baltimore Colts Dec. 28 at Cleveland Stadium.}}</ref> Cleveland lost that game under snowy conditions on a 49-yard field goal by [[Pat Summerall]] as time expired, and then lost a playoff game against the Giants the following week to end the season.<ref name=\"Giants beat Browns, 1958\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns lose to Giants, 13\u201310 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19581214BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UWzQl1D?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19581214BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 14, 1958 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Browns lose playoff 1958\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns Lose Playoff, 10\u20130 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19581221BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UX2pmtm?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19581221BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 21, 1958 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Giants went on to play the [[Baltimore Colts]] in the [[1958 NFL Championship Game|championship]], a game often cited as the seed of professional football's popularity surge in the U.S.{{sfn|Bowden|2008}}\n\nCleveland's campaigns in [[1959 Cleveland Browns season|1959]] and [[1960 Cleveland Browns season|1960]] were unremarkable, aside from Brown's league-leading rushing totals in both seasons.<ref name=\"Browns end 1959 season\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|title=Browns' 14 In 4th Nip Eagles, 28\u201321|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 14, 1959|page=35|quote=Jim Brown&nbsp;... for the third straight year the National League rushing champion with 1,329&nbsp;yards&nbsp;...}}</ref> Plum, meanwhile, became the established starting quarterback, bringing a measure of stability to the squad not seen since Graham's retirement. He led the team to a 7\u20135 record in 1959 and an 8\u20133\u20131 record in 1960, but neither was good enough to win the Eastern Conference and advance to the championship.<ref name=\"1959 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=1959 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1959.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UX6C046?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1959.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"1960 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=1960 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1960.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UX9lmYQ?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1960.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Behind the scenes, however, all was not well. A conflict took shape between Paul Brown and Jim Brown; emboldened by his success, the fullback began to question his coach's disciplinarian methods. He called the coach \"Little Caesar\" behind his back. At halftime during a game in 1959, Paul Brown questioned the severity of an injury Jim Brown was sidelined for, which further inflamed tensions between the two.{{sfn|Dyer|2007|p=114}}\n\n===Art Modell takes ownership===\n\n[[Fred \"Curly\" Morrison]], a former Browns running back who worked as an advertising executive for [[CBS]] television, learned in 1960 that Dave Jones was looking to sell the Browns and told the story to [[Art Modell]], a 35-year-old advertising and television executive from [[Brooklyn]].{{sfn|Coughlin|2011|p=212\u2013213}} Modell was intrigued, partly because of the potentially lucrative television rights that one of the NFL's most successful franchises could bring as football began to challenge baseball as America's biggest sport.{{sfn|Coughlin|2011|pp=213\u2013214}} Having borrowed as much money as he could, Modell completed the purchase in March 1961 for $3.925 million. Bob Gries, who had a share in the Browns from the beginning, agreed to buy in again at the new valuation and take a stake of almost 40%, defraying Modell's costs substantially.{{sfn|Coughlin|2011|p=214}} As the previous owners did when they took over, Modell quickly assured Cleveland fans that Brown would \"have a free hand\" in running the organization and awarded him a new eight-year contract.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=37}} \"As far as I'm concerned Paul Brown can send [plays] in by carrier pigeon\", Modell said. \"In my opinion he has no peer as a football coach. His record speaks for itself. I view our relationship as a working partnership.\"{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=43}}\n\nThe 1961 season was typical on the field: Jim Brown led the league in rushing for the fifth straight season and the team ended with an 8\u20135\u20131 record. That left Cleveland two games out of a berth in the championship.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=50}} During that year, however, players began to question Paul Brown's strict and often overbearing demeanor, while many challenged his control over the team's strategy. Milt Plum spoke out against Brown calling all the team's offensive plays, and Jim Brown said on a weekly radio broadcast that the coach's play-calling and handling of Plum were undermining the quarterback's confidence.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=48}}{{sfn|Lebovitz|2006|p=15}} They found a willing listener in Modell, a bachelor who was closer to their age than the coach's.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=43, 47}}\n\nFurther cracks appeared in the \"working partnership\" between Paul Brown and Modell before the 1962 season. Brown made a trade without informing Modell, giving up star halfback [[Bobby Mitchell]] to acquire the rights to Syracuse running back [[Ernie Davis]], the first African-American to win the [[Heisman Trophy]].{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=50}} Davis was chosen by the [[Washington Redskins]] with the first overall pick in the 1962 draft, but while Davis was the first black player ever selected by Washington, team owner [[George Preston Marshall]] made the move only after being given an ultimatum to add an African-American player or risk losing his stadium lease. Davis demanded a trade, leaving the door open to the Browns, who signed him to a three-year contract worth $80,000.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=51}} As Davis was preparing for the [[College All-Star Game]], however, he came down with a mystery illness and was later diagnosed with [[leukemia]]. Brown ruled Davis out for the season, but the running back returned to Cleveland and began a conditioning program after one of his doctors said playing football would not exacerbate his condition.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=52}} Modell thought Davis could be prepared to play, and Davis, who by then knew he was dying, wanted to be part of the team. Brown, however, continued to insist that he sit out, driving a deeper wedge between him and Modell. Davis died the following May.{{sfn|Lebovitz|2006|pp=15\u201316}}\n\nThe rift between Brown and Modell only widened as the 1962 season progressed. [[Frank Ryan (American football)|Frank Ryan]] took Milt Plum's place as the team's starting quarterback by the end of the season, and the Browns finished with a 7\u20136\u20131 record. Jim Brown was not the NFL's leading rusher for the only time in his career.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=57}}\n\n===Paul Brown is fired===\n\nOn January 9, 1963, Art Modell sent a statement to the newswires: \"Paul E. Brown, head coach and general manager, will no longer serve the team in those capacities\", it said.<ref name=\"Paul Brown fired\">{{cite news|last=Friedman|first=Larry|title=Paul Brown Fired After 17 Years With Browns|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1908&dat=19630111&id=jmEfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ldQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3133,483230|accessdate=May 18, 2012|newspaper=Nevada Daily Mail|date=January 10, 1963|agency=Associated Press|page=8}}</ref> Immediate reaction to the decision was muted due to a newspaper strike that kept the [[Cleveland Plain Dealer]] and [[Cleveland Press]] off the newsstands until April. A printing company executive, however, got together a group of sportswriters and published a 32-page magazine fielding players' views on the firing. Opinions were mixed; Modell came in for his share of criticism, but tackle and team captain [[Mike McCormack (American football)|Mike McCormack]] said he did not think the team could win under Brown.{{sfn|Lebovitz|2006|p=13\u201314}} Nonetheless, it was a shocking end to the 17-year Cleveland career of a coach who was already a seminal figure in the city's sports history.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=62\u201363}} Among many innovations, Brown was the first coach to call plays for his quarterback, give players IQ and personality tests and use game film to evaluate opponents.{{sfn|Cantor|2008|p=3}} Even Jim Brown lauded his pioneering role in integrating the game:\n\n<blockquote>Paul Brown integrated pro football without uttering a single word about integration. He just went out, signed a bunch of great black athletes, and started kicking butt. That's how you do it. You don't talk about it.&nbsp;... [I]n his own way, the man integrated football the right way \u2013 and no one was going to stop him.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=49}}</blockquote>\n\nModell named Brown's chief assistant, [[Blanton Collier]], as the team's new head coach.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=64}} Collier was a friendly, studious man who became a player favorite as an assistant on both offense and defense under Brown.{{sfn|Groza|2003|p=52}} He installed an open offense and allowed Ryan to call his own plays.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=67}} In Collier's first season, the Browns finished with a 10\u20134 record but fell short of a division title.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=75, 77}} Jim Brown won the [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|MVP award]] in 1963 with a record 1,863&nbsp;yards rushing. Dominant blocking from the Browns' offensive line, which included guard [[Gene Hickerson]] and left tackle [[Dick Schafrath]], helped boost his totals.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=74, 78}}\n\n===1964 championship===\n\n[[File:Cleveland Browns quarterback Frank Ryan, 1964.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Cleveland quarterback Frank Ryan is mobbed after the 1964 championship.]]\n\nCleveland climbed back to the top of the eastern division in 1964 with a 10\u20133\u20131 record behind Jim Brown's league-leading 1,446&nbsp;yards of rushing.<ref name=\"1964 statistics\">{{cite web|title=1964 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1964.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UXIe1c9?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1964.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Rookie wide receiver [[Paul Warfield]] led the team with 52 catches,{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=112, 198}} and Frank Ryan cemented his place as the team's starting quarterback, recording the best game of his career in the season closer against the New York Giants, a game the Browns needed to win to advance to the championship.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=118\u2013119}} Yet despite Cleveland's prowess, the Browns went into the [[1964 NFL Championship Game|championship game]] as heavy underdogs against the Baltimore Colts. Most sportswriters predicted an easy win for the Colts, who led the league in scoring behind quarterback [[Johnny Unitas]] and halfback [[Lenny Moore]]. The Browns' defense, moreover, was suspect. The team gave up 20 more first downs than any other in the league.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=122\u2013124}} The teams, however, had not faced each other for three years. Before the game, Collier and Colts coach [[Don Shula]] agreed to give each other full access to video of regular-season games. Ever the student, Collier took full advantage of the opportunity. The Browns had run what was dubbed a \"rubber band\" pass defense, allowing short throws while trying to prevent big plays. The Colts' top receivers, however, [[Raymond Berry]] and [[Jimmy Orr]], were not fast. They tended to pick apart defenses with short, tactical completions, which led Collier to institute a man-to-man pass defense for the game. This, he figured, would buy more time for the defensive line and force Unitas to scramble \u2014 not his forte.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=131\u2013132}}\n\nThe strategy paid off, and in the wind-whipped Cleveland Municipal Stadium two days after [[Christmas]], the Browns beat the Colts 27\u20130. Neither team scored in the first half, prompting ''[[New York Times]]'' columnist [[Red Smith (sportswriter)|Red Smith]] to quip, \"Never have so many paid so dearly \u2013 $10, $8, and $6 \u2013 and suffered so sorely to see so little.\"{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=148}} In the second half, the Browns' defense held on and the offense kicked into gear. Baltimore's cornerbacks were double-teaming Warfield, which Ryan exploited by throwing three touchdowns to his second wideout, [[Gary Collins (American football)|Gary Collins]]. The Browns scored 10 points in the third quarter and a further 17 in the fourth, clinching the first title since Otto Graham's departure after the 1955 season.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=150\u2013151}} Collins was named the game's MVP.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=158}}  This would be the last time that any professional sports team from Cleveland would win a league title until 2016, when the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]'s [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] won the [[2016 NBA Finals]].\nTo date, this remains the last time that the Browns have won the NFL title.\n\nThe following year was a strong one as Jim Brown gritted out another league-leading rushing season.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=178}} The Browns ended with an 11\u20133 record and comfortably won the eastern division.<ref name=\"1965 statistics\">{{cite web|title=1965 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1965.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UXOrD2U?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1965.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> That set up a second straight appearance in the [[1965 NFL Championship Game|NFL Championship game]] against the Packers on a slippery, mucky [[Lambeau Field]] on January 2, 1966. While the score was close early on, [[Vince Lombardi]]'s team held the Browns scoreless in the second half, winning 23\u201312 in an upset on a [[Paul Hornung]] touchdown.{{sfn|Page|2010|pp=206\u2013209}} After the season, the NFL and the competing [[American Football League]] agreed to [[AFL\u2013NFL merger|merge]] starting in 1970, but would play an inter-league championship from the 1966 season onward. The 1965 championship thus became the NFL's last before the Super Bowl era, which ushered in a new age of popularity and prosperity for professional football.\n\n{{quote|text=In time, this game would be nearly forgotten, lost in the middle of Lombardi's great triumphs.&nbsp;... This was both unfair and fitting in a sense, because the game was best considered on its own, a faded dream played in the mist and slop, a transitory moment between football past and future.|sign=[[David Maraniss]]|source=''When Pride Still Mattered: A Life of Vince Lombardi''{{sfn|Maraniss|2000}}}}\n\n==Playoff disappointments (1966\u20131973)==\n\nIn early 1966 Jim Brown, who had begun an acting career two years before, was shooting for his second film in London.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=176\u2013178}} ''[[The Dirty Dozen]]'' cast Brown as Robert Jefferson, a convict sent to France during World War II to assassinate German officers meeting at a castle near [[Rennes]] in [[Brittany]]. Production delays due to bad weather meant he would miss at least the first part of training camp on the campus of [[Hiram College]], which annoyed Modell, who threatened to fine Brown $1,500 for every week of camp he missed.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=178\u2013179}} Brown, who had previously said that 1966 would be his last season, announced his retirement instead.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=179}} At the end of his nine-year career, Brown held records for most rushing yards in a game, a season and a career. He also owned the record for all-purpose yards in a career and best average per carry for a running back at 5.22&nbsp;yards, a mark that still stands.<ref name=\"Jim Brown career HOF stats\">{{cite web|title=Jim Brown|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.aspx?PlayerId=33&tab=Highlights|publisher=Pro Football Hall Of Fame|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UZ5wryd?url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.aspx?PlayerId=33&tab=Highlights|archivedate=June 17, 2012|accessdate=June 15, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith Brown gone, halfback [[Leroy Kelly]] became the team's primary rusher in 1966. Kelly, an eighth-round draft choice who saw limited playing time in two years as a backup, ably filled his predecessor's shoes.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|pp=272\u2013276}} Cleveland missed the playoffs in 1966, but made it to the postseason the following year after a realignment of the NFL's divisions that placed the Browns in the new [[Century Division]].{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=50}} The Browns, however, lost the 1967 eastern conference championship to the [[Dallas Cowboys]].{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=50}} After a year in which he made just 11 of 23 field goal attempts, placekicker Lou Groza, the last remaining player from the inaugural 1946 Browns team, retired before the start of the 1968 season.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=190}} Groza, who had been on the roster for 21 seasons and was 44 years old when he hung up his spikes, said in his memoir that retiring was \"the saddest day of my football life.\"{{sfn|Groza|2003|p=100}}\n\nFurther playoff defeats followed. In 1968, as a 32-year-old Ryan was benched in favor of [[Bill Nelsen]],<ref name=\"Ryan benched for Nelsen\">{{cite news|last=Place|first=Tom|title=Nelsen Expects Big Rush By Steelers|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=October 2, 1968|page=33|quote=Coach Blanton Collier has tagged him as the man to rally to the Browns from two straight inept offensive performances in a move that sends Frank Ryan to the bench. After losing to Dallas, 28\u20137, two weeks ago and Los Angeles, 24\u20136, last Sunday, Collier decided a change had to be made.}}</ref> the Browns finished with a 10\u20134 record but lost to the Colts in the playoffs.<ref name=\"Colts beat Browns, 1968\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns' Title Bid Ends, 34\u20130 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19681229BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UZElYZJ?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19681229BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 29, 1968 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Another playoff loss ended the Browns' season in 1969, this time to the [[Minnesota Vikings]].<ref name=\"Vikings beat Browns, 1970\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Vikings Repulse Browns, 27\u20137 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19700104BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UZMEIjN?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19700104BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=January 4, 1970 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After the American Football League's merger with the NFL was finalized in early 1970, the Browns, [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] and Baltimore Colts moved to the new American Football Conference along with the 10 teams of the former AFL. The Browns were slotted in the [[AFC Central]] in the 26-team league, alongside the Steelers, the [[Houston Oilers]] and the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], a team Paul Brown founded in 1968 in the AFL.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|pp=51\u201352}} Cleveland's first big move under the new league structure was to trade star receiver Paul Warfield in January 1970 to the [[Miami Dolphins]] for the rights to draft [[Purdue University]] quarterback [[Mike Phipps]] as a replacement for Bill Nelsen, who had a pair of bad knees.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=61}}<ref name=\"Warfield trade announced\">{{cite news|title=Browns Trade Warfield, Three Others for Jones, Draft Pick|newspaper=The Bryan Times|date=January 27, 1970|agency=United Press International|page=8|quote='Paul has played so well for us and is such a high type person that I hated like the devil to consider any trade involving him,' Modell said. 'However, it was the overwhelming consensus of all our combined thinking that we had a pressing need for backup protection behind quarterback Bill Nelsen.' Warfield called his trade to the Dolphins a 'great surprise'.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1986 Jeno's Pizza - 31 - Rick Volk and Leroy Kelly.jpg|thumb|right|The Browns playing against the Baltimore Colts in a 1971 divisional playoff Game.]]\nThe Browns opened the first post-merger season of 1970 by beating [[Joe Namath]] and the New York Jets in the first-ever broadcast of [[Monday Night Football]] on September 21.{{sfn|Boyer|2006|pp=66\u201368}} The following month, Cleveland faced Paul Brown's Bengals for the first time in a regular-season game, winning 30\u201327. That game was a highlight in an otherwise unsuccessful season. The Browns lost their second match against the Bengals 14\u201310 in November, when Phipps made his first start \u2014 Brown called it \"my greatest victory\" \u2014 and finished 7\u20137.<ref name=\"Browns beat Bengals, 1970\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns nip Cincy, so do Birds |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19701011BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UZOzlMZ?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19701011BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=October 11, 1970 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nPlagued by hearing problems, the 64-year-old Collier announced his retirement before the end of the 1970 season.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=52}} In eight years as coach, Collier led Cleveland to a championship and a 74\u201333\u20132 record.<ref name=\"Collier retires\">{{cite news|title=Browns' Blanton Says He's Retiring This Year|newspaper=Rochester Sentinel|date=December 2, 1970}}</ref> [[Nick Skorich]] was named as his replacement the following year.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=61}} Skorich came to the Browns as offensive coordinator in 1964, when the team won the championship.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=61}} In Cleveland's first year under Skorich, the team improved to 9\u20135 but lost to the Colts in a divisional playoff.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=62}} Mike Phipps was promoted to starting quarterback over Nelsen before the 1972 season.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=62}} After a sluggish start, the Browns went on tear and finished with a 10\u20134 record. That put Cleveland in a playoff against the undefeated Miami Dolphins. The Browns took a lead in the fourth quarter on a touchdown catch by wide receiver [[Fair Hooker]], but the Dolphins responded with a long drive of their own, aided by a pair of Paul Warfield receptions. Running back [[Jim Kiick]] ran for a touchdown, sealing a 20\u201314 win and preserving the Dolphins' perfect season.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=63}} The following year, Phipps threw 20 interceptions and completed less than half of his passes.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=63}} After winning four of the first six games, the Browns slumped and placed third in the division with a 7\u20135\u20132 record.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=63}}\n\n==Brian Sipe era and the Kardiac Kids (1974\u20131984)==\n\nTransition and poor play marked the mid- to late-1970s. Though Collier agreed to come back to the Browns as a quarterbacks coach on an informal basis, his retirement severed the last direct link to Brown and the team's early years.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=297}} Meanwhile, a new generation of players began to replace the old hands who kept Cleveland in playoff contention through most of the 1960s. Gene Hickerson, an anchor on the offensive line in the 1960s, retired at the end of the 1973 season.<ref name=\"Hickerson hall of fame\">{{cite web|title=Gene Hickerson |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.aspx?PLAYER_ID=263 |publisher=Pro Football Hall of Fame |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UauC4Rm?url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.aspx?PLAYER_ID=263 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> An aging Leroy Kelly left the same year to play in the short-lived [[World Football League]].{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=276}} Offensive lineman Dick Schafrath, a six-time Pro Bowl selection, retired in 1971.{{sfn|Pluto|1997|p=205}}\n\nAgainst that backdrop, the Browns finished the 1974 season with a 4\u201310 record, only the second losing season in the team's history.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=63}} Phipps' woes persisted, and he shared playing time with rookie quarterback [[Brian Sipe]], who Cleveland selected in the 13th round of the 1972 draft out of [[San Diego State]].{{sfn|Pluto|2010|p=62}} Modell fired Skorich after the season. \"You've got to be a winner in this game, and I just didn't produce\", Skorich said at the time.<ref name=\"Skorich fired\">{{cite news|title=Browns Coach Skorich Fired|newspaper=Bangor Daily News|date=December 17, 1974|agency=Associated Press|page=21}}</ref> After pursuing Dolphins offensive line coach [[Monte Clark]], Modell hired [[Forrest Gregg]] as Skorch's replacement.{{sfn|Gregg|2009|pp=196\u2013197}} Gregg, an assistant coach and former Green Bay Packers offensive lineman, preached a hard-nosed, physical brand of football, learned as an offensive lineman on Green Bay's dynastic 1960s teams under Lombardi.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|pp=63\u201364}} His success as a player, however, did not immediately translate into success as a coach. The regular season began with the worst losing streak in Cleveland's history. Gregg's first win did not come until November 23 against Paul Brown's Cincinnati Bengals, and Cleveland finished with a 3\u201311 record.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=64}}\n\nThe team improved the following year, ending with a 9\u20135 record but missing the playoffs.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=16}} The highlight of that season was an 18\u201316 victory over the Pittsburgh Steelers on October 10.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=64}} Kicker [[Don Cockroft]] booted four field goals, while defensive end [[Joe (Turkey) Jones|Joe \"Turkey\" Jones]]' pile-driving sack of quarterback [[Terry Bradshaw]] added fuel to the heated rivalry between the teams.<ref name=\"Browns beat Steelers, 1976\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Steelers jolted |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19761010BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UayWnuK?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19761010BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=October 10, 1976 |url-status=dead }}</ref> While Gregg won the NFL's [[National Football League Coach of the Year Award|Coach of the Year award]] for turning the Browns around as Sipe became the starting quarterback, by the beginning of the 1977 season the same kind of friction that dogged Paul Brown's relationship with Modell was surfacing between the owner and the hotheaded Gregg.{{sfn|Gregg|2009|pp=227\u2013236}} Cleveland got off to a strong start that year, but Sipe hurt his shoulder and elbow in a November 13 game against the Steelers, and backup [[Dave Mays]] took the reins.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=16}} With Mays as the quarterback \u2013 Modell traded Phipps to the [[Chicago Bears]] for a couple of draft picks \u2013 Cleveland slipped to 6\u20137 going into the final game of the season and Modell asked Gregg to resign.<ref name=\"Gregg fired\">{{cite news|title=Gregg Out Of Work After Big 1976 Season|newspaper=The Leader-Post|date=December 20, 1977|agency=Associated Press|page=16|quote=Most persons close to the scene agree that the catalyst in Gregg's downfall was his temper, which turned off many of the veteran players on the team and widened an apparent personality conflict between him and owner Art Modell.}}</ref>\n\nModell said he would look outside the Browns organization for a new coach, a break from past hirings that drew from the team's own ranks.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=11}} Peter Hadhazy, who Modell had hired as the Browns' first general manager, recommended a 45-year-old [[New Orleans Saints]] receivers coach named [[Sam Rutigliano]]. After an interview before Christmas in which Modell and Rutigliano spent hours talking and watching game film in Modell's basement, the owner named him head coach on December 27, 1977.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=11}} An affable, charismatic man with an even temper, Rutigliano was a stark contrast to Gregg.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=11\u201312}} Sipe immediately flourished under Rutigliano, racking up 21 touchdowns and 2,906 passing yards during the 1978 season, when the NFL moved to a 16-game schedule.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=16}} His prime targets were [[Reggie Rucker]], a veteran receiver the Browns signed in 1975, and [[Ozzie Newsome]], a rookie tight end out of [[University of Alabama|Alabama]] who the Browns drafted with a pick acquired in the Phipps trade.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=19\u201321}} Cleveland won its first three games, but poor defense dashed the team's playoff chances and the Browns finished with an 8\u20138 record.<ref name=\"1978 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=1978 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1978.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ub2Wcep?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1978.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Kardiac Kids===\n\n[[File:Sipe1979bySherk.jpeg|thumb|right|Cleveland Browns quarterback Brian Sipe led the \"Kardiac Kids\" to a series of last-minute victories.]]\n\nRutigliano was a gambler: he tinkered with offenses, took chances on trick plays and was not afraid to break with the play-calling conventions of his time.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=12\u201313}} The coach, who earned the nickname \"Riverboat Sam\" for his risk-taking approach, once said that security was \"for cowards\". \"I believe in gambling\", he said. \"No successful man ever got anywhere without gambling.\"{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=13}} This seat-of-your-pants philosophy began to manifest itself on the field in 1979. The campaign started with a nail-biter against the New York Jets that the Browns won in overtime on a Cockroft field goal as time expired. \"If we continue to play 'em that way all year, I'll be gone before the 10th game because my heart just won't take it\", Rutigliano said after the game.<ref name=\"Browns beat Jets in OT, 1979\">{{cite news|last=Heaton |first=Chuck |title=Browns stun Jets in OT |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19790902BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ub4u7Cx?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19790902BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 25, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=September 2, 1979 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the second week, Cleveland beat the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] 27\u201324 on a Sipe touchdown to Rucker with 52 seconds left.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=74}} The third game was an equally improbable 13\u201310 win against the Baltimore Colts.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=74}} ''Cleveland Plain Dealer'' sports editor [[Hal Lebovitz]] wrote after the game that these \"[[Kardiac Kids]]\" were lucky to have pulled off the win after Colts kicker [[Toni Linhart]] missed three field goals.<ref name=\"Lebovitz on Kardiac Kids\">{{cite news|last=Lebovitz|first=Hal|title=Gift from Colts|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 17, 1979|page=1\u2013C}}</ref>\n\nAfter a string of four wins and three losses, the late-game heroics returned in an overtime victory on November 18 against the Miami Dolphins.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=13}} \"You should never pipe Browns games into an intensive care unit, expose them to anyone weak of pulse\", wrote [[Toledo Blade]] columnist Jim Taylor. \"They're one of those teams that stands 8\u20134, and could easily be 1\u201311.\"<ref name=\"Blade on Kardiac Kids\">{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Jim|title=Browns' Routine Not Routine|newspaper=The Toledo Blade|date=November 19, 1979|page=20}}</ref> While the Browns' 9\u20137 record did not get the team into the playoffs \u2013 the defense struggled all year, forcing Sipe and the offense to compensate with late-game comebacks \u2013 a sense of optimism and excitement took hold.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=13\u201314}}\n\nThe Kardiac Kids magic returned in the third game of the next season against the Chiefs, when the Browns scored a touchdown in the fourth quarter to win 20\u201313.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=75}} More down-to-the-wire games followed, including one against Green Bay on October 19 in which the team won on a touchdown to receiver [[Dave Logan (American football)|Dave Logan]] on the last play of the game.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=82\u201383}} After a close win over the Steelers and a victory over the Bears in which Sipe broke Otto Graham's club record for career passing yards, the Browns met the Colts and eked out a 28\u201327 win.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=98\u201399, 108, 111, 118}} The team ended with an 11\u20135 record.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=223}}\n\n===Red Right 88===\n\n{{Main|Red Right 88}}\n\nThat was good for first place in the AFC Central and a trip to the postseason for the first time since 1972.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=76}} The Browns began their playoff run against the [[Oakland Raiders]] on January 4, 1981 in a bitterly cold Cleveland Municipal Stadium.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=234\u2013236}} The game started slowly: each team scored only a touchdown in the first half, although Cockroft missed Cleveland's extra point because of a bad snap.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=238\u2013242}} In the third quarter, Cleveland went ahead 12\u20137 on a pair of Cockroft field goals, but the Raiders came back in the final period, driving 80&nbsp;yards down the field for a touchdown. That put Oakland ahead 14\u201312.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=243\u2013245}} The ball changed hands five times with no scoring from either side, and with 2:22 on the clock, Cleveland had a final shot to win the game.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=246\u2013247}} Sipe and the offense took over at the Browns' 15-yard line. In eight plays, Cleveland drove down to Oakland's 14, leaving 56 seconds on the clock.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=250}}\n\n[[File:Sam-Rutigliano-1979.jpg|thumb|left|Sam Rutigliano, the Browns' head coach during the Kardiac Kids years]]\n\nAfter a one-yard [[Mike Pruitt]] run, Rutigliano called a timeout.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=250}} A short field goal would have been the safe bet \u2014 that was all Cleveland needed to win. Rutigliano, ever the risk-taker, decided to go for a touchdown. The coach was reluctant to stake the game's outcome on the usually sure-footed Cockroft, who had missed two field goals and an extra point earlier in the game.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=250}} The play he called was [[Red Right 88]], a passing formation in which a slanting Logan would be Sipe's primary target, while Newsome was insurance. If everyone was covered, Rutigliano told Sipe on the sidelines, \"if you feel you have to force the ball, throw it into Lake Erie, throw it into some blonde's lap in the bleachers.\"{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=251}} Sipe took the snap, dropped back and threw to Newsome as he crossed to the left. But Oakland safety [[Mike Davis (defensive back)|Mike Davis]] leaped in front and intercepted the ball, cementing the Oakland win. The Raiders went on to win [[Super Bowl XV]], while Red Right 88 became an enduring symbol of Cleveland's postseason stumbles.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=252\u2013254, 261, 265}}\n\nDespite 1980's playoff defeat, the Browns were widely expected to be even better the following year. But 1981 came with none of the comebacks or late-game magic the Kardiac Kids were known for. Several games were close, but most were losses. Sipe threw only 17 touchdowns and was intercepted 25 times.{{sfn|Knight|2003|pp=269\u2013270}} The team finished 5\u201311.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=272}} The [[1982 NFL strike]], which began in September and lasted until mid-November, shortened the regular season the following year to nine games.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=276}} Coming off a poor year, Sipe split starts with his backup, [[Paul McDonald (American football)|Paul McDonald]], and neither was able to bring back the old Kardiac Kids spark.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=276}} The team ended with a 4\u20135 record, which qualified for an expanded Super Bowl playoff tournament created to accommodate the shorter season. The Browns faced the Raiders in a rematch of 1980's playoff thriller. This time, though, McDonald was the starter and the ending was far from tense. The Raiders won 27\u201310.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=276}}\n\nThe following two years brought the Sipe era and the short-lived success of the Kardiac Kids to an end.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=277}} Sipe returned to form in 1983, and the team narrowly missed a spot in the playoffs after a loss to the Houston Oilers in the second-to-last game of the regular season.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=78}} Sipe signed before the end of the season to play for the [[New Jersey Generals]], a team owned by real estate mogul [[Donald Trump]] in the upstart [[United States Football League]].{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=277}}\n\nIn training camp before the 1984 season, cornerback [[Hanford Dixon]] tried to motivate the team's defensive linemen by barking at them between plays in practice and calling them \"the Dogs\". \"You need guys who play like dogs up front, like dogs chasing a cat\", Dixon said.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=26}} The media picked up on the name, which gained traction in part because of the improvement of the Browns' defense during the regular season. Fans put on face paint and dog masks, and the phenomenon coalesced in rowdy fans in Cleveland Stadium's cheap bleachers section close to the field.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=26}} The [[Dawg Pound]], as the section was eventually nicknamed, is a continuing symbol of Cleveland's dedicated fan base.{{sfn|Boyer|2006|pp=101\u2013105}}\n\nDespite the defensive improvement, Sipe's departure left Cleveland's offense in disarray in 1984. Browns began the season 1\u20137 with McDonald at quarterback, and fans' frustration with the team and Rutigliano boiled over.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=78}} The breaking point came in an October 7 game against the [[New England Patriots]] that bore an eerie resemblance to Cleveland's 1980 playoff loss to the Raiders. The Browns were down 17\u201316 in the fourth quarter, and lost on an interception in New England's end zone as time expired.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=278}} Chants of \"Goodbye Sam\" rung out from the stands after the New England game. Modell called the play-calling \"inexcusable\" and fired Rutigliano two weeks later.<ref name=\"Rutigliano on hot seat\">{{cite news|last=Schneider|first=Russ|title=Rutigliano's control is key to his destiny|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=October 14, 1984|page=2\u2013B}}</ref> Defensive coordinator [[Marty Schottenheimer]] took over, and the Browns ended with a 5\u201311 record.{{sfn|Knight|2003|p=279}}\n\n==Bernie Kosar years, The Drive and The Fumble (1985\u20131990)==\n\nThe selection of [[Miami Hurricanes football|University of Miami]] quarterback [[Bernie Kosar]] in 1985's [[supplemental draft]] ushered in a new, largely successful era for Cleveland. With Schottenheimer, Kosar and a cast of talented players on offense and defense, the team reached greater heights than Rutigliano and Sipe ever did. Though they became consistent playoff contenders in this era, the Browns did not reach the Super Bowl, falling one win short three times in the late 1980s.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=299\u2013300}}\n\n[[File:Bruce-and-Clay-Matthews-80s.jpg|thumb|right|Browns linebacker [[Clay Matthews, Jr.|Clay Matthews]] (right) with his brother [[Bruce Matthews (American football)|Bruce Matthews]] of the Houston Oilers. Matthews played a key role on Cleveland's defenses of the late 1980s.]]\n\nKosar, who wanted to play for Cleveland because his family lived in a suburb of nearby [[Youngstown, Ohio|Youngstown]], signed a five-year contract worth nearly $6 million in 1985 and was immediately embraced by the Browns organization and the team's fans.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=16, 21}} \"It's not an everyday occurrence that somebody ''wants'' to play in Cleveland\", Modell said. \"This has lent such an aura to Bernie.\"<ref name=\"SI on Bernie 1985\">{{cite journal|last=Looney|first=Douglas S.|title=There's A Love Feast On Lake Erie|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=August 26, 1985}}</ref> Kosar saw his first action in the fifth week of the 1985 season against the New England Patriots, when he substituted before halftime for [[Gary Danielson]], a 34-year-old veteran who the Browns had acquired in the offseason from the Lions.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=24, 44\u201345}} Kosar fumbled his first-ever NFL snap, but rebounded and led the team to a 24\u201320 win.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=45}} A mix of success and failure followed, but Kosar progressed a bit more each Sunday and led the team to an 8\u20138 record.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=50, 52\u201354}} Two young running backs, [[Earnest Byner]] and [[Kevin Mack]], complemented Kosar's aerial attack with more than 1,000&nbsp;yards rushing each.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=54\u201355}}\n\nWhile not stellar, the Browns' record won first place in a weak AFC Central, and the team looked poised to shock the heavily favored Miami Dolphins in a divisional playoff game on January 4, 1986.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=56}} Cleveland surged to a 21\u20133 halftime lead, and it took a spirited second-half comeback by [[Dan Marino]] and the Dolphins to win it 24\u201321 and end the Browns' season.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=58\u201362}} Despite the loss, many people expected Cleveland to be back the following year. \"The Browns' days, the good days, are here and ahead of us\", radio personality Pete Franklin said.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=62}}\n\nPrior to the 1986 season the Browns lost standout safety and former defensive rookie of the year [[Don Rogers (safety)|Don Rogers]]. Rogers died of a cocaine overdose leaving the team without one of its best defenders in the secondary for the 1986 season. Despite the tumultuous off season, 1986 marked Cleveland's entry into the ranks of the NFL's elite as Kosar's play improved and the defensive unit came together. Kosar threw for 3,854&nbsp;yards to a corps of receivers that included [[Brian Brennan]], Newsome and rookie [[Webster Slaughter]].{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=93, 95, 98}} On defense, cornerbacks [[Frank Minnifield]] and Hanford Dixon emerged as one of the NFL's premiere pass-defending duos.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=28\u201329}} After a slow start, the Browns rose to the top of the divisional standings, twice beating the Pittsburgh Steelers and ending a 16-game losing streak at [[Three Rivers Stadium]].{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=73, 79, 93}} A 12\u20134 record earned Cleveland home-field advantage throughout the playoffs.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=89}}\n\nThe Browns' first opponents in the 1986 playoffs were the New York Jets.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=97\u201398}} The Jets were ahead for most of the game and held a 20\u201310 lead as time wound down in the final quarter. But Cleveland took over and began a march down the field, ending with a Kevin Mack touchdown.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=100\u2013103}} The defense forced the Jets to punt after the ensuing kickoff, leaving the offense with less than a minute to get within field goal range and even the score at 20\u201320. A pass interference penalty and a completion to Slaughter put the ball at the Jets' five-yard line, and kicker [[Mark Moseley]] booted through the tying score with 11 seconds left.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=103\u2013105}} In an initial 15-minute overtime period, Moseley missed a short field goal and neither team scored, sending the game into double overtime.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=106\u2013108}} This time, Moseley made a field goal and won the game for the Browns 23\u201320. It was the team's first playoff victory in 17 years.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=109}}\n\n===The Drive===\n\n{{Main|The Drive}}\n\nThe following week, the Browns matched up against the [[Denver Broncos]] in the AFC Championship game in Cleveland.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=116}} Denver got out to an early lead, but Cleveland tied the game and then went ahead 20\u201313 in the fourth quarter.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=116, 118\u2013119}} After the ensuing kickoff, the Broncos were pinned at their own 2-yard line with 5:32 remaining. Denver quarterback [[John Elway]] then engineered a 98-yard drive for a touchdown with the cold, whipping wind in his face.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=121\u2013127}} \"[[The Drive]]\", as the series came to be known, tied the score and sent the game into overtime. Cleveland received the ball first in the [[sudden death (sport)|sudden-death period]] but was stopped by the Denver defense. On Denver's first possession, Elway again led the Broncos on a long drive ending with a [[Rich Karlis]] field goal that sailed just inside the left upright and won the game.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=128\u2013130}} The drive that tied the game has since come to be seen as one of the best in playoff history, and is remembered by Cleveland fans as an historic meltdown. Denver went on to lose [[Super Bowl XXI]] to the New York Giants.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=131\u2013132}}\n\n{{quote|text=The drive, one of the finest ever engineered in a championship game, had been performed directly in the Browns' faces. There was no sneakiness about it; John Elway had simply shown what a man with all the tools could do. It was what everybody who had watched him enter the league as perhaps the most heralded quarterback since Joe Namath knew he could do. One was left with the distinct feeling that Elway would have marched his team down a 200-yard-or 300-yard-or five-mile-long field to pay dirt.|sign=[[Rick Telander]]|source=''Sports Illustrated''<ref name=\"Telander on The Drive\">{{cite journal|last=Telander|first=Rick|title=Getting There The Hard Way|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=January 19, 1987}}</ref>}}\n\nAlthough downtrodden by 1986's playoff defeat, Cleveland continued to win the following season.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=132}} Minnifield and Dixon excelled defending the pass, while Matthews and defensive tackle [[Bob Golic]] kept runners in check.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=152\u2013153, 162}} The Browns finished with a 10\u20135 record in 1987 and won the AFC Central for the third year in a row.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=92}} In the divisional playoff round, the Browns faced the [[Indianapolis Colts]] and won 38\u201321.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=166\u2013167}}\n\n===The Fumble===\n\n{{Main|The Fumble}}\n\nThe win set up a rematch with the Broncos in the AFC Championship in Denver.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=169}} The Broncos held a 21\u20133 lead at halftime, but a pair of rushing touchdowns and another by receiver [[Reggie Langhorne]] brought Cleveland to within seven points.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=173\u2013177}} Cleveland scored again in the fourth quarter, but the Broncos went ahead again by seven points on a touchdown with four minutes left.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=178\u2013179}} After Denver's kickoff, Kosar and the offense reached the Broncos' eight-yard line with 1:12 remaining.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=180}} Kosar handed the ball to Earnest Byner on a second down. Byner ran left and broke inside with a clear path to the end zone, but was stripped by Denver's [[Jeremiah Castille]] just before crossing the goal line. The Broncos ran down the clock before intentionally taking a [[Safety (American and Canadian football score)|safety]] and winning 38\u201333.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=181\u2013183}} \"[[The Fumble]]\" quickly entered the lexicon of the Browns' modern-era disappointment, just as The Drive had a year before.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=92}}\n\nThe 1988 season was marred by injuries to the Browns' quarterbacks. Kosar was injured in the opener against Kansas City Chiefs and two backups were subsequently injured, leaving [[Don Strock]], who the Browns signed as an emergency fill-in, to start before Kosar's return.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=191\u2013192, 197}} Kosar came back but was hurt again at the end of the regular season.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=209}} Despite the rotating cast of quarterbacks, Cleveland managed to finish with a 10\u20136 record and made the playoffs as a wild-card team.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=211, 215\u2013218}} Cleveland met the Houston Oilers in the wild-card playoff round at home, but lost the game 24\u201323.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=226}} Four days after the Oilers loss, Schottenheimer and Modell announced that the coach would leave the team by mutual consent. Modell felt hiring an offensive coordinator was necessary to keep pace with the Oilers and the Bengals, a pair of divisional opponents then on the rise, but Schottenheimer said it \"became evident that some of the differences we had, we weren't going to be able to resolve.\"{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=228\u2013229}}<ref name=\"Schottenheimer leaves Browns\">{{cite news|last=Melvin|first=Chuck|title=Schottenheimer Leaves Cleveland|newspaper=Gainesville Sun|date=December 28, 1988|agency=Associated Press|page=1\u2013C}}</ref> Modell named [[Bud Carson]] as his replacement.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=232\u2013233}}\n\nCarson, an architect of Pittsburgh's 1970s \"[[Steel Curtain]]\" defenses, made several changes to Cleveland's lineup.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=233}} Byner was traded to the Washington Redskins in April, while the Browns moved up in the draft to acquire [[Eric Metcalf]].{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=236\u2013238}} Kevin Mack, meanwhile, was suspended for the first four games of the 1989 season after pleading guilty to cocaine possession.<ref name=\"Mack cocaine plea\">{{cite news|title=Mack Pleads Guilty To Using Cocaine |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/08/31/sports/sports-people-football-mack-pleads-guilty-to-using-cocaine.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UcGD6Pe?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1989/08/31/sports/sports-people-football-mack-pleads-guilty-to-using-cocaine.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 27, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=August 26, 1989 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Despite these changes, Kosar led Cleveland to a division-winning 9\u20136\u20131 record in 1989, including a season-opening 51\u20130 shutout of the rival Pittsburgh Steelers and the team's first victory over the Denver Broncos in 15 years.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=243\u2013245, 252}} Cleveland narrowly survived a scare from the [[Buffalo Bills]] in the first playoff game, staving off a comeback thanks to an interception in the Browns' end zone by Clay Matthews with 14 seconds on the clock.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=281\u2013282}} The victory set up the third AFC championship matchup in four years between the Browns and Broncos. The Broncos led from start to finish, and a long Elway touchdown pass to Sammy Winder put the game way in the fourth quarter. Denver won 37\u201321.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=283\u2013285}}\n\nThe defeat in [[Mile High Stadium]] proved to be the last of Cleveland's streak of playoff appearances in the mid- to late-1980s. Kosar played through numerous injuries in 1989, including bruising on his right arm and a bad knee.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=265, 278}} Strong defense had carried the Browns to the playoffs even when the offense faltered, but that all crumbled in 1990. Kosar threw more interceptions than touchdowns for the first time in his career, and the defense allowed more points than any other in the league.<ref name=\"1990 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=1990 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1990.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UcIuG2k?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1990.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Browns' 2\u20137 start cost Carson his job.{{sfn|Knight|2006|pp=288\u2013289}} [[Jim Shofner]] was named interim head coach, and the team finished 3\u201313.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=290}} After the season [[Bill Belichick]], the defensive coordinator of the then-Super Bowl champion New York Giants, was named head coach.{{sfn|Knight|2006|p=292}}\n\n==Bill Belichick and Modell's move (1991\u20131995)==\n\n===Belichick era===\n\nBelichick, who came to the Browns after 12 years mostly with the Giants under [[Bill Parcells]], quickly made his mark by restricting media access to the team. He acted gruff or bored at press conferences, shrugging, rolling his eyes and often giving short answers to long questions.{{sfn|Holley|2011|p=1}} This bred the perception that the new coach was not a good communicator and lacked a vision for the team. Behind the scenes, however, he was trying to remake the Browns. He reformed Cleveland's scouting methods and, in conjunction with player personnel director [[Michael Lombardi (sportscaster)|Mike Lombardi]], tried to form a coherent identity: a big and strong cold-weather team.{{sfn|Holley|2011|pp=1\u20132}} Belichick's new way forward, however, did not immediately translate to on-field success. Cleveland's record only improved slightly in 1991 to 6\u201310 as the offense struggled to produce scoring drives and the defense was plagued by injuries.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=101}} Kosar was a rare bright spot, passing for almost 3,500&nbsp;yards and 18 touchdowns.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=101}} Bridging the end of the 1990 season and the beginning of 1991, the quarterback threw a then-record 307 straight passes without an interception.{{sfn|Gordon|2002|p=84}} Kosar broke his ankle twice and sat out for most of the 1992 season, leaving quarterback [[Mike Tomczak]] under center. The team finished with a 7\u20139 record and did not make the playoffs.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=101}}\n\nBy the end of 1992, Kosar's physical decline had long been apparent to Belichick, which left the coach with a difficult choice.{{sfn|Holley|2011|pp=7\u20138}} Kosar was Cleveland's most popular athlete, a hometown boy who had forgone big money and a bigger profile to lead a struggling team back to the top.{{sfn|Holley|2011|pp=7\u20138}} While he recognized it would be an unpopular decision, Belichick wanted to bench Kosar, and in 1992 the team picked up a potential replacement in [[Vinny Testaverde]] from the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].{{sfn|Holley|2011|pp=8\u20139}} Belichick named Kosar the starter before the 1993 season,{{sfn|Holley|2011|p=13}} but in the third game against the Raiders, Belichick pulled Kosar after he threw his third interception of the night. Taking over with Los Angeles ahead 13\u20130, Testaverde led two touchdown drives to win the game. Two weeks later, Belichick named Testaverde the starter. On the verge of tears after a loss to the Dolphins, Kosar said he was disappointed with the decision and felt he had done what he could with what was at his disposal.<ref name=\"Testaverde named starter\">{{cite news|last=Cabot |first=Mary Kay |title=The Job is Testaverde's |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19931010BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UlYco7d?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19931010BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 28, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=October 10, 1993 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nKosar returned after Testaverde suffered a separated right shoulder in a win against the Steelers on October 24, but it was only temporary. The day after a loss against the Broncos the following week, the team cut him.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=101}} Belichick cited his declining skills, while Modell said it was the right move and asked fans to \"bear with us.\"<ref name=\"Kosar cut\">{{cite news|title=First-place Browns Cut Kosar|newspaper=Daily News, Bowling Green|date=November 9, 1993|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Fans brought out grills and set fire to their season tickets. A 20-year-old student at [[Baldwin\u2013Wallace College]] picketed outside the team's training facilities with a sign that read, \"Cut Belichick, Not Bernie.\"{{sfn|Holley|2011|p=13\u201314}} Cleveland won only two of the eight games after Kosar's release, finishing with a 7\u20139 record for the second year in a row.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=101}}\n\nCleveland managed to right the ship in 1994. While the quarterback situation had not stabilized, the defense led the league in fewest points allowed.<ref name=\"1994 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=1994 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1994.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UlcSpHc?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1994.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Browns finished 11\u20135, making the playoffs for the first time in five years. The Browns beat the Patriots in a wild-card game,<ref>{{cite news|last=Cabot |first=Mary Kay |title=One Playoff Down Browns 'Step Up' And Beat Patriots 20\u201313 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19950101BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UlftXA1?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19950101BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=January 1, 1995 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but arch-rival Pittsburgh won a 29\u20139 victory in the divisional playoff, ending the Browns' season.<ref name=\"Steelers beat Browns, 1994\">{{cite news|last=Cabot |first=Mary Kay |title=Simply The Pitts The Browns Get Whipped, Indisputably |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/19950107BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ulj9rpH?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F19950107BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=January 7, 1995 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Modell's Move to Baltimore===\n\n{{Main|Cleveland Browns relocation controversy}}\n\n[[File:Cleveland Municipal Stadium last game played in the stadium December 17, 1995.jpg|thumb|right|Browns owner Art Modell's 25-year lease of Cleveland Municipal Stadium planted the seed of financial troubles that culminated in his decision to relocate the team in 1995.]]\n\nAs the Browns recaptured a hint of past success in 1994, all was not well behind the scenes. Modell was in financial trouble. The origins of Modell's woes dated to 1973, when he worked out a deal to lease Cleveland Municipal Stadium from the city for a pittance: only enough to service the facility's debt and pay property taxes.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|p=137}} Cleveland Browns Stadium Corporation, or Stadium Corp., a company Modell and a business associate created and owned, held the 25-year lease. Stadium Corp. then subleased the stadium to the Browns and the [[Cleveland Indians]], and rented it out for concerts and other events.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|pp=137\u2013138}} While the deal worked fine for the city and Modell early on, the owner was later dogged by excessive borrowing and lawsuits.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|pp=137\u2013145}}\n\n[[File:1980-modell-browns crop.jpg|thumb|right|Cleveland owner Art Modell in 1983. Lawsuits by Browns minority owner Bob Gries and the Indians in the early 1980s exacerbated his financial problems.]]\n\nWhen the stadium was profitable, Modell had used Stadium Corp. to buy land in [[Strongsville, Ohio|Strongsville]] that he had previously acquired as the potential site for a future new stadium. Modell originally paid $625,000 for the land, but sold it to his own Stadium Corp. for more than $3 million. Then, when the stadium was taking losses in 1981, he sold Stadium Corp. itself to the Browns for $6 million. This led to a fight the following year with Bob Gries, whose family had been part of the Browns' ownership group since its founding and had 43% of the team to Modell's 53%. Gries's complaint was that Modell treated the Browns and Stadium Corp. as his own fiefdom, rarely consulting him about the team's business. The sale of Stadium Corp. to the Browns, he argued, enriched Modell at the team's expense.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|pp=139\u2013140}} Gries's case went to the [[Supreme Court of Ohio|Ohio Supreme Court]], where he won. In 1986, Modell had to reverse the Browns' purchase of Stadium Corp. and pay $1 million in Gries's legal fees. This left Modell in need of financial help, and it came in the form of [[Al Lerner]], a banking and real estate executive who bought half of Stadium Corp. and 5% of the Browns in 1986.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|p=139}}\n\nHis reputation damaged by the lawsuits, Modell was eager to get out of Cleveland. He met with Baltimore officials about selling the Browns to Lerner and buying an expansion team to replace the Colts, who had left for Indianapolis in 1984. He also discussed moving the Browns.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|p=143}} Proposals were made to spend $175 million on a stadium renovation after the Indians and [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] got new facilities in downtown Cleveland, but it was not enough.{{sfn|Morgan|1997|pp=143\u2013145}} As the Browns started the 1995 season with a 4\u20134 record, word leaked that Modell was moving the team.<ref name=\"NYT on Browns move\">{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Timothy W.|title=Baltimore Browns May Be a Done Deal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/04/sports/football-baltimore-browns-may-be-a-done-deal.html?src=pm|accessdate=May 31, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=November 4, 1995}}</ref> Beset by rising player salaries and political indifference to the team's financial plight, he said he was forced to move.<ref name=\"SI on Browns move\">{{cite journal|last=Munson |first=Lester |title=A Busted Play |journal=Sports Illustrated |date=December 4, 1995 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1007507/index.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UlqeldI?url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1007507/index.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 31, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The day after Modell formally announced the move, Cleveland voters overwhelmingly approved the $175 million of stadium renovations. Despite this, Modell ruled out a reversal of his decision, saying his relationship with Cleveland had been irrevocably severed. \"The bridge is down, burned, disappeared\", he said. \"There's not even a canoe there for me.\"<ref name=\"Modell bridges burned\">{{cite news|title=Modell: franchise movement is bad (but I'm still going)|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=November 8, 1995|agency=Associated Press|page=25}}</ref>\n\nThe city immediately sued to prevent the move, on the basis that the lease of the stadium was active until 1998. Fans were in an uproar, staging protests, signing petitions, filing lawsuits and appealing to other NFL owners to block the relocation. Advertisers pulled out of the stadium, fearing fans' ire.<ref name=\"NYT on Modell's move reaction\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=A City Fights To Save The Browns|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/12/sports/pro-football-a-city-fights-to-save-the-browns.html?ref=art_modell&pagewanted=all|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ulvzp8V?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/12/sports/pro-football-a-city-fights-to-save-the-browns.html?ref=art_modell&pagewanted=all|archivedate=June 17, 2012|accessdate=May 31, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 12, 1995|url-status=live}}</ref> Talks between the city, Modell and the NFL continued as the Browns finished the season with a 5\u201311 record. At the team's final home game against the Bengals, unruly fans in the Dawg Pound bleachers section rained debris, beer bottles and entire sections of seats onto the field, forcing officials to move play to the opposite end to ensure players' safety.{{sfn|Boyer|2006|p=131}} Cleveland won the game, its only victory after the announcement of the move.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=103}}\n\nThe following February, the warring parties reached a compromise. Under its terms, Modell would be allowed to take his personnel to Baltimore, but would leave Cleveland the Browns' colors, logos and heritage for a reactivated Browns franchise that would take the field no later than 1999.<ref name=\"Modell cleared to move\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir |first=Richard |title=N.F.L. Gives Modell a Ticket to Baltimore |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/10/sports/pro-football-nfl-gives-modell-a-ticket-to-baltimore.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Um048ay?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/10/sports/pro-football-nfl-gives-modell-a-ticket-to-baltimore.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |date=February 10, 1996 |work=The New York Times |url-status=dead }}</ref> The $175 million earmarked for stadium improvements was to be used instead build a new stadium, with up to $48 million of additional financial assistance from the NFL. Further, Modell was ordered to pay Cleveland $9.3 million to compensate for lost revenues and taxes during the Browns' three years of inactivity, plus up to $2.25 million of the city's legal fees. As a result of the deal Modell's team was technically an expansion franchise, called the [[Baltimore Ravens]].<ref name=\"Modell deal details\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=How Compromise Built Cleveland a New Stadium|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/12/sports/pro-football-how-compromise-built-cleveland-a-new-stadium.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=June 17, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Um3PzfT?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/12/sports/pro-football-how-compromise-built-cleveland-a-new-stadium.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|archivedate=June 17, 2012|date=February 12, 1996|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Inactivity (1996\u20131998)==\n\nPreparations for a reactivated franchise began shortly after Modell, the city and the NFL struck their compromise. The NFL established the Cleveland Browns Trust to direct the Browns' return in early 1996, and in June  appointed Bill Futterer as its president. Futterer, who had helped bring the [[Carolina Panthers]] and [[Charlotte Hornets]] expansion teams to [[North Carolina]], was charged with marketing the team, selling season tickets and representing the NFL's interests in the construction of a new stadium.<ref name=\"Futterer appointed\">{{cite news|title=Exec appointed for new Browns|newspaper=The Vindicator|date=June 28, 1996|agency=Associated Press|page=C3}}</ref> The trust also leased suites, sold [[personal seat license]]s in the new stadium and reorganized Browns Backers fan clubs.<ref name=\"NYT on Browns, 1998\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=The Price of Cleveland's Heart|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/02/sports/pro-football-the-price-of-cleveland-s-heart.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=16 June 2012|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Uor4H0s?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/02/sports/pro-football-the-price-of-cleveland-s-heart.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|archivedate=17 June 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 2, 1998|url-status=live}}</ref> By September 1996, architects were finalizing the design of a new stadium to be built following the destruction of Cleveland Municipal Stadium.<ref name=\"Stadium proposal\">{{cite news|title=Stadium proposed to be architecturally unique|newspaper=The Vindicator|date=September 9, 1996|agency=Associated Press|page=D1}}</ref> Demolition work began on the old stadium in November, and the ground-breaking for the new stadium took place the following May.<ref name=\"Stadium groundbreaking\">{{cite news|title=Ceremony kicks off project building phase|newspaper=The Vindicator|date=May 16, 1997|agency=Associated Press|page=C5}}</ref>\n\nAs the stadium's construction got underway, the NFL began to search for an owner for the team, which the league decided would be an expansion franchise March 23, 1998.<ref name=\"Browns to be expansion team\">{{cite news|title=Cleveland rejoices return of Browns|newspaper=Observer-Reporter|date=March 25, 1998|agency=Associated Press|page=C4}}</ref> A litany of potential owners lined up, including Kosar and a group backed partly by [[HBO]] founder Charles Dolan, comedian [[Bill Cosby]] and former Miami coach [[Don Shula]].<ref name=\"Cosby joins Dolans\">{{cite news|title=Cosby joins Dolans in attempt to acquire Browns|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=June 3, 1998|agency=Associated Press|page=33}}</ref><ref name=\"Shula joins ownership group\">{{cite news|last=Affleck|first=John|title=Shula joins Browns group|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=June 16, 1998|agency=Associated Press|page=C\u20136}}</ref> The ultimate winner was Al Lerner, the Baltimore man who had helped Modell in 1986 by buying a small stake in the Browns.<ref name=\"Owner list cut to four\">{{cite news|title=Owner list for Browns cut to four candidates|newspaper=Lawrence Journal-World|date=September 1, 1998|agency=Associated Press|page=6C}}</ref><ref name=\"Lerner wins Browns\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir |first=Richard |title=Lerner Wins Browns for $530 Million |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/09/sports/pro-football-lerner-wins-browns-for-530-million.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Up1RTEd?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/09/sports/pro-football-lerner-wins-browns-for-530-million.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=September 9, 1998 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A seven-member NFL expansion committee awarded the team to Lerner for $530 million in September 1998.<ref name=\"Lerner wins Browns\" /> Lerner, then 65 years old, had a majority share, while [[Carmen Policy]], who helped build the 49ers dynasty of the 1980s, owned 10% of the team and was to run football operations.<ref name=\"Lerner wins Browns\" />\n\n[[File:Browns Stadium-2.jpg|thumb|right|upright=2.0|[[FirstEnergy Stadium]], then known as Cleveland Browns Stadium, in 2006]]\n\nAs the Browns geared up to reactivate, the Browns Trust set up a countdown clock for the team's return<ref name=\"Browns to be expansion team\" /> and used Hall of Famers such as Lou Groza and Jim Brown extensively to promote the team, alongside celebrity fans including [[Drew Carey]].<ref name=\"Browns return rally\">{{cite news|last=Wray|first=Brandon|title=Cleveland holds Browns return rally|newspaper=The Bryan Times|date=August 21, 1998|agency=Associated Press|page=3}}</ref> Lerner and Policy hired [[Dwight Clark]], a former 49ers wide receiver, as the team's operations director in December 1998.<ref name=\"Clark hired\">{{cite news|title=Clark Takes Browns' Reins |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/01/sports/pro-football-clark-takes-browns-reins.html?src=pm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Up4hpyj?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/01/sports/pro-football-clark-takes-browns-reins.html?src=pm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=December 1, 1998 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The owners then signed [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] offensive coordinator [[Chris Palmer (American football)|Chris Palmer]] in January 1999 as the reactivated team's first head coach.<ref name=\"Palmer hired\">{{cite news|title=Browns to name Palmer as coach|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=January 21, 1999|agency=Associated Press|page=4C}}</ref> The NFL then conducted an [[1999 NFL Expansion Draft|expansion draft]] the following month to stock the new Browns team with players.<ref name=\"Expansion draft NYT\">{{cite news|last=Pennington |first=Bill |title=130 Veteran Faces For the Browns |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/16/sports/nfl-roundup-expansion-draft-130-veteran-faces-for-the-browns.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Up7uWCY?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/16/sports/nfl-roundup-expansion-draft-130-veteran-faces-for-the-browns.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=January 16, 1999 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The team added to its roster through free agency,<ref name=\"Free agency signings 1999\">{{cite news|title=Brown inks with Browns|newspaper=Kingman Daily Miner|date=March 4, 1999|agency=Associated Press|page=6}}</ref> and was also given the first pick in the [[1999 NFL Draft|draft]] in April 1999, which it used to draft quarterback [[Tim Couch]].<ref name=\"Couch chosen in 1999\">{{cite news|last=Freeman |first=Mike |title=Couch Gets Squeezed Before First Game |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/19/sports/on-pro-football-couch-gets-squeezed-before-first-game.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UpDK1Ye?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/19/sports/on-pro-football-couch-gets-squeezed-before-first-game.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=April 19, 1999 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nConstruction on the new stadium finished on time in August 1999, paving the way for Cleveland to host a football game for the first time in more than three years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypaper.com/columns/story.asp?id=8519 |title=Welcome to the Big Time |publisher=Citypaper.com |date=September 23, 1998 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UpGmCh7?url=http://www2.citypaper.com/columns/story.asp?id=8519 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=December 2, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During the years after Modell's move and the Browns' suspension, a dozen new stadiums were built for NFL teams. Citing the precedent set by the Browns' relocation, NFL owners used the threat of a move to convince their cities to build new stadiums with public funds.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Katherine C.|last=Leone|title=No Team, No Peace: Franchise Free Agency in the National Football League|journal=[[Columbia Law Review]]|volume=97|issue=2|pages=473\u2013523|year=1997|doi=10.2307/1123368}}</ref>\n\n==Rejoining the NFL (1999\u20132004)==\n\n[[File:Blimp Hall Fame.JPG|thumb|right|The Browns' first pre-season game following reactivation was played at the Pro Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio.]]\n\nCleveland fans' hopes were high upon the arrival of the new team. However, as an expansion team the Browns were forced to build a new roster from scratch using rookies, free agents, and the players other teams chose not to protect in the expansion draft.  With a new team composed of a mix of fresh faces and castoffs, the Browns floundered. The Steelers shut out the Browns 43\u20130 in the season opener at Cleveland Browns Stadium on September 12, 1999, the first of seven straight losses. A 2\u201314 season in 1999 was followed by a 3\u201313 record in 2000 after Couch suffered a season-ending thumb injury. Early in 2001, Policy and Lerner fired Palmer. The coach and the team, Policy said, were not headed in the right direction.<ref name=\"Palmer fired\">{{cite news|title=Palmer fired after 5\u201327 record at helm of Browns |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/news/2001/01/11/browns_palmer_ap/ |publisher=CNNSI.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Upoai9F?url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/news/2001/01/11/browns_palmer_ap/ |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Mike McCarthy (American football)|Mike McCarthy]], New Orleans' offensive coordinator, [[Herman Edwards]], a Tampa Bay assistant coach, and [[Marvin Lewis]], Baltimore's defensive coordinator, were mentioned as possible replacements for Palmer.<ref name=\"Palmer fired\" /> Policy also met with [[Butch Davis]], the head coach of the University of Miami's football team. After rejecting an initial offer in December, Davis accepted the job the following month. Davis had turned around Miami's football program and put the team back in championship contention; Policy and Lerner hoped he could do the same in Cleveland.<ref name=\"Davis hired\">{{cite news|last=Nobles |first=Charlie |title=Browns Hire Miami's Davis To Be Coach |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/01/30/sports/pro-football-browns-hire-miami-s-davis-to-be-coach.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Upqu4rY?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/01/30/sports/pro-football-browns-hire-miami-s-davis-to-be-coach.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=January 30, 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Butch Davis era: 2001\u20132004===\n\nThe Browns improved under Davis, and contended for a spot in the 2001 playoffs until a loss in the 15th week against Jacksonville that featured one of the most controversial calls in team history.<ref name=\"PD on bottlegate\">{{cite news|last=Grossi |first=Tony |title=They can't hold their beer Fans pelt field with bottles after reversal |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/20011216BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UptChpU?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F20011216BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 16, 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref> As time expired in the fourth quarter with the Jaguars ahead 15\u201310, Couch led a drive into Jacksonville territory. On a fourth-down play that the team needed to convert to stay in the game, Couch threw to receiver [[Quincy Morgan]] over the middle. Morgan appeared to bobble the ball before grasping it firmly as he hit the ground. After the pass was ruled complete and Couch spiked the ball to stop the clock, officials reversed Morgan's catch on a Jacksonville challenge. As Davis pleaded his case that the play could not be reviewed because another play had been run, frustrated fans began throwing plastic beer bottles onto the field. Amid the bedlam, later named \"[[bottlegate]]\", officials ended the game with 48 seconds on the clock and left the field as objects rained down on them from the stands.<ref name=\"PD on bottlegate\" /> After most of the fans had left, NFL commissioner [[Paul Tagliabue]] called and ordered the game to be completed. Jacksonville ran down the clock for the win, and the Browns finished the season at 7\u20139.<ref name=\"PD on final 2001 game\">{{cite news|last=Grossi |first=Tony |title=A hot finish to a cold day Offense, Couch steal show with 4th-quarter comeback |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/20011230BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UpwTmFn?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F20011230BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 30, 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCleveland improved again in 2002, but Lerner did not live to see his team make the playoffs. He died in October 2002 at 69 of brain cancer. Browns players wore a patch with the initials \"AL\" for the remainder of the season.<ref name=\"Lerner dies\">{{cite news|title=Browns owner Lerner dies at age of 69|newspaper=The Free Lance-Star|date=October 24, 2002|agency=Associated Press|page=B5}}</ref> Ownership of the team, meanwhile, passed to his son [[Randy Lerner|Randy]].<ref name=\"Randy Lerner takes over\">{{cite news|title=Lerner wasn't typical owner |url=http://cjonline.com/stories/102502/spo_lerner.shtml |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Upyk6F8?url=http://cjonline.com/stories/102502/spo_lerner.shtml |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Topeka Capital-Journal |date=October 25, 2002 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> Cleveland finished the season with a 9\u20137 record, earning a spot in the playoffs as a wild-card team.<ref name=\"Browns last 2002 game\">{{cite news|last=Grossi |first=Tony |title=Browns Stand Strong |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/20021229BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Uq0ps3c?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F20021229BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=December 29, 2002 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Couch suffered a broken leg in the final game of the season, however, and backup [[Kelly Holcomb]] started in the Browns' first playoff game versus the Steelers. Cleveland held the lead for most of the game as Holcomb passed for 429&nbsp;yards. But a defensive collapse helped Pittsburgh come charging back in the fourth quarter and win 36\u201333 to end the Browns' season.<ref name=\"Browns lose to Steelers, 2002\">{{cite news|last=Grossi |first=Tony |title=Bitter End For Browns |url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?/browns/more/history/20030106BROWNS.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Uq2gaI8?url=http://www.cleveland.com/brownshistory/plaindealer/index.ssf?%2Fbrowns%2Fmore%2Fhistory%2F20030106BROWNS.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=January 6, 2003 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  To date, this is the only postseason appearance for the Browns since resuming operations in 1999.\n\nThe team's progress under Davis screeched to a halt in 2003. The Browns finished 5\u201311, and Randy Lerner embarked upon a major front-office reshuffling.{{sfn|Henkel|2005|p=115}} Policy resigned unexpectedly as president and chief executive of the Browns in April 2004, saying things had changed after Al Lerner's death. \"I opened the door and it was like someone sucked the air and the life out of Berea\", he said. \"He was a major presence for the organization. I'm talking about the aura, and the inner power of the man.\"<ref name=\"Policy resigns\">{{cite news|title=Browns' Policy stepping aside|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=April 8, 2004|agency=Associated Press|page=C2}}</ref> [[John Collins (sports executive)|John Collins]] was named as his replacement.<ref name=\"Policy resigns\" /> Several other front-office executives also stepped down, including chief contract negotiator Lal Heneghan and lead spokesman Todd Stewart.<ref name=\"Front office firings 2004\">{{cite news|title=Browns fire lead spokesman|newspaper=The Beaufort Gazette|date=July 21, 2004|agency=Associated Press|page=1B}}</ref>\n\nThe 2004 season was little better, and Davis resigned in November with the team at 3\u20138. Lerner had given him a contract extension through 2007 that January, but Davis said \"intense pressure and scrutiny\" made the move necessary.<ref name=\"Davis resigns\">{{cite news|last=Withers |first=Tom |title=Butch Davis resigns as Browns coach |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2004-11-30-davis-resignation_x.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Uq5Wswz?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2004-11-30-davis-resignation_x.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |date=November 30, 2004 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> Offensive coordinator [[Terry Robiskie]] was named head coach for the remainder of the season, which the Browns finished 4\u201312.<ref name=\"Davis resigns\" />\n\n==Struggles and change (2005\u20132012)==\n\n===Savage/Crennel: 2005\u20132008===\n\n[[File:20080728 Braylon Edwards.jpg|thumb|right|Browns wide receiver Braylon Edwards made the Pro Bowl in the 2007 season, along with five other teammates.]]\n\nOn January 6, 2005, while the Browns were still searching for a new head coach, the team announced [[Phil Savage]]'s appointment as general manager.<ref name=\"Savage hired\">{{cite news|title=Browns get their man: Savage hired as GM |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2005-01-07-savage-gm_x.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UqwO1Sy?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2005-01-07-savage-gm_x.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |date=January 7, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Savage, who was director of player personnel for the Baltimore Ravens for two years, had a hand in drafting [[Ed Reed]], [[Jamal Lewis]], [[Ray Lewis]] and other stars for the Ravens.<ref name=\"Savage hired\" />\n\nA month later, Cleveland brought in [[Romeo Crennel]] as the head coach, signing him to a five-year deal worth $11 million. Crennel was the defensive coordinator for the New England Patriots, who had just won the Super Bowl.<ref name=\"Crennel hired\">{{cite news|authorlink=Nick Cafardo|last=Cafardo|first=Nick|title=In love with Romeo|newspaper=Ocala Star-Banner|date=February 9, 2005|page=5C}}</ref> His style was described as \"quiet, reserved and gentlemanly\", but he said he wanted to stock the team with tough, physical players.<ref name=\"Crennel hired\" /> Before the start of training camp, the Browns acquired veteran quarterback [[Trent Dilfer]] from the [[Seattle Seahawks]].<ref name=\"Dilfer trade\">{{cite news|title=Seattle trades Dilfer to Browns for fourth-round draft pick |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/seahawks/2002198274_webhawk05.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UqzmD5j?url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/seahawks/2002198274_webhawk05.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=Seattle Times |date=March 5, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the draft that year the Browns took wide receiver [[Braylon Edwards]] with the third pick in the first round.<ref name=\"Browns take Edwards\">{{cite news|title=Browns to rebuild with Edwards |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2005/football/nfl/specials/draft/2005/04/23/bc.fbn.draft.edwards.ap/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ur4kyVa?url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2005/football/nfl/specials/draft/2005/04/23/bc.fbn.draft.edwards.ap/ |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Sports Illustrated |date=April 23, 2005 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDilfer was the starting quarterback to begin the 2005 season. The team started 2\u20132, but had two three-game losing streaks later in the season and finished with a 6\u201310 record.<ref name=\"2005 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2005 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2005.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ur7F66N?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2005.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the team's final five games, rookie [[Charlie Frye]] took over as the starting quarterback, winning two of those contests. Before the Browns' final regular-season game, the front office was embroiled in a controversy that threatened to send the team into rebuilding mode. Citing sources, ESPN reported that president John Collins was going to fire general manager Phil Savage over \"philosophical differences\" in managing the salary cap.<ref name=\"Savage to be fired\">{{cite news|title=Sources: Browns ready to fire GM Savage |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2275447 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrFGWss?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2275447 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=December 30, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The resulting uproar from fans and local media was so strong that it was Collins who resigned on January 3, 2006.<ref name=\"Collins quits\">{{cite news|title=Browns' Collins quits job in power struggle|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=January 4, 2006|agency=Associated Press|page=C2}}</ref> A replacement for Collins was not immediately named, and Randy Lerner assumed his responsibilities.<ref name=\"Collins quits\" />\n\nCleveland regressed in the ensuing season, finishing with a 4\u201312 record. Edwards and tight end [[Kellen Winslow II|Kellen Winslow Jr.]], who the Browns had drafted in 2004, put up respectable numbers, but the Browns were close to the bottom of the league in points scored and offensive yards gained.<ref name=\"2006 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2006 Cleveland Browns Players & Statistics |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2006.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrQsd1d?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2006.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Frye injured his wrist toward the end of the season and shared starts with quarterback [[Derek Anderson (American football)|Derek Anderson]], who showed promise in the five games he played in.<ref name=\"Frye wrist injury\">{{cite news|title=Frye's wrist may be broken; Taylor, Maroney, Wilson top infirmed list |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2006-12-03-injury-roundup_x.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrTkg5s?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2006-12-03-injury-roundup_x.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |date=December 4, 2006 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> During the season, the team produced a series of articles on its website called ''60th Moments''. The series commemorated the establishment of the Browns 60 years before in 1946, recapturing the 60 greatest moments in franchise history. Beginning on September 6, 2006, the Browns' site ran articles covering those 60 moments; the final article ran on December 31, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|author=King, Steve|date=September 5, 2006|title=Moment 60 \u2013 A new era|url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/article.php?id=5606|work=ClevelandBrowns.com|publisher=Cleveland Browns|accessdate=September 9, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061021103223/http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/article.php?id=5606|archivedate=October 21, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=King, Steve|date=December 31, 2006|title=Moment 1: Dawson's strike|url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/article.php?id=6364|work=ClevelandBrowns.com|publisher=Cleveland Browns|accessdate=September 9, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012155946/http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/article.php?id=6364|archivedate=October 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\nAfter two losing seasons, the Browns made it back to contention in 2007. After opening with a 34\u20137 loss to the Steelers, the Browns traded Frye to the Seahawks and put Anderson in as the starter.<ref name=\"Frye dealt to Seahawks\">{{cite web|title=Browns deal quarterback Frye to Seahawks for draft pick |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3014233 |publisher=ESPN.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrWA83g?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3014233 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In his first start, Anderson led the Browns to a surprise 51\u201345 win over the Cincinnati Bengals, throwing five touchdown passes and tying the franchise record. More success followed, and the Browns finished the regular season with a 10\u20136 record, the team's best mark since finishing 11\u20135 in 1994.<ref name=\"2007 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2007 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2007.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrYi8v2?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2007.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> While the Browns tied with the Steelers for first place in the AFC North, the team missed the playoffs because of two tie-breaking losses to Pittsburgh earlier in the season. Still, six players were selected for the Pro Bowl, including Anderson, Winslow, Edwards, kick returner [[Josh Cribbs]] and rookie left tackle [[Joe Thomas (American football)|Joe Thomas]].<ref name=\"2007 Pro Bowl roster\">{{cite web|title=2007 NFL Pro Bowlers |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2007/probowl.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrbGSUJ?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2007/probowl.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Crennel agreed to a two-year contract extension until 2011,<ref name=\"Crennel contract extension\">{{cite news|last=Withers |first=Tom |title=Browns, Crennel agree on contract extension through 2011 |url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/sports/2008/01/29/browns29.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrdsqW4?url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/sports/2008/01/29/browns29.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=The Columbus Dispatch |date=January 9, 2008 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the team hired Mike Keenan as team president, filling a position left vacant upon the departure of Collins two years before.<ref name=\"Keenan hired\">{{cite news|title=Keenan appointed as Browns team president |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3408378 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrivLK8?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3408378 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=May 22, 2008 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nExpectations were high for the 2008 season, but Cleveland finished last in the AFC North with a 4\u201312 record.<ref name=\"2008 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2008 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2008.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrkmzGL?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2008.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Anderson shared starts with [[Ken Dorsey]], who the Browns had acquired by trading away Trent Dilfer, and [[Brady Quinn]], a young quarterback the team drafted in 2007.<ref name=\"Dorsey to Browns\">{{cite news|title=49ers trade Dorsey to Browns for Dilfer |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2006-05-05-dilfer-trade_x.htm?POE=SPOISVA |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UrpgUux?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2006-05-05-dilfer-trade_x.htm?POE=SPOISVA |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |date=May 5, 2006 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Quinn drafted\">{{cite news|last=Fine |first=Larry |title=Quinn gets wish to play for Browns |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/04/28/us-nfl-draft-quinn-idUSL2802480020070428 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ursg6kU?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/04/28/us-nfl-draft-quinn-idUSL2802480020070428 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=Reuters |date=April 28, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Browns never contended during 2008 and failed to score a touchdown in the final six games. Near the end of the season, two scandals shook the team. It was revealed that several Browns players, including Winslow, were suffering from [[Staphylococcal infection|staph infections]], which raised questions about sanitation in the Browns' Berea practice facilities.<ref name=\"Staph infection scandal\">{{cite news|last=Lubinger |first=Bill |title=Are staph infections plaguing the Browns? |url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2008/10/are_staph_infections_plaguing.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Urxw80z?url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2008/10/are_staph_infections_plaguing.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer |date=October 20, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In November, Savage found himself in the center of a media storm after an angry e-mail exchange with a fan was published on [[Deadspin]], a sports blog.<ref name=\"Savage Deadspin scandal\">{{cite web|last=Daulerio |first=A.J. |title=Browns' GM Phil Savage Responds To Email Hecklers Swiftly, But Not Very Politely |url=http://deadspin.com/5093632/browns-gm-phil-savage-responds-to-email-hecklers-swiftly-but-not-very-politely-update |publisher=Deadspin.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Us1Cb0L?url=http://deadspin.com/5093632/browns-gm-phil-savage-responds-to-email-hecklers-swiftly-but-not-very-politely-update |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Shortly after the final game, a 31\u20130 loss to the Steelers, Lerner fired Savage and, a day later, Crennel.<ref name=\"Crennel, Savage fired\">{{cite web|title=Crennel fired after Browns' 4-win season |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3797518 |publisher=ESPN.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Us3mPuj?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3797518 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Holmgren/Heckert: 2009\u20132011===\n\nCleveland pursued former Steelers coach and Browns linebacker [[Bill Cowher]] and former Browns scout Scott Pioli for the head coaching job.<ref name=\"Crennel, Savage fired\" /> The team, however, hired former New York Jets coach [[Eric Mangini]] in January 2009.<ref name=\"Mangini hired\">{{cite news|last=Cimini |first=Rich |title=Cleveland Browns hire ex-Jet Eric Mangini as their new head coach |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-01-07/sports/17914557_1_eric-mangini-belichick-coaching-tree-jets |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Us73lV6?url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-01-07/sports/17914557_1_eric-mangini-belichick-coaching-tree-jets |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=New York Daily News |date=January 7, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Before the start of the season, Mangini and the front office traded Winslow to the Buccaneers after five seasons marked by injuries and a motorcycle crash that threatened to end the tight end's career.<ref name=\"Winslow traded\">{{cite news|title=Winslow traded to Bucs for draft picks |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3939777 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Us9WBnE?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3939777 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=February 27, 2009 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Browns showed little sign of improvement in Mangini's first year, finishing 5\u201311 in 2009. While Cleveland lost 11 of its first 12 games, the team won the final four games of the season, including a 13\u20136 victory over the rival Steelers.<ref name=\"2009 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2009 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2009.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsCFgEh?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2009.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the season, Lerner hired former Packers coach [[Mike Holmgren]] as team president, moving Keenan to chief financial officer.<ref name=\"Holmgren hired\">{{cite news|title=Browns Say Holmgren Will Become Team President |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/22/sports/football/22nfl.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsEea8l?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/22/sports/football/22nfl.html?_r=2 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=December 21, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A month later, the owner hired Eagles front-office executive [[Tom Heckert, Jr.|Tom Heckert]] as general manager.<ref name=\"Heckert hired\">{{cite news|title=AP: Browns hiring Eagles' Tom Heckert as GM |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2010-01-10-tom-heckert-eagles_N.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsHqtzs?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/browns/2010-01-10-tom-heckert-eagles_N.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |date=January 12, 2010 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> Heckert replaced former general manager [[George Kokinis]], who was fired the previous November. The new management said Mangini would return for a second season.<ref name=\"Heckert hired\" />\n\nUnder Holmgren and Heckert's watch, the Browns overhauled the quarterbacking corps. Brady Quinn was traded to the Denver Broncos for running back [[Peyton Hillis]] in March,<ref name=\"Quinn trade\">{{cite news|title=Quinn sent to Broncos for Hillis, picks |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4995081 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsLHYEx?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4995081 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=March 15, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> while Derek Anderson was released.<ref name=\"Anderson released\">{{cite news|title=Browns release former Pro Bowl QB Derek Anderson |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/03/09/browns-release-qb-derek-anderson/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsNhJR4?url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/03/09/browns-release-qb-derek-anderson/ |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 17, 2012 |newspaper=Fox News |date=March 9, 2010 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> Meanwhile, [[Jake Delhomme]] was acquired from Carolina and Seneca Wallace from Seattle.<ref name=\"Delhomme signs\">{{cite news|last=Chandler |first=Charles |title=Delhomme signs with Browns |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/03/13/387855/delhomme-signs-with-browns.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsRFjwp?url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/03/13/387855/delhomme-signs-with-browns.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=Charlotte News-Observer |date=March 13, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The team also drafted quarterback [[Colt McCoy]] from the [[University of Texas]].<ref name=\"McCoy drafted\">{{cite news|last=Chadiha|first=Jeffri|title=McCoy, Mays among best draft bargains|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft10/columns/story?columnist=chadiha_jeffri&id=5132963|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsUPfrz?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft10/columns/story?columnist=chadiha_jeffri&id=5132963|archivedate=June 17, 2012|accessdate=June 16, 2012|newspaper=ESPN|date=April 24, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> With Delhomme as the starting quarterback, Cleveland lost its first three games and continued to struggle. Wallace started four games, but was replaced by McCoy in the second half of the season. Hillis had a breakout season, rushing for 1,177&nbsp;yards, and was later chosen to appear on the cover of the [[Madden NFL 12]] video game.<ref name=\"Hillis chosen Madden\">{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Craig |title=Voters pick Browns' Hillis for 'Madden NFL 12' cover |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-04-27/tech/hillis.madden.cover_1_madden-curse-michael-vick-madden-nfl?_s=PM:TECH |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsX5vrU?url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-04-27/tech/hillis.madden.cover_1_madden-curse-michael-vick-madden-nfl?_s=PM:TECH |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=CNN |date=April 27, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Despite the emergence of Hillis, the Browns finished with a 5\u201311 record for the second season in a row, and Mangini was fired in January 2011.<ref name=\"Mangini fired\">{{cite news|title=Mangini Fired by Browns After Second Straight 5\u201311 Season |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2011/01/03/mangini-fired-browns-second-straight-season/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsZZb6u?url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2011/01/03/mangini-fired-browns-second-straight-season/ |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=Fox News |date=January 3, 2011 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFollowing Mangini's firing, the Browns named [[Pat Shurmur]] as his replacement. Formerly the offensive coordinator for the [[St. Louis Rams]], Shurmur helped groom quarterback [[Sam Bradford]]. Holmgren and Heckert hoped he could do the same with McCoy.<ref name=\"Shurmur hired\">{{cite news|title=Browns hire Pat Shurmur as coach |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=6018483 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Usbtez9?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=6018483 |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=January 13, 2011 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref> Contract negotiations between the NFL Players Association and the league shortened the 2011 off-season, which gave Shurmur little time to coach McCoy or institute his version of the [[West Coast offense]].<ref name=\"Shurmur and McCoy\">{{cite news|last=Lankhof |first=Bill |title=Shurmur hopes to turn Browns around |url=https://lfpress.com/sports/football/2011/01/13/16880561.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsfcCqb?url=http://www.lfpress.com/sports/football/2011/01/13/16880561.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |newspaper=London Free Press |date=January 13, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The team started at 2\u20131, then 3\u20133, but McCoy's struggles and a lack of offensive production led to a series of defeats, including six straight losses to end the year. The Browns finished the season at 4\u201312.<ref name=\"2011 Browns stats\">{{cite web|title=2011 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2011.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UshkLK2?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/2011.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During that same season, comedian and frustrated Browns fan [[Mike Polk]] made a video to complain about the team's futility, screaming \"You are a factory of sadness!\" while facing [[Cleveland Browns Stadium]]. \"Factory of Sadness\" has since become a colloquial nickname for the stadium.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2011/11/cleveland_browns_fans_growing.html | title=Are Cleveland Browns fans at last growing weary of their NFL 'factory of sadness'? | publisher=Cleveland.com | work=The Plain Dealer | date=November 11, 2011 | accessdate=December 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the offseason, Hillis signed as a free agent with the Kansas City Chiefs after a lackluster season and unsuccessful contract talks with the Browns.<ref name=\"Hillis to KC\">{{cite news|last=Teicher |first=Adam |title=Hillis ready to help Chiefs however he can |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d827a1c9a/article/hillis-ready-for-fresh-start-with-chiefs-after-disappointing-year |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UsqF4NF?url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d827a1c9a/article/hillis-ready-for-fresh-start-with-chiefs-after-disappointing-year |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 17, 2012 |newspaper=NFL.com |date=May 3, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the [[2012 NFL Draft|2012 draft]], the Browns chose running back [[Trent Richardson]] with the third selection and took quarterback [[Brandon Weeden]] with the 22nd pick. Weeden was expected to replace McCoy at quarterback after McCoy's limited success in one and a half seasons as the starter.<ref name=\"Weeden expected to start\">{{cite news|title=GM expects Brandon Weeden to start |url=http://espn.go.com/dallas/nfl/story/_/id/7957477/cleveland-browns-gm-expecting-brandon-weeden-guy-season |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68UstzJXE?url=http://espn.go.com/dallas/nfl/story/_/id/7957477/cleveland-browns-gm-expecting-brandon-weeden-guy-season |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 2, 2012 |newspaper=ESPN |date=May 22, 2012 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn September 6, Art Modell died in Baltimore at the age of 87.<ref name=\"Modell AP obit\">{{cite news|last=Ginsburg|first=David|title=Former Ravens owner Art Modell dies at 87|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/former-ravens-owner-art-modell-112143255--nfl.html|accessdate=October 7, 2012|newspaper=Yahoo.com|date=September 6, 2012|agency=Associated Press|location=Baltimore}}</ref> Although the Browns planned to have a moment of silence on their home opener for their former owner, his family asked the team not to, well aware of the less-than-friendly reaction it was likely to get.<ref name=\"Browns cancel Modell silence\">{{cite news|last=Cabot|first=Mary Kay|title=Cleveland Browns cancel Art Modell recognition Sunday at request of Modell family|url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2012/09/cleveland_browns_cancel_their.html|accessdate=October 7, 2012|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 8, 2012}}</ref> Weeden started the Browns' first game of the season. The 28-year-old rookie threw four interceptions in a 17\u201316 loss to Philadelphia in which the Browns' only touchdown was scored by the defense.<ref name=\"Browns first game\">{{cite news|last=Withers|first=Tom|title=Eagles win season opener against Browns, 17\u201316|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wpvi/story?section=news/sports/pro/football&id=8803974|accessdate=October 7, 2012|newspaper=ABC 6 News|date=September 9, 2012|agency=Associated Press|location=Cleveland}}</ref>\n\n==Jimmy Haslam era (2012\u2013present)==\n[[File:Haslam 2012 Sports Awards (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|175px|Current Browns owner [[Jimmy Haslam]]]]\n[[File:Johnny Manziel training camp Browns 2014.jpg|right|thumb|175px|The Browns selected high-profile and controversial quarterback [[Johnny Manziel]] in the first round of the [[2014 NFL draft]] with much fanfare.<br />After two seasons of inconsistent play and numerous off-field incidents, Manziel was waived by the team on March 11, 2016]]\n\nIn July 2012, owner Randy Lerner announced he planned to sell the Browns to businessman [[Jimmy Haslam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d82ad9ba4/article/cleveland-browns-up-for-sale-mike-holmgren-confirms?module=HP11_breaking_news |title=Cleveland Browns up for sale, Mike Holmgren confirms |publisher=Nfl.com |date= |accessdate=June 2, 2013}}</ref> The sale was finalized on August 2, 2012, in excess of $1&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite web|first=Adam|last=Schefter |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/8225861/randy-lerner-sells-cleveland-browns-more-1b-sources-say |title=Randy Lerner sells Cleveland Browns for more than $1B, sources say |publisher=ESPN |date=August 2, 2012 |accessdate=September 3, 2012}}</ref> Haslam officially was approved as the new owner on October 16, 2012, at the NFL owners' meetings, and the very next day former Eagles president [[Joe Banner]] was named as the Browns' new CEO.\n\nThe Browns began the 2012 season by losing their first five games. Having lost their last six games to end the 2011 season, this marked an 11-game losing streak, tied for the longest in team history with the 1974\u20131975 teams.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130120023351/http://www.cleveland.com/ohio-sports-blog/index.ssf/2012/10/cleveland_browns_loseto_the_n_1.html]</ref> On October 12, the Browns defeated the Bengals 34\u201324 in Cleveland, behind two touchdown passes from rookie quarterback [[Brandon Weeden]] (on his 29th birthday) to end the streak. On December 31, 2012, head coach Pat Shurmur and general manager [[Tom Heckert, Jr.|Tom Heckert]] were fired. Shurmur went 9\u201323 in his two seasons as head coach.\n\n===Banner/Lombardi/Chudzinski: 2013===\nAfter interviewing numerous candidates such as [[Chip Kelly]] and [[Ken Whisenhunt]], the Browns decided to hire former offensive coordinator and tight ends coach, [[Rob Chudzinski]], on January 10, 2013.\n\nOn January 15, 2013, Haslam and Banner announced the naming rights to Cleveland Browns Stadium were sold to [[FirstEnergy]], and the stadium would be renamed FirstEnergy Stadium. The name change officially received [[Cleveland City Council]] approval on February 15, 2013.\n\nOn January 18, 2013, the Browns hired [[Michael Lombardi (sportscaster)|Michael Lombardi]] \u2013 who had a previous stint with the Browns in the player personnel department in the 1980s and 90s \u2013 as Vice President of Player Personnel (two months later he was officially given the title of general manager), making him Tom Heckert's replacement.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schudel|first=Jeff|url=http://morningjournal.com/articles/2013/03/06/sports/doc5136b61a5c34b767388986.txt |title=Cleveland Browns name Mike Lombardi General Manager, hire Ray Farmer as Assistant GM |publisher=morningjournal.com |date=March 6, 2013 |accessdate=June 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Browns would finish with a 4-12 record in the first season under the new regime, finishing last in the AFC North Division, and losing seven in a row to finish the 2013 campaign. Following the 2013 season finale on December 29, 2013, the Browns fired Chudzinski after only one year as head coach.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sessler|first=Marc|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000305869/article/rob-chudzinski-fired-by-cleveland-browns|title=Rob Chudzinski fired by Cleveland Browns|publisher=[[National Football League]]|date=December 29, 2013|accessdate=December 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Scheiner/Farmer/Pettine: 2014-2015===\nOn January 24, 2014, the Browns hired Bills defensive coordinator [[Mike Pettine]] as the 15th full-time head coach in team history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/10330448/cleveland-browns-tab-mike-pettine-head-coach |title=Cleveland Browns tab Mike Pettine as next coach - ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=January 24, 2014 |accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref> On February 11, 2014 the Browns announced that Lombardi would be replaced by [[Ray Farmer]] as general manager, and that Joe Banner would resign as CEO.<ref name=\"go\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/10435830/cleveland-browns-overhaul-front-office-name-ray-farmer-new-gm |title=Cleveland Browns overhaul front office, name Ray Farmer as new GM |publisher=espn.go.com|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref> In the first round of the [[2014 NFL draft]], the Browns selected [[cornerback]] [[Justin Gilbert]] from [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma State]] with the eighth pick, and Heisman Trophy-winning quarterback [[Johnny Manziel]]  of Texas A&M with the 22nd overall pick.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-nfl-draft-live-20140508-htmlstory.html|title=Browns 2014 draft picks|publisher=[[LA Times]]|accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in the 2014 season, the Browns use a live [[bullmastiff]] named \"Swagger\" as their new mascot.<ref name = \"Swagger\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000364960/article/browns-to-use-live-bullmastiff-swagger-as-mascot|title=Cleveland Browns to Use Live Bullmastiff as Mascot|publisher=[[NFL.com]]|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> On October 5, 2014, the Browns staged the largest rally in team history, when after trailing the [[Tennessee Titans]] 28-3 with 1:09 left in the second quarter, Cleveland scored 26 unanswered points to win the game 29-28. This was also the largest rally by a road team in NFL history.<ref name=\"go2\">{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=400554204 |title=Browns vs. Titans - Game Recap - October 5, 2014 - ESPN |publisher=scores.espn.go.com|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"twitter\">{{cite tweet|user=NFLhistory|author=NFL History|number=518871685668147200|date=5 October 2014|title=. @Browns' 25-point comeback today is largest in @NFL history by a road team|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref>  After a 7-4 start, the Browns would lose their final five games to finish the 2014 season at 7-9, last in the AFC North.\n\nIn February 2015, the team made headlines when two high-profile players were in the news due to substance abuse issues. On Monday February 2, it was announced quarterback [[Johnny Manziel]] had checked himself into a treatment center, reportedly for alcoholism. The following day, wide receiver [[Josh Gordon]] was suspended for the 2015 season due to failing a drug test.<ref name=\"espncleveland\">{{cite web|url=http://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=41941 |title=It's time for Browns GM Ray Farmer to face the music and answer some tough questions |publisher=espncleveland.com |accessdate=September 29, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930155325/https://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=41941 |archivedate=September 30, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> On February 28, it was revealed that former [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] quarterback [[Josh McCown]] had signed a three-year deal with the Browns. On March 30, the NFL announced that Browns general manager [[Ray Farmer]] would be suspended for the first four regular season games, and that the team would be fined $250,000 (U.S.) for Farmer text messaging the coaching staff during games in the 2014 season, which is against NFL rules. The story had been dubbed \"Textgate\" due to its scandalous nature.<ref name=\"espncleveland2\">{{cite web|url=http://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=43681 |title=The penalties on the Browns and GM Ray Farmer run deeper than a fine and suspension |publisher=espncleveland.com |accessdate=September 29, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930125814/https://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=43681 |archivedate=September 30, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn April 14 at a ceremony at the [[Huntington Convention Center of Cleveland]], the team unveiled their new uniforms. They feature brown, white, and orange jerseys along with brown, white, and orange pants that can be worn in any combination. Unique features include the word \"Cleveland\" across the front of the jersey, the word \"Browns\" going down the pant leg, and the words \"Dawg Pound\" on the inside collar - all first of their kind features on NFL uniforms. Browns President [[Alec Scheiner]] compared these new jerseys to those of the [[Oregon Ducks football]] team, as the Ducks are known for their various uniform combinations.<ref name=\"espncleveland3\">{{cite web|url=http://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=44131 |title=Browns two-year uniform makeover returns attention now to the team and quarterback |publisher=espncleveland.com |accessdate=September 29, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930130329/https://espncleveland.com/common/more.php?m=49&action=blog&r=17&post_id=44131 |archivedate=September 30, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2015 NFL draft]], the Browns had two first round picks, selecting [[nose tackle]] [[Danny Shelton]] from [[Washington Huskies football|Washington]] at #12, and [[offensive lineman]] [[Cameron Erving]] from [[Florida State]] at #19.\n\nOn September 8, 2015, the Browns announced that they indefinitely suspended offensive line coach [[Andy Moeller]] after an alleged domestic assault incident at his home during Labor Day weekend. This meant that at the beginning of the 2015 regular season, the team had a player ([[Josh Gordon]]), a coach ([[Moeller]]), and a front office executive ([[Ray Farmer]]) all suspended for various league and legal infractions.<ref name=\"irontontribune\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irontontribune.com/2015/09/08/browns-suspend-moeller |title=Browns suspend Moeller &#124; The Tribune |publisher=irontontribune.com|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref>  Moeller would subsequently be fired on September 29.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsnet5.com/sports/browns/cleveland-browns-and-offensive-line-coach-andy-moeller-agree-to-part-ways|title=Cleveland Browns and offensive line coach Andy Moeller agree to 'part ways'|first=Tim|last=Rearden|date=September 30, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001044214/http://www.newsnet5.com/sports/browns/cleveland-browns-and-offensive-line-coach-andy-moeller-agree-to-part-ways|archivedate=October 1, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter starting 2-3, the Browns lost 10 of their last 11 games to finish the 2015 season at 3-13. This stretch included a 33-27 home loss to the Baltimore Ravens in which Ravens safety Will Hill return a blocked field goal 64 yards for a touchdown on the game's final play. The Browns lost at home 37-3 to the division-rival Cincinnati Bengals the following week, dropping the team\u00b4s record to 2-10 and making them the first team in the 2015 season to be mathematically eliminated from playoff contention. On January 3, 2016, soon after the final game of the season (a 28-12 loss to the Pittsburgh Steelers), both Ray Farmer and Mike Pettine were fired from their respective positions as general manager and head coach.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rosenthal|first=Gregg|title=Cleveland Browns fire Mike Pettine, GM Ray Farmer|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000614532/article/cleveland-browns-fire-general-manager-ray-farmer|publisher=National Football League|date=January 3, 2016|accessdate=January 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Brown/DePodesta/Jackson/Dorsey: 2016-2018===\n [[File:Hue Jackson Browns Mini Camp.png|right|thumb|175px|Former head coach [[Hue Jackson]] won only three out of 40 games with the Browns and posted an 0\u201316 record in 2017]]\nIn January 2016, the Browns made headlines when after firing Farmer and Pettine, promoted general counsel [[Sashi Brown]] to executive vice president of football operations, and hired longtime baseball executive [[Paul DePodesta]] as [[chief strategy officer]]. These moves were viewed nationally as the Browns trying to take a more analytics intensive approach to building the team, taking a page from the \"[[Moneyball]]\" style of [[Major League Baseball]] teams like the [[Oakland Athletics]] - of which DePodesta helped pioneer during his time as an assistant to Athletics general manager [[Billy Beane]]. With Brown essentially taking over general manager duties, this marks the fourth different head of personnel (either as general manager or similar job title) under the Haslam ownership era, which began in 2012.<ref name=\"BrownsHireDePodesta\">{{cite web|title=Paul DePodesta named Browns Chief Strategy Officer|url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-5/Paul-DePodesta-named-Browns-Chief-Strategy-Officer/fffdcf77-786a-441c-ba4d-a715669be515|publisher=Cleveland Browns|date=January 5, 2016|accessdate=January 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109195438/http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-5/Paul-DePodesta-named-Browns-Chief-Strategy-Officer/fffdcf77-786a-441c-ba4d-a715669be515|archive-date=January 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/cleveland-browns/post/_/id/17513/paul-depodesta-takes-browns-from-draft-day-to-moneyball|title=Paul DePodesta takes Browns from 'Draft Day' to 'Moneyball'|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 2016, the Browns hired Bengals offensive coordinator (and former Oakland head coach) [[Hue Jackson]] as head coach - making him the eighth full-time head coach since the team's return in 1999 and fourth since 2012, when the Haslam ownership era began.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cabot|first1=Mary Kay|title=Hue Jackson hired as Cleveland Browns' 8th head coach since 1999|url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2016/01/hue_jackson_named_cleveland_br.html#incart_big-photo|accessdate=January 13, 2016|agency=Cleveland.com|publisher=The Plain Dealer|date=January 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, the Browns hired Andrew Berry\u2014a longtime scout with the [[Indianapolis Colts]]\u2013as vice president of personnel. Berry, being a [[Harvard]] alumnus like DePodesta and Sashi Brown, has been noted as furthering the Browns new analytic approach, and the trio has been dubbed as the \"Harvard Connection\" (and other similar monikers) by local and national media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waitingfornextyear.com/2016/02/wfny-roundtable-cleveland-browns-staff/|title=WFNY Roundtable: Meet the Browns staff|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/cleveland-browns-sashi-brown-paul-depodesta-andrew-berry-harvard-front-office-012816|title=Harvard triumvirate now running the show in Cleveland - FOX Sports|date=January 28, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> On March 4, team president Alex Scheiner announced he would be stepping down from his post effective March 31, and would remain with the team as a consultant for the rest of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14902886/alex-scheiner-resigns-cleveland-browns-president-effective-march-31|title=Browns president Scheiner resigns from post|publisher=}}</ref>  With this move, Paul DePodesta essentially became the top ranked executive of the team in his role as Chief Strategy Officer.<ref name = \"PDP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2016/01/05/cleveland-browns-new-york-mets-paul-depodesta-hired|title=Browns hire Paul DePodesta as executive VP|first=SI|last=Wire|publisher=}}</ref>  This makes DePodesta the fourth different top executive of the team under the Haslams' ownership. On March 11, following two seasons of inconsistent play on the field and numerous highly publicized incidents off the field, the Browns waived quarterback Johnny Manziel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14933932/johnny-manziel-waived-cleveland-browns-tumultuous-two-years|title=Browns part ways with Manziel after two seasons|publisher=}}</ref> On March 24, the Browns signed quarterback [[Robert Griffin III]] to a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/15058201/cleveland-browns-sign-robert-griffin-iii|title=Browns sign RG III as latest quarterback project|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nGoing into the [[2016 NFL Draft]], the Browns had the #2 overall pick.  They traded that pick to Philadelphia in exchange for the #8 pick in the first round (along with various later round 2016 picks, and Philadelphia's first round pick in 2017).  On draft night they traded the #8 pick to Tennessee in exchange for the #15 pick in the first round (and later round picks). With the #15 pick in the 2016 draft, the Browns selected wide receiver [[Corey Coleman]] from [[Baylor University|Baylor]].\n\nThe 2016 season began with the Browns losing their first 14 games, which combined with losing their last three games in 2015, gave the team a franchise record 17 game losing streak.  On December 24, in a game that has since been dubbed \"The Christmas Miracle\", the Browns defeated the [[San Diego Chargers]] 20-17.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsnet5.com/sports/browns/a-christmas-miracle-browns-get-first-win-of-the-season-beat-chargers-20-17|title=A Christmas miracle: Browns get first win of the season, beat Chargers 20-17|first=Tom|last=Withers|date=December 24, 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cleveland.cbslocal.com/2016/12/24/browns-hang-on-to-beat-chargers-20-17/|title=A Christmas Miracle: Browns Hang On To Beat Chargers 20-17|first=Daryl |last=Ruiter|publisher=}}</ref> The Browns then lost their last game of the season to finish 1-15 - then the worst record in team history. With that final game loss, the Browns clinched the #1 pick in the [[2017 NFL Draft]], with which the Browns selected [[Myles Garrett]], a [[defensive end]] from [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]].\n\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = vertical\n   | width     = 175\n   | footer    = Hue Jackson's first two seasons, while historically atrocious, netted the Browns two consecutive first overall picks: [[Myles Garrett]] (top) and [[Baker Mayfield]] (bottom)\n   | image1    = Myles_Garrett_2018.jpg\n   | alt1      = \n   | caption1  = \n   | image2    = Baker_Mayfield_training_camp_2018_(2)_(cropped).jpg\n   | alt2      = \n   | caption2  = \n}}\n\nIn the midst of a disappointing 2017 season, Brown was fired as executive vice president of football operations on December 7, 2017,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2017/12/browns_sashi_brown_has_been_fi.html#incart_2box|title=Browns' Sashi Brown has been fired and Hue Jackson will remain as head coach|last1=Cabot|first1=Mary Kay|date=December 7, 2017|publisher=Cleveland.com}}</ref> and hired [[John Dorsey (American football)|John Dorsey]] as general manager the same day, making him the ninth general manager/head of personnel since the Browns' return in 1999, and the fifth in the Haslam ownership era.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-5/Browns-name-John-Dorsey-General-Manager/afd38a04-201f-4f9f-bfb8-88f6aa9f320c|title=Browns name John Dorsey General Manager|date=December 7, 2017|publisher=ClevelandBrowns.com|access-date=May 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208105235/http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-5/Browns-name-John-Dorsey-General-Manager/afd38a04-201f-4f9f-bfb8-88f6aa9f320c|archive-date=December 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/executives.htm Cleveland Browns executives - Pro Football Reference]</ref> The Browns finished the 2017 season with an 0\u201316 record, becoming only the second team in league history to do so,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/amp/news/cleveland-browns-become-second-winless-team-nfl-history/|title=Cleveland Browns become second team in NFL history to go 0-16|accessdate=1 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> and for the second straight season giving the team the #1 pick in the [[2018 NFL Draft]] (along with the #4 pick, which was previously acquired via trade from Houston). Despite the winless season and a 1-31 record as head coach of the Browns, Hue Jackson was retained by Haslam.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theringer.com/nfl/2018/1/1/16837862/browns-retain-hue-jackson|title=The Browns Are Retaining the Least Successful Coach in NFL History|date=January 1, 2018|publisher=The Ringer}}</ref> With the first overall pick, the Browns selected former [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]] quarterback and 2017 Heisman Trophy winner [[Baker Mayfield]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2018/04/browns_draft_baker_mayfield_no.html|title=Browns draft Baker Mayfield No. 1 overall in 2018 NFL draft|date=April 27, 2018|publisher=Cleveland.com}}</ref>\n\nDespite Mayfield's status as the #1 overall pick, the Browns began the [[2018 NFL season]] with veteran [[Tyrod Taylor]] as the starting quarterback.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/tyrod-taylor-starter-browns-baker-mayfields-strong-debut/story?id=57147161|title=Tyrod Taylor still starter for Browns, despite Baker Mayfield's strong debut|date=August 12, 2018|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> On opening day, the Browns tied the [[2018 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] 21\u201321 after neither team scored in overtime, ending the Browns' losing streak at 17 games, but extending their winless streak to 18 games. Two weeks later, on September 20, Mayfield entered the game near the end of the first half after Taylor left with a concussion and led the Browns to a 21\u201317 comeback victory over the [[2018 New York Jets season|New York Jets]]  at FirstEnergy Stadium. The victory was the Browns' first since week 16 of the 2016 season, ending their winless streak at 19 games, which was the 4th-longest in NFL history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/20/sports/cleveland-browns-win.html|title=Baker Mayfield Ends Cleveland Browns\u2019 635-Day Winless Streak|date=September 20, 2018|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> Four days later, Jackson announced Mayfield as the Browns' starter for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24783519/baker-mayfield-named-starter-cleveland-browns|title=Baker Mayfield gets starting QB nod for Week 4|date=September 24, 2018|publisher=ESPN.com}}</ref> On October 7, 2018, the Browns defeated the [[2018 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] 12\u20139 in overtime to end an 18-game winless streak against divisional opponents dating back to 2015. After a Week 8 loss to the Pittsburgh Steelers that dropped the Browns to a 2-5-1 record, Hue Jackson was fired as head coach along with offensive coordinator Todd Haley.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000980394/article/browns-fire-hue-jackson-promote-gregg-williams|title=Browns fire Hue Jackson, promote Gregg Williams|date=October 29, 2018|publisher=NFL.com}}</ref> Jackson's final record of 3-36-1 as the Browns' head coach is the worst of any coach's with a single franchise in NFL history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2018/11/1/18048338/hue-jackson-cleveland-browns-coach-tenure-review|title=Review: Hue Jackson\u2019s astoundingly bad tenure with the Browns will never be topped|date=November 1, 2018|publisher=SB Nation}}</ref> Defensive coordinator Gregg Williams was named interim head coach and running backs coach [[Freddie Kitchens]] was named interim offensive coordinator. Their 35\u201320 win over the [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]] at [[Paul Brown Stadium]] on November 25 was the Browns' first win away from home since 2014 and broke a 25-game road losing streak that ranks second all-time in NFL history. Three weeks later, the Browns defeated the [[2018 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] 17\u201316 at [[Broncos Stadium at Mile High]], their first win over Denver since 1990. Following the coaching changes the Browns won five of their remaining eight games to finish the season 7\u20138\u20131, one win shy of having their first winning season since 2007. Mayfield enjoyed a successful rookie season, throwing for 3,725 yards and 27 touchdowns (an NFL record for a rookie quarterback) despite starting only 13 games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001006054/article/baker-mayfield-breaks-rookie-passing-td-record|title=Baker Mayfield breaks rookie passing TD record|date=December 30, 2018|publisher=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===Dorsey/Kitchens: 2019===\n\nOn January 9, 2019, owner Jimmy Haslam and general manager John Dorsey named interim offensive coordinator Freddie Kitchens the 17th head coach of the Cleveland Browns, due in part to the offense's rapid improvement and Baker Mayfield's growth under Kitchens in the second half of the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2019/01/browns-will-name-freddie-kitchens-head-coach-today-per-report.html|title=Freddie Kitchens hired as Cleveland Browns head coach|date=January 9, 2019|publisher=Cleveland.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2019, the Browns acquired Pro Bowl wide receiver [[Odell Beckham Jr.]] and pass rusher [[Olivier Vernon]] in two separate trades with the New York Giants in exchange for offensive guard [[Kevin Zeitler]], safety [[Jabrill Peppers]], and two draft picks, including the Browns' 2019 first-round pick.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/03/08/olivier-vernon-kevin-zeitler-trade-giants-browns|title=Giants Trade Odell Beckham Jr. and Olivier Vernon to Browns|date=March 13, 2019|publisher=Sports Illustrated}}</ref> The trade is widely considered one of the most significant and bizarre in NFL history: the Giants traded Beckham (26 years old on the day of the trade) despite his status as one of the best wide receivers in the NFL only one year after signing him to the largest contract for a wide receiver in NFL history at the time.<ref>\n{{cite news|url=https://www.cleveland.com/sports/2019/03/cleveland-browns-odell-beckham-trade-strange-comments-from-giants-ownership-terry-pluto.html|title=Cleveland Browns: Odell Beckham trade & strange comments from Giants ownership|date=March 31, 2019|publisher=Cleveland.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fancy-stats/wp/2016/11/06/odell-beckham-jr-could-become-the-nfls-best-wide-receiver-ever/|title=Odell Beckham Jr. could become the NFL\u2019s best wide receiver ever|date=November 6, 2016|publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/28/odell-beckham-jr-signs-record-breaking-95-million-deal-with-new-york-giants.html|title=Odell Beckham Jr. signs record-breaking $95 million deal with New York Giants|date=August 28, 2018|publisher=CNBC}}</ref> The move instantly raised expectations for the Browns, with many declaring them a Super Bowl contender despite their recent history and [[List of NFL franchise post-season droughts|16-year playoff drought]], the longest active streak in the NFL.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2825356-the-browns-finally-are-super-bowl-contenders-after-landing-odell-beckham-jr|title=The Browns Finally Are Super Bowl Contenders After Landing Odell Beckham Jr.|date=March 12, 2019|publisher=Bleacher Report}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|2019]] season would be a disaster for the Browns as they finished with a record of 6\u201310. With that record, combined with many numerous discipline problems from both on and off the field plus poor play, the Cleveland Browns fired Freddie Kitchens hours after the Browns' loss to the Cincinnati Bengals on December 29. Two days later, the Browns also parted ways with general manager John Dorsey after disagreements with discussions about structural reformations of the team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001093675/article/browns-part-ways-with-general-manager-john-dorsey|title=Browns part ways with general manager John Dorsey|date=December 31, 2019|publisher=NFL.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28400906/john-dorsey-browns-general-manager|title=John Dorsey out as Browns general manager|date=December 31, 2019|publisher=espn.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|American football|Sports}}\n* [[List of Cleveland Browns seasons]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bowden|first=Mark|year=2008|title=The Best Game Ever: Giants vs. Colts, 1958, and the Birth of the Modern NFL|publisher=Atlantic Monthly Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-87113-988-7|ref={{sfnRef|Bowden|2008}}|url=https://archive.org/details/bestgameevergian00bowd}}\n* {{cite book|last=Boyer|first=Mary Schmitt|year=2006|title=Browns Essential|publisher=Triumph Books|location=Chicago|isbn=978-1-57243-873-6|ref={{sfnRef|Boyer|2006}}|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/brownsessentiale0000boye}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cantor|first=George|year=2008|title=Paul Brown: The Man Who Invented Modern Football|publisher=Triumph Books|location=Chicago|isbn=978-1-57243-725-8|ref={{sfnRef|Cantor|2008}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Coughlin|first=Dan|year=2011|title=Pass the Nuts: More Stories About the Most Unusual People and Remarkable Events from My Four Decades As a Sports Journalist|isbn=978-1-59851-073-7|ref={{sfnRef|Coughlin|2011}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Dyer|first=Bob|year=2007|title=The Top 20 Moments in Cleveland Sports: Tremendous Tales of Heroes and Heartbreaks|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-59851-030-0|ref={{sfnRef|Dyer|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Felser|first=Larry|year=2008|title=The Birth of the New NFL: How the 1966 NFL/AFL Merger Transformed Pro Football|publisher=Lyons Press|location=Guilford, Connecticut|isbn=1-59921-151-3|ref={{sfnRef|Felser|2008}}|url=https://archive.org/details/birthofnewnflhow00fels}}\n* {{cite book|last=Felton|first=Bruce|year=2007|title=What Were They Thinking?, New and Revised: Really Bad Ideas Throughout History|publisher=The Lyons Press|location=Guilford, Connecticut|isbn=1-59921-132-7|ref={{sfnRef|Cantor|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Freeman|first=Mike|year=2007|title=Jim Brown: The Fierce Life of an American Hero|publisher=It Books|location=New York|isbn=0-06-077683-8|ref={{sfnRef|Freeman|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Gordon|first=Roger|year=2002|title=Cleveland Browns A-Z|publisher=Sports Publishing LLC|location=Champaign, Illinois|isbn=978-1-58261-240-9 |ref={{sfnRef|Gordon|2002}} }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Gregg|first1=Forrest|authorlink1=Forrest Gregg|last2=O'Toole|first2=Andrew|year=2009|title=Winning in the Trenches: A Lifetime of Football|publisher=Clerisy Press|location=Covington, Kentucky|isbn=1-57860-363-3|ref={{sfnRef|Gregg|2009}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Grossi|first=Tony|year=2004|title=Tales From the Browns Sideline|publisher=Sports Publishing LLC|location=Champaign, Illinois|isbn=978-1-58261-713-8 |ref={{sfnRef|Grossi|2004}} }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Groza|first1=Lou|authorlink1=Lou Groza|last2=Hodermarsky|first2=Mark|year=2003|title=The Toe: The Lou Groza Story|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-886228-80-1|ref={{sfnRef|Groza|2003}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|year=2007|title=Browns Scrapbook: A Fond Look Back at Five Decades of Football, from a Legendary Cleveland Sportswriter|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-59851-043-0|ref={{sfnRef|Heaton|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Henkel|first=Frank M.|year=2005|title=Cleveland Browns History|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=Mount Pleasant, South Carolina|isbn=978-0-7385-3428-2 |ref={{sfnRef|Henkel|2005}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Hollander|first=Zander|year=1983|title=Strange But True Football Stories|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=978-0-394-80198-8|ref={{sfnRef|Hollander|1983}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Holley|first=Michael|year=2011|title=War Room: The Legacy of Bill Belichick and the Art of Building the Perfect Team|publisher=It Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0-06-208239-8|ref={{sfnRef|Holley|2011}}|url=https://archive.org/details/warroomlegacyofb00holl_0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Knight|first=Jonathan|year=2003|title=Kardiac Kids: The Story of the 1980 Cleveland Browns|publisher=Kent State University Press|location=Kent, Ohio|isbn=0-87338-761-9|ref={{sfnRef|Knight|2003}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Knight|first=Jonathan|year=2006|title=Sundays in the Pound: The Heroics and Heartbreak of the 1985\u201389 Cleveland Browns|publisher=Kent State University Press|location=Kent, Ohio|isbn=978-0-87338-866-5|ref={{sfnRef|Knight|2006}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Lebovitz|first=Hal|authorlink=Hal Lebovitz|year=2006|title=The Best of Hal Lebovitz: Great Sportswriting from Six Decades in Cleveland|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-59851-023-2|ref={{sfnRef|Lebovitz|2006}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Maraniss|first=David|year=2000|title=When Pride Still Mattered : A Life Of Vince Lombardi|url=https://archive.org/details/whenpridestillma00mara|url-access=registration|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=978-0-684-87018-2|ref={{sfnRef|Maraniss|2000}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Maxymuk|first=John|year=2007|title=Strong Arm Tactics: A Historical and Statistical Analysis of the Professional Quarterback|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|isbn=978-0-7864-3277-6|ref={{sfnRef|Maxymuk|2007}}|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786432776}}\n* {{cite book|last=Miller|first=Jeff|year=2004|title=Going Long : The Wild Ten Year Saga of the Renegade American Football League in the Words of Those Who Lived It|publisher=McGraw-Hill|location=New York|isbn=978-0-07-144154-4|ref={{sfnRef|Miller|2004}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Miller|first=Jeffrey|year=2007|title=Rockin' the Rockpile: The Buffalo Bills of the American Football League|publisher=ECW Press|location=Toronto|isbn=978-1-55022-797-0|ref={{sfnRef|Miller|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Morgan|first=Jon|year=1997|title=Glory for Sale: Fans, Dollars and the New NFL|publisher=Bancroft Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-0-9631246-5-4|ref={{sfnRef|Morgan|1997}} }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Neft|first1=David S.|last2=Cohen|first2=Richard M.|last3=Korch|first3=Rick|year=1994|title=The Football Encyclopedia: The Complete History of Professional Football from 1892 to the Present|publisher=St. Martin's Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-312-11435-0|ref={{sfnRef|Neft|1994}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Page|first=Joseph S.|year=2010|title=Pro Football Championships Before the Super Bowl: A Year-by-Year History, 1926\u20131965 |publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|isbn=978-0-7864-4809-8|ref={{sfnRef|Page|2010}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Peterson|first=Robert W.|year=1997|title=Pigskin: The Early Years of Pro Football|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-511913-8|ref={{sfnRef|Peterson|1997}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Piascik|first=Andy|year=2007|title=The Best Show in Football: The 1946\u20131955 Cleveland Browns|publisher=Taylor Trade Publishing|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=978-1-58979-571-6|ref={{sfnRef|Piascik|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Pluto|first=Terry|authorlink=Terry Pluto|year=1997|title=Browns Town 1964: Cleveland Browns and the 1964 Championship|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-886228-72-6|ref={{sfnRef|Pluto|1997}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Pluto|first=Terry|year=2010|title=Things I've Learned from Watching the Browns|publisher=Gray & Company|location=Cleveland|isbn=978-1-59851-065-2|ref={{sfnRef|Pluto|2010}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Schwarz|first=Ted|year=2010|title=Shocking Stories of the Cleveland Mob|publisher=The History Press|location=Charleston, South Carolina|isbn=978-1-59629-918-4|ref={{sfnRef|Schwarz|2010}} }